<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--China-Thief     04-24 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--China-Thief,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Stole From American Consulate To Be Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Shanghai man has been sentenced to die for
stealing money and goods from the U.S. consulate in his home city,
an official newspaper reported today.
   The Shanghai Intermediate People's Court on Saturday handed down
the death sentence to Zhang Ping for stealing 33,000 yuan ($8,900)
from the consulate, the China Daily said.
   Zhang broke into the consulate in China's largest city an
unspecified number of times between December 1986 and February
1988, it said.
   Zhang, also accused of stealing goods in other areas around
Shanghai, was arrested last May and confessed to his crimes, the
daily said. He had previously served a three-year prison term for
theft.
   Chinese courts generally hand down stiff sentences for any crime
against foreigners. The government has also called on courts to
deal harshly with criminals in the face of a nationwide rise in
crime.
   Shanghai courts handled 2,801 theft cases last year, up 22.5
percent over 1987, sentencing 12 convicted thiefs to death and 13
to life in prison.
</TEXT>
