<FIRST>r i PM-Nepal-India Bjt   04-24 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nepal-India, Bjt,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mountain Kingdom Suffers For Standing Up To Its Neighbor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BINAYA GURUACHARYA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When tiny Nepal stood up to its giant
neighbor India in a treaty dispute, India imposed a trade blockade
that has caused shortages of fuel, salt, medicines and other
essentials in the mountain kingdom.
   The trouble started last month when Nepal rebuffed India by
refusing to accept a treaty encompassing both trade and transit
rights.
   Nepal wanted to renew two separate treaties _ one for trade and
the other for transit, or passage through the country _ that
expired March 23.
   Being a landlocked nation, Nepal insists that transit is a
constant necessity and wants it treated separately on a long-term
basis rather than linked in a trade pact with changing conditions.
   India's halt on trade with its Himalayan neighbor has created
hardships for many of Nepal's 17 million people.
   Dipak Silwal, a schoolteacher, called India's move ``the
unfriendly act of a friendly country.''
   ``They have stopped export of even salt. India wanted to deprive
Nepalese of even that pinch of salt essential for human
consumption,'' he said.
   Kamal Tuladhar, the owner of a pharmacy, said, ``We are unable
to meet the demands of people who need regular medicines to treat
diabetes, heart diseases or blood pressure.''
   Before the blockade Nepal imported more than $150,000 worth of
medicines from India each month.
   Nepal is bordered on three sides by India and shares its
northern frontier with China's Tibet region. That geography has led
Nepal to conduct most of its business with India and handle
virtually all other foreign trade through the Indian port of
Calcutta.
   When the treaties lapsed, India closed 13 of the 15 crossing
points along the border with Nepal and stopped exports.
   If India wins the argument and Nepal agrees on one treaty
covering both trade and transit that would give give India a
stronger bargaining position in any future disputes.
   Both India and Nepal are predominantly Hindu and have had a
special relationship for decades. But China has been wooing Nepal
and India has watched with concern China's growing influence on the
buffer state.
   Indian-Nepalese relations were hurt earlier this year when Nepal
bought artillery from China. Nepal also offered China and other
nations trade terms that India considered better than the offers it
had received.
   Silwal expressed confidence the Nepalese could cope with the
situation while the stalemate continues: ``We can survive with them
(the Indian goods) or without them and most things, though
rationed, are available in the markets.'' People in Katmandu now
use kerosene to cook because gas, imported from India, is not
available. But some people say the weekly ration of about three
quarts of kerosene per family is insufficient.
   Truckloads of logs for fuel are being hauled into the capital
from the southern plains and that is causing a problem.
   The sharp rise in logging and ``thoughtless destruction of
forest will adversely effect the environment,'' said K.P. Sigdel,
the head of Nepal's Forum of Environment Communicators.
   Nepal has bought petroleum products from Singapore, Saudi Arabia
and other countries but shipments are held up at the Indian border
and the government rationed gasoline.
   ``I get 15 liters (about 4 gallons) of gasoline per week, but
this is hardly enough for a day,'' said taxi driver Laxmi
Manandhar. ``I have to garage my car most of the time.''
   An Indian news agency reported that smugglers who once supplied
luxury goods to the Nepalese ``are now doing a booming business in
items like salt, kerosene, gasoline and diesel fuel.''
   ``About 500 couriers are operating along the border and
delivering their wares to remote areas,'' said United News of India.
</TEXT>
