<DOCNO> AP890424-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-100Days-BushStaff Bjt   04-24 0879</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-100 Days-Bush Staff, Bjt,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>An Activist Bush Keeps Aides On Toes, Republicans Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is showing little inclination
to delegate a lot of authority to subordinates, even though he
surrounded himself with strong personalities in the Cabinet and in
his inner circle of top-level White House advisers.
   Bush has said he wants his Cabinet members to speak out, to say
what they think. So he did not directly second-guess Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh when asked last week what he thought about
Thornburgh's idea to test public housing tenants for drug use.
   ``We've got a good Cabinet system, and I encourage people to
speak out,'' the president said. ``But the decisions on something
of that nature will be made right here ... and they're not going to
be made until I have all the facts.''
   How Bush goes about the job of fact-finding as he nears
decisions on key issues says much about the style of his presidency
_ and the relative strength of his staff.
   Despite the presence of some key presidential advisers from past
administrations, such as national security adviser Brent Scowcroft
and budget director Richard Darman, Bush's staff, in relative
terms, is less influential than many of its predecessors.
   Administration sources and Republican Party officials privy to
how things work in the White House inner sanctum said in interviews
that Bush is a much more activist, hands-on type of president. He
gets immersed in the kind of internal policy debates that his
predecessor, Ronald Reagan, sought to avoid, these observers said.
   Reagan's aides frequently depicted him as a passive player in
the Cabinet, sub-Cabinet and staff-level discussions of policy
options, saying he chose to stay away from the arguments and await
the recommendations of his aides.
   Typifying the contrasting Bush style was a call that one
presidential adviser got at home on a Saturday night. Bush wanted
to find out what had been done about a matter they discussed
earlier in the week, and he didn't want to wait until Monday, said
the aide, who asked not to be identified.
   When the White House press corps was told at the last moment
recently that Bush had canceled a planned four-day weekend trip to
his seaside resort home in Kennebunkport, Maine, press secretary
Marlin Fitzwater explained that the president had decided he simply
didn't want to go there after all.
   Interviews with a host of knowledgeable Republicans inside and
outside the administration produced a consensus on the most
powerful of the Bush aides. Not surprisingly, Scowcroft, Darman and
chief of staff John Sununu topped the list. Secretary of State
James A. Baker III, predictably, continues to wield heavy influence.
   ``The proximity question has a lot to do with your influence,''
said Tom Korologos, a consultant who was close to the Reagan White
House and has ties to the new administration as well. ``A guy can
walk up to him in the hallway and say, `Hey, how do you feel about
this?''' he said. ``That might be considered bad government, but
that's the way it works.''
   An administration official, speaking anonymously, said that in
the Bush White House, compared to Reagan's, ``it's a much more
difficult role for the staff ... because they never know just where
they stand. They never have absolute authority to do something
because Bush interjects himself so much.''
   ``In the Reagan administration, you could feel pretty safe to
act, at least on what things to recommend, if you had a pretty good
line on the Reagan philosophy,'' he said. ``But with Bush, it (the
issue under debate) could turn around at any moment.''
   Gary Bauer, who was a domestic policy adviser to Reagan and who
now runs a private family research center, said that Reagan ``used
to like for us to thoroughly discuss and air these issues without
him. And if there was a consensus, bring it to him for sign-off. If
there wasn't, to go and debate it in front of him.''
   ``My sense is that President Bush wants to be involved as much
as he can in an issue and I think that just requires the staff to
operate differently,'' Bauer said, adding:
   ``When I was there, one sometimes got frustrated that you didn't
have more presidential involvement early on. But on the other hand,
it really gave you a chance to assert yourself and to influence
policy. ... Maybe they (the Bush staff) wish they had a little more
flexibility to act before the president gets into it.''
   Former White House political adviser Mitchell Daniels said that
while Bush has a strong first team of advisers like Sununu, Darman
and Scowcroft, he believes the lower-level aides perform
essentially as functionaries.
   The administration official said the staff is ``less powerful''
under Bush than under Reagan because Bush is ``more engaged and is
deciding more of the issues. Bush is less predictable than Reagan.
He's a sort of compromiser and do-what's-right kind of person.''
   Korologos said that while Reagan ran the White House like a
chairman of the board of a business, Bush operates much in the
fashion of a corporate chief executive officer.
   ``George Bush knows this government. He doesn't have to learn
the initials and the acronyms,'' Korologos said.
</TEXT>
