<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Labor'sProfile     04-24 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Labor's Profile,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Keeping A High Profile, Seeking To Gain From Recent Good Will</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lane Kirkland sees the ``sanctification of
greed'' he attributes to the Reagan years beginning to crumble,
bringing favorable winds to the sails of the movement he often
refers to as a ship.
   ``I think there is perhaps the beginning of some change in
climate,'' the AFL-CIO president said in an interview last week.
``We've been beating against some fairly strong winds, but I think
the ship is sound and seaworthy. And winds change.''
   His is a view cautiously shared by other labor leaders, who in
recent weeks have found themselves awash with good news, a rare
tiding in a decade the American labor movement would prefer to
forget.
   Few labor leaders expect a sudden turnaround of the decline of
the 1980s, during which membership in unions has dropped by 3
million to 17 million and the percentage of workers who are union
members dropped from 23 percent in 1980 to 16.8 percent last year.
   But many believe the passing of the Reagan administration and
labor's recent high profile may help unions halt their slide and
improve their public standing.
   ``I think the American people are listening to what we are
saying and, yes, I think things are progressing,'' United Auto
Workers President Owen Bieber said.
   But Kirkland cautions against reading too much into recent
developments.
   ``We of course swim in a sea of public opinion that helps us and
hurts us and is valuable but I do not think that we can rely upon
external trends or perceptions or fortunes to build the labor
movement,'' he said. ``Our strength comes from within.''
   Still, it's hard not to notice labor's presence these days.
   Eastern Airlines has been virtually grounded for two months by a
Machinists strike that in itself has buoyed the labor movement
because of overwhelming solidarity among traditionally fractious
airline unions. A Harris poll released last week found that 60
percent of respondents supported the strikers.
   The labor-backed effort to raise the minimum wage has become the
first domestic policy showdown between Congress and President Bush,
with polls showing public opinion squarely behind efforts to end
the nine-year freeze in the floor wage.
   Unions are feeling better at the bargaining table as well.
   Two unions representing more than a half-million
telecommunications workers at AT&amp;T and regional telephone companies
are engaged in the largest round of collective bargaining this
year, national steel-industry contract talks are under way and
labor last week won a National Labor Relations Board ruling
expected to help unions organize the growing health care work force.
   Also, the Teamsters recently settled a racketeering suit with
the government, bringing fresh negative reports about alleged mob
influence on the union but promises for reform as well. The
settlement averted what would have been a lengthy trial likely to
tarnish labor's image regardless of its outcome.
   There is more to come.
   The minimum wage is just the first priority on a lengthy labor
agenda that also includes proposals for parental leave, child care,
health care, curbs on mergers and buyouts and worker-safety issues.
Most of these are ``safe'' issues _ those with public support.
   On tap for April 28 is a nationwide ``Workers Memorial Day''
during which unions will stage events in 17 states and the District
of Columbia to highlight workplace hazards.
   And labor's considerable political war chest will be directed in
the next two years on state races _ for governorships and
legislative seats _ in hopes of gaining powerful influence on the
redistricting that will follow the 1990 Census.
   The labor movement even is picking up its belated efforts to
join the TV age, seeking to foster good will with ad campaigns,
including a new Auto Workers series questioning the long-term
effects of mergers and moving jobs overseas.
   The ads make a pitch for patriotism and recount America's
industrial heydays.
   ``We wanted to show that what we're really concerned about is
not just our own well-being but the well-being of our country,''
said Bieber.
   In addition, the AFL-CIO is reviving its ``Union Yes''
television campaign this month, spots in which a handful of
entertainers promote union membership.
   Whether the high profile will result in substantive gains for
labor is anybody's guess.
   But Kirkland has no illusions of trouble-free days ahead,
regardless of whether labor gains from its recent prominence.
   ``Ups and downs have happened all throughout our history and
will in the future, I'm sure,'' he said. ``We've learned to live
with that.''
</TEXT>
