<FIRST>r w PM-AmericaFirst     04-24 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-America First,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto Workers Take To TV To Tackle `Merger-Mania'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Labor's Profile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's auto workers are taking on Wall
Street and corporate power brokers with a new advertising campaign
attacking ``merger-mania'' and movement of jobs oversees.
   There's another obvious but unstated goal as well: to foster
good will toward unions.
   ``American Business Should Put America's Future First'' is the
title of the $4 million campaign begun this month by the United
Auto Workers in an effort to sway public opinion in favor of
labor-backed efforts to curb mergers and acquisitions.
   The campaign comes at a time when the labor movement has an
unusually high profile because of a number of recent events,
including the Eastern Airlines strike and labor-backed efforts to
raise the minimum wage.
   But there's no mention of the word ``union'' in the text of the
TV ads, although labor's ``Union Yes'' logo appears on the final
frame.
   Instead, the UAW makes a pitch to patriotism, with newsreel
footage of products manufactured in the United States in the past
40 years as well as shots of auto workers on an assembly line.
   ``Producing quality products has always been one of our nation's
great strengths,'' the narrator says in one ad as viewers get a
glimpse of 1950s clock radios, televisions and refrigerators. ``Our
auto industry put this country on wheels. American pioneered the
electronic age. Our computer technology brought us a whole new
world of information.''
   The picture then shifts to a frantic floor session on Wall
Street as the narrator continues:
   ``But in the '80s, some of the best-known products of American
business have been takeovers, junk bonds and making money by moving
money. Let's turn it around. We need to put America's future
first.''
   In the second spot two UAW engine assemblers talk of quality
products and good-paying jobs before the camera turns to UAW
President Owen Bieber.
   ``But some corporations are putting short-term profits ahead of
long-term strength,'' Bieber says. ``Moving jobs overseas, mergers
and takeovers that are unproductive. They don't help build America.
Investing and training in top-notch facilities: that's good for all
of us.''
   A related print ad campaign features corporate executives
surrounding a craps table and betting company assets.
   The TV spots are running in two dozen markets, primarily where
UAW workers are concentrated but also in Washington, New York,
Chicago and Los Angeles and nationally on several cable channels.
   The print ads are to run in a variety of newspapers, magazines
and business journals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
