<FIRST>r a PM-Utility-Crash Bjt   04-24 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Utility-Crash, Bjt,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Crash, Dead Canaries Expand Grand Jury Probe Into Southern
Co.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of an executive in a plane crash and
the discovery of dead canaries at a lawyer's home have added a
strange twist to a federal tax-fraud investigation of Southern Co.,
a big Southeast utility.
   A grand jury is investigating allegations that Gulf Power Co., a
Southern subsidiary, forced suppliers to make campaign
contributions to a variety of Florida politicians.
   The utility allegedly reimbursed the suppliers and covered the
payments with inflated or bogus invoices, according to recent
published reports that quoted grand jury witnesses.
   The investigation began after an accountant for Georgia Power
Co., another Southern subsidiary, told the Internal Revenue Service
last year that the utility may have accounted improperly for spare
parts. The Securities and Exchange Commission also is investigating.
   Now, the grand jury has widened its inquiry to include the April
10 plane crash that killed three.
   Among the victims was Jake Horton, a Gulf Power executive who
had just been told by his employers that he might be disciplined
for accounting irregularities. Investigators haven't determined the
cause of the crash, but one witness said the grand jury asked him
about the possibility of sabotage or suicide.
   ``Any allegations that what we're doing was related to the air
crash we would certainly be concerned with,'' said U.S. Attorney
Robert L. Barr Jr., whose office is conducting the investigation in
Atlanta.
   Barr also indicated there may be ties between the grand jury
probe and the discovery of dead canaries at the homes and office of
Fred Levin, a Pensacola, Fla., lawyer who has worked for Gulf Power.
   Levin had met with Horton recently. The executive believed he
had been targeted for indictment and told Levin he wanted to clear
his name, according to Levin.
   Barr wouldn't say whether the grand jury had been investigating
Horton before the crash.
   Atlanta-based Southern Co. brings electricity to 11 million
customers through five subsidiaries in four Southeast states. Its
revenues last year were $2.1 billion.
   Horton was senior vice president of Pensacola-based Gulf Power.
He and two company pilots were killed when the plane crashed into a
Pensacola apartment complex 90 seconds after taking off for Atlanta.
   Allan R. Barton, president of Mississippi Power Co., another
Southern subsidiary, said the grand jury asked him last week if
sabotage or suicide could have been involved. Barton said he didn't
have any clues.
   The National Transportation Safety Board said flight tapes show
that a fire broke out in the cockpit before the crash, but no cause
has been established.
   ``We have not uncovered anything that would indicate any type of
sabotage so far,'' said NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz.
Nevertheless, the FBI is checking for any sign of criminal intent,
he said.
   Shortly before boarding the plane, Horton had met with Gulf
Power President Doug McCrary and Dr. Reed Bell, chairman of its
audit committee.
   The meeting was held to discuss ``concern over Mr. Horton's
possible circumvention of company policies and procedures and his
supervision of processing of invoices from vendors,'' Southern Co.
said in a statement.
   The audit committee recommended Horton be fired or suspended,
but no action was taken at the meeting, the company said.
   Last week, canaries with broken necks turned up outside the
office and two homes of Levin.
   ``I don't know what else I've done to deserve a dead canary,''
Levin told Atlanta's WSB-TV. ``I am deeply, deeply concerned, and I
don't even stay at home now.''
   Carter Haynes, a Gulf Power spokesman, said Levin's firm had
represented the utility for about five years in personal injury
cases. Haynes said he could recall no recent case that might have
inspired someone to leave a dead canary as a warning to Levin.
   Authorities haven't established a motive and have no suspect on
the canaries, said Ray Barnes, special operations supervisor at the
Escambia County, Fla., sheriff's office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
