<FIRST>r i PM-China-Disasters     04-24 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Disasters,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Natural Disasters Kill 7,300 in China Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoons, earthquakes, drought and other natural
disasters killed 7,300 people and caused $27 billion in damage in
China last year, an official newspaper reported today.
   Civil Affairs Minister Cui Naifu said 1988 was China's worst for
natural disasters in the past decade, the China Daily said.
   Cui said the death toll was up 34 percent over 1987, while the
number of injured, 70,000, was an increase of 75 percent. About 230
million people, more than a fifth of China's population, were
affected by disasters, he said.
   More than 600 people died in floods that swamped large areas of
southern and northeastern China, Cui said.
   There were 25 earthquakes measuring 5 or more on the Richter
scale, with the most damaging, in southwest China's Yunnan Province
last November, killing 730 people and injuring 4,000.
   The most devastating of numerous typhoons to strike the
southeastern coast killed 120 in Zhejiang province in August.
   Cui said drought affected 813 million acres of farmland
throughout the country, and that 378 million acres produced no
crops because of dry weather.
</TEXT>
