<FIRST>r a PM-DelayedDream     04-24 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Delayed Dream,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fame May Be Coming to 1950s Rock Star _ 30 Years Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dreams have finally started coming true for
Joe Clay, the school bus driver who was rediscovered three years
ago by European teen-agers craving '50s rock 'n' roll.
   Eight European concert tours later, Clay _ also known as C.J.
Cheramie to his neighbors and the students and teachers on his bus
routes _ is looking at the possibility of a movie of his life and
maybe a book.
   A one-year option on his life story was bought recently by Fries
Entertainment in Los Angeles.
   ``This is the same production people that did `La Bamba' and
`Officer and a Gentleman.' It's kind of getting a little exciting
now,'' Cheramie said. ``This is the best thing that ever happened
so far.''
   Cheramie, 51, started singing at 40 years ago, and had a brief
career singing rock 'n' roll. In 1957, he recorded nine songs,
appeared on the ``Ed Sullivan Show'' and performed with Elvis
Presely at the Louisiana Hayride in Shreveport.
   He went to New York but grew frustrated with a career that
wasn't moving and a manager who wouldn't give it a push.
   He came home, worked in a band, and 15 years ago began driving
the bus.
   Then, in 1986, an English music promoter found him at his modest
two-story house in a New Orleans suburb, and sent him on a concert
tour to England, Holland and Sweden. It was a trip to success such
as Clay had never known.
   ``It's hard to come home and explain what happens to me over
there,'' he said. ``I really become Joe Clay. I really stay on the
clouds. I'm on a natural high.''
   He recently resigned from his bus-driving job because finding a
substitute while he was on tour had become a problem.
   He's been to Europe twice this year and will release a record
with two new songs next month. In September, he will return to tour
and to make an album in Holland. In December, there's another tour.
   Two weeks ago, the Country Music Association released on record,
tape and compact disc a collection of vintage 1956-1959 rockabilly
music, including Cheramie doing his first nine songs.
   News of the possible movie came a few weeks ago, although the
project is not definite.
   Cheramie said he doesn't regret having missed the gold three
decades ago.
   ``It's so much better now. I don't think I could have handled it
then,'' he said.
</TEXT>
