<FIRST>r a PM-WinerySlayings     04-24 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winery Slayings,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivor Of Father's Rampage Turns 3 Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PETALUMA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The little girl who survived her
father's confessed killing spree was marking her third birthday
today with greetings and 500 toys sent from around the country to
the hospital where she is recovering.
   Petaluma Valley Hospital planned a quiet celebration with cake
and ice cream for Carmina Salcido, her relatives and staff members
who have cared for the girl since she was found with her throat
slit at a trash dump.
   Carmina has received numerous birthday cards and presents,
including the toys and clothes, said spokeswoman Mary Frost.
   Her father, Ramon Salcido, 28, remained in the Sonoma County
jail under a 24-hour suicide watch, and awaiting a May 5 hearing to
enter a plea to seven counts of murder.
   Salcido is accused of killing his wife, Angela, a co-worker, his
mother-in-law and her two young daughters, and his two other
daughters, Sofia, 4, and Teresa, 1. He confessed to the crimes
after his arrest in Mexico, authorities said.
   Most of the victims were found April 14 but Salcido's daughters
were found the next day at the dump.
   Carmina's condition continued to improve after another operation
Friday, when surgeons removed a feeding tube and inspected her
wound for infection. Hospital spokeswoman Fran Adams said the girl
was in good condition on Sunday.
   Carmina and her two sisters may not have been the last victims
of the killing spree, as initially believed.
   The Santa Rosa Press Democrat, citing unidentified law
enforcement sources, said Sunday investigators now believe the
three girls were actually the first victims in the April 14 rampage.
   Sheriff's sources told the newspaper that it now appears the
girls had their throats slashed about 6 a.m. at the dump, before
Salcido allegedly tossed them over an embankment one at a time.
   If the new account is accurate, Carmina was at the dump for more
than 30 hours before she was found.
   Salcido is then believed to have driven to Cotati to kill his
mother-in-law and her two daughters, returned to his home in Boyes
Hot Springs to kill his wife, and then to Grand Cru Winery, where
he allegedly fatally shot his co-worker, Tracy Toovey, the
newspaper reported.
   The killing spree ended a few minutes later when Salcido
allegedly shot and wounded another co-worker, Kenneth Butti, and
tried to shoot Butti's wife, Terri, according to the newspaper's
sources.
   Salcido reportedly provided details to investigators while he
was being brought back from Mexico late last week.
</TEXT>
