<FIRST>r a PM-TribalDispute Bjt   04-24 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tribal Dispute, Bjt,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Against BIA Agent Spark Conflict Over Tribal Authority</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dateline Rocky Boy and reservation Rocky Boys, cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKY BOY, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a century after frontier
Indian wars ceased on the plains and valleys of Montana, native
Americans are embroiled in a new battle for independence against
the federal government.
   On the Rocky Boys Indian Reservation in north-central Montana, a
tribal prosecutor has filed criminal charges against the chief
agent of the Bureau of Indian Affairs, accusing him of interfering
in tribal affairs by threatening not to recognize an elected tribal
government.
   The case has implications nationwide for Indian tribes' power to
control their own governments and reservations.
   ``My whole idea in this thing was, `How much authority does this
guy have?''' said Chippewa-Cree Tribal Prosecutor Jim Morsette.
``This is a problem not only in Rocky Boy, but on all the
reservations.''
   The federal government responded by suing Morsette, a tribal
councilman and the chief tribal judge in federal court.
   The government acknowledges Indian reservations are sovereign
territory, but it claims tribal courts have no jurisdiction over
BIA personnel performing official duties.
   U.S. District Judge Paul Hatfield of Great Falls should decide
the issue later this year.
   Most tribes have their own constitutions and laws, approved by
the federal government.
   Yet many tribal programs on reservations _ law enforcement,
schools, road maintenance, welfare _ are operated under contract
with the BIA, which provides the money and acts as overseer. The
agency also has the power to revoke contracts and run programs
itself.
   ``When it's not operating the way it's supposed to, we step in
and take over,'' said Richard Whitesell, the bureau's area director
in Billings.
   On poorer reservations like Rocky Boys, where unemployment runs
at about 75 percent among 2,400 resident tribal members, federal
money is the main source of employment and income and the bureau's
authority carries clout.
   Despite the bureau's often pervasive role in tribal affairs, its
stated goal is to help the tribes become more independent. Morsette
and his allies say that isn't happening on the Rocky Boys
Reservation.
   Their complaints center on Rocky Boys BIA Superintendent Ken
Davis.
   On Jan. 9, Morsette charged Davis in tribal court with three
misdemeanors: obstructing justice, cruelty to animals and contempt
of court.
   Davis refused to appear in court, saying it had no jurisdiction
over him as a bureau employee. Chief Tribal Judge Russell Standing
Rock issued an arrest warrant, but a federal judge agreed to a
government request and blocked the charges until the jurisdictional
question is settled.
   The contempt-of-court charge is the most significant. It accuses
Davis of interfering with a tribal court order involving alleged
voting fraud in a June 1988 tribal election.
   Davis told a tribal election official the bureau might not
recognize the tribal government elected under the court order,
according to court records. Without the bureau's recognition, a
tribe could lose its contracts.
   Morsette said Davis' comments were improper and illegal and
portrayed an outdated, paternalistic attitude toward Indians.
   ``It's the attitude that the BIA has always had: `We know what's
best for you. ... You're still our Indians,''' Morsette said.
``Well, (our) constitution is for us to interpret, in our court.''
   Davis and government attorneys maintain he was merely performing
his job as adviser to the tribe and is therefore immune from legal
action by the tribe.
   ``He said, `There are some problems I see. I recognize your
authority to resolve them, but you need to get them resolved,'''
said Roger W. Thomas, an Interior Department attorney.
   The pursuit of criminal charges in tribal court against a BIA
superintendent appears unique, but the government argues that the
matter is a civil case. Federal courts have ruled in previous civil
cases that tribal courts have no jurisdiction over federal
employees acting in official capacity.
   Morsette and Standing Rock are paying their legal fees without
support from the tribal council. They say it will be tough to win
against the government and all its resources, but add that the case
is too important to drop because of its implications for tribal
independence.
   ``I'm kind of bullheaded this way, but I have always stressed to
my people ... that we're the boss _ the Indians, the tribe,'' said
Standing Rock. ``We tell the BIA what to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Arafat-France     04-24 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arafat-France,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Chairman To Make First Official Visit To France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat will make his first
official visit to France early in May, meeting with President
Francois Mitterrand and other government officials, Foreign
Minister Roland Dumas announced.
   News reports have said the Palestine Liberation Organization
leader's visit has been set for May 2, but Dumas said only that it
would come in the month's ``early days.''
   Interviewed on French television on Sunday, Dumas said France
remains ``a close friend of Israel,'' which has criticized the
planned visit. French Jewish groups also have protested the
invitation, which was announced previously without any date being
set.
   ``France takes into account Israel's concerns, but also the
reality of the Palestinian people,'' Dumas said.
   He said the actions of the Palestine National Council last
November in Algiers and statements by Arafat in Geneva accepting
the right of Israel to exist and renouncing terrorism made the
visit possible.
   Dumas noted that Arafat already has made official visits to
Greece, Spain and Italy and has been received by Pope John Paul II.
   Dumas and other French foreign ministers have met with Arafat on
several occasions, but never before in Paris.
   After Arafat's statements in Geneva, the United States dropped
its ban on all contacts with the PLO.
   Since then representatives of the group in Tunis, Tunisia, where
the PLO is headquartered, have met several times with U.S.
Ambassador Robert Pelletreau.
