<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SteinbeckHotel     04-24 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinbeck Hotel,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Where Steinbeck Lounged To Be Demolished</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALINAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city is planning to demolish the
Hotel Cominos, where a young John Steinbeck caroused. He later
wrote about the hotel in ``The Long Valley,'' ``Dubious Battle''
and ``East of Eden.''
   The gray cast-stone and stucco hotel _ with its grand ballroom,
marble fireplace, hardwood floors and frosted glass chandeliers
with gold leaf trim _ was a center of activity when Steinbeck's
hometown had a population of 4,000.
   Today, the hotel stands abandoned and rubble-filled and
officials in this city of 100,000 residents say they have more
important thing to spend money on.
   They decided earlier this month to tear it down soon.
   ``Steinbeck used to go down to the hotel,'' recalled Betty
Brusa, who briefly met him when she was a girl in the 1920s. ``He
belonged to what was called the `rat pack.' They broke up the lobby
one night throwing things at one another.''
   Steinbeck, born in Salinas in 1902, moved away to college and
went on to win a Nobel Prize for literature in 1962, six years
before his death. He was in town long enough to see what opened as
the Abbott House in 1874 transformed into the Cominos.
   The hotel declined in the 1950s and began a steep slide in the
1960s. It closed in the early 1980s and now belongs to the city.
   ``This is the most significant landmark in town,'' said Gary
Breschini, an archaeologist. He said preservationists are willing
to allow most of the hotel to be razed if the original part, the
Abbott, is restored. They estimate the cost at $500,000.
   Officials, however, said it would cost about $3.5 million, money
that should go to projects more vital to the growing city.
   A redevelopment plan calls for replacing the hotel with a
parking lot, an office building and a Steinbeck museum behind a
facade depicting the original hotel.
   The city's decision stirred memories of a brillant writer who
became hated by his own neighbors because of his defense of migrant
farm workers.
   ``Steinbeck was not liked in this town,'' said Brusa, president
of the Monterey County Historical Society. ``They did not
understand him. They burned `The Grapes of Wrath' here.''
   This year is the 50th anniversary of the ``The Grapes of
Wrath,'' the Pulitzer Prize-winning novel that was once banned in
the Salinas library.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NearMisses     04-24 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Near Misses,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Near Misses In New York Area; Piedmont Jet Evacuated In N.C.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jumbo jet and a commuter plane flew about 100
feet apart as they approached Kennedy International Airport, and 45
minutes later a jetliner reported coming within 400 yards of a
private plane.
   No injuries were reported in either incident Sunday, and Federal
Aviation Administration spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen said they were
``totally unrelated and happened miles and miles apart.''
   Also Sunday, a Piedmont Airlines jet was evacuated at
Fayetteville, N.C., Regional Airport when the crew noticed smoke
inside the plane. Two of its 76 passengers were injured during the
evacuation, officials said.
   The first near miss involved a small turboprop commuter plane
and a Boeing 747, Bergen said.
   TWA Flight 701 from London was flying at 1,900 feet about five
miles southeast of Kennedy when the pilot reported that a Pocono
airline plane had passed about 100 feet above and to the right,
Bergen said.
   Both planes were being monitored by air traffic controllers and
preparing to land at Kennedy, she said.
   The Pocono pilot had been instructed to land after the TWA
plane, which was scheduled behind an Air France jetliner, she said.
The Air France jet had just landed when the Pocono plane flew by
the TWA jet, Bergen said.
   Bergen said the TWA pilot did not take evasive action. The
Pocono Merlin SW-4 was ordered to abort its landing so the TWA
flight could land first.
   Bergen did not know where Pocono Flight 7636 originated, and
there was no answer Sunday night at the airline's New York office.
   The other near miss occurred near Westchester County Airport and
involved a Pan Am jet flying LaGuardia Airport to Boston and a
small Cessna plane, Bergen said.
   The Pan Am Boeing 727 had been cleared by air controllers to
climb to 17,000 feet and had just passed 10,000 feet when the
captain reported that the Cessna was 400 yards away and had a
vertical separation of 200 feet, said Bergen.
   The Pan Am plane turned and climbed in the opposite direction to
avoid the Cessna 414, Bergen said.
   She said the captain's reports will be studied along with tapes
and other materials to determine who erred. She said officials have
the Cessna's registration number and have determined the plane was
headed for Bedford, Pa. It was not under the direction of the
traffic controllers.
   Bergen said she did not know how many people were aboard the
planes in the two incidents.
   In Fayetteville, the Piedmont jetliner left the terminal, then
made an abrupt stop, a passenger said. Dave Shipley, spokesman for
USAir Group Inc., which owns Piedmont, said a crew member informed
the pilot of smoke in the passenger compartment.
   Shipley said the smoke came from smoldering loose oil in the
plane's duct system near an auxiliary power unit mounted in the
tail section. Heat from the unit may have caused the oil to
smolder, he said.
   ``There was no fire, but there was some smoke coming out of
it,'' Shipley said. ``The smoke intensified enough that he felt it
was prudent to stop the airplane and disembark the passengers down
the evacuation chute.''
   The Boeing 727-200 was headed to Pittsburgh.
   One passenger suffered broken bones in his back and another
complained of chest pains and lower back pains, said relatives and
officials.
   Shipley said three chutes were used and that one of them was
deflated after it was punctured by a sharp object carried by a
passenger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
