<FIRST>r a PM-CarAuction     04-24 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Car Auction,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare 1931 Bugatti Classic Auto Auctioned For $11 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare 1931 Bugatti Type-41 Royale received a
record $11 million bid at an international classic car auction.
   The bid was made by Ed Weaver, a carpet mill owner from Dalton,
Ga. During the six-minute, 20-second auction, Weaver outbid three
other bidders, including author Clyve Cussler of Denver and
Domino's Pizza of Detroit.
   But owner Hans Thulin of Stockholm wants $15 million for the
Bugatti, one of only six in existence, and continued negotiations
with Weaver late Sunday.
   A determination on whether the vehicle will be sold was expected
today.
   Bidding at the Landmark Hotel and Casino opened at $2 million,
jumped to $5 million and began proceeding in $1 million increments
within the first minute of bidding.
   The previous auction price record for an automobile was $9.87
million set in 1987 in London by Thulin on the same Italian
vehicle, officials said.
   A total of 546 cars were auctioned at this two-day event known
as The Auction, bringing total bids of between $45 million and $50
million, according to co-organizers Richie Clyne and Don Williams.
   Thirty-four vehicles went for at least $100,000 each at the
third-annual auction, including a 1932 Duesenberg Murphy SJ, which
sold for $1.15 million.
   The event attracted 2,000 bidders from 14 countries, according
to Clyne.
</TEXT>
