<SECOND>PM-China-Hu Yaobang,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hu's Ashes To Be Buried in Remote Forest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ashes of former Communist Party chief Hu
Yaobang are to be buried in a remote southern China forest planted
by members of the Communist Youth League he once headed, a
newspaper reported today.
   The party's official People's Daily said Hu's widow Li Zhao
requested that the ashes be buried on the Gongqing (Communist
Youth) reclamation farm in Jiangxi province.
   Gongqing farm was started in 1955 by 98 Shanghai youth under the
guidance of Hu, then secretary of the Communist Youth League.
   Hu died of a heart attack on April 15 at age 73. He was cremated
on Saturday following a state funeral in the Great Hall of the
People attended by 4,000 of China's top leaders.
   The death of the reformist leader has sparked weeklong student
demonstrations for democratic reforms. Today, students at major
Beijing universities began an indefinite class boycott to press
their demands for free speech and an end to government corruption.
   Hu was ousted as party general secretary in January 1987 after
being accused of being soft on student demonstrations and Western
liberal trends.
