<DOCNO> AP890424-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     04-24 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
today and stock prices fell in the lightest trading so far this
year amid concerns about a possible interest rate increase and an
intensifying political scandal.
   The dollar closed at 131.38 yen, down from its close of 131.45
yen on Friday. It opened at 131.37 yen and ranged between 131.20
and 131.45 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues dropped 223.89 points, or 0.68 percent, closing at
33,805.92 points.
   Volume was exceptionally light at about 450 million shares. The
market fell 155.34 points on Friday.
   Concern about the Recruit stock-profiteering and bribery scandal
shaking Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's government, a possible
discount rate increase by the Bank of Japan and hesitancy before a
weeklong holiday next week dampened the foreign exchange and stock
markets, dealers said.
   ``It was a broad decline,'' said Christopher Taylor, head of
equity sales at Baring Securities Japan Ltd.
   ``Institutional investors are really worried the Nikkei Dow
might plunge even if the discount rate is raised just 0.5
percent,'' although rumors were rife that it would be raised as
much as 1 percent, said a salesman at a foreign securities house
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said that because of Golden Week, the coming holiday,
``institutional investors are trying to wait to see what everyone
else is doing.''
   Speculation about a possible discount rate increase later this
week also helped dampen currency trading, traders said.
   ``Some people expect the Bank of Japan will move to hike the
discount rate after the consumer price index is announed this
week,'' said Ichiro Ikeda, head of the international corporate desk
in the foreign exchange section of Chemical Bank. He said he
remained skeptical of the rumor.
   The rate is what the central bank charges for loans to
commercial banks, and in turn influences their interest rates.
   ``The market is very uncertain and very quiet,'' said Norio
Takeda, senior manager of foreign exchange at the Bank of Tokyo. He
noted that traders also were waiting for an expected announcement
sometime this week by the West German government about a tax change.
   West Germany's withholding tax, which went into effect Jan. 1,
has prompted large capital outflows and a weaker mark since it was
announced last year.
</TEXT>
