<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     04-24 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Iraq,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Both Sides Reaffirm Truce But Remain Deadlocked In Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq made no progress in their latest
round of peace talks but remain committed to the cease-fire that
halted their eight-year war, says U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar.
   The U.N. chief, who chaired the four days of talks between the
countries' foreign ministers that ended Sunday, said he might seek
a fifth round of talks in June.
   ``We have clarified positions again, but what I call progress
has not been obtained,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
   He said both sides reassured him of their commitment ``to the
upholding of the cease-fire and the pursuit of the process.''
   The talks have been stalled since the first round began on Aug.
25, five days after the U.N.-supervised truce halted hostilities.
   Iran and Iraq said they are ready for more talks but accused
each other of instransigence on resolving issues.
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, said Iraq had
refused a proposed 15-day period for withdrawing its troops from
Iranian soil. Velayati had demanded that Perez de Cuellar set such
a timetable.
   The United Nations says that about 260 square miles of Iranian
territory remain under Iraqi control. Tehran says the area is three
times as large.
   Velayati said Iraq's foreign minister, Tariq Aziz, also
continued to reject U.N. proposals for repatriation of prisoners
and clearing the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, Iraq's only sea outlet, of
silt and war debris.
   Aziz said Iran ``refrained from the correct manner of conducting
negotiations'' but did not mention specific issues.
</TEXT>
