<FIRST>r a PM-Burning-Sheriff     04-24 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burning-Sheriff,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Minister Resigns Rather Than Dismiss ``Mississippi Burning''
Sheriff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERIDIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black minister stepped down after
church members' relentless attacks for his hiring of a white former
sheriff acquitted in the slaying of three civil rights workers 25
years ago.
   For his last sermon at Golden Grove Missionary Baptist Church in
Meehan, the Rev. Evan E. McDonald chose the topics of God's love
and forgiveness _ qualities he said he showed in hiring former
Neshoba County Sheriff Lawrence Rainey as a guard in his Meridian
security service.
   The killings were depicted in the movie ``Mississippi Burning.''
   ``For 17 years, I didn't have any kind of problem with that
church and _ boom!'' McDonald said before Sunday's service. ``Some
of the people real close to me said as long as that man was working
for me there would be no peace in that church. I told them I'd
leave for peace sake. ...
   ``We teach love. We teach forgiveness. Here are people who
profess to be Christians and they behave like heathens,'' McDonald
said, adding that he had received threatening telephone calls and
his security business is ``not flourishing like it should.''
   Hervy Spinks, chairman of the church's deacons, declined to
comment.
   ``That's between him and God,'' he said of McDonald's
resignation.
   Rainey was among 18 men indicted by a federal grand jury after
the 1964 slayings of 21-year-old James Chaney, who was black, and
20-year-old Andrew Goodman and 24-year-old Michael Schwerner, who
were white. He was acquitted in 1967 of violating their civil
rights by depriving them of life.
   The controversy in the small church surfaced after People
magazine published an article Jan. 9 about Rainey, noting the irony
of his working for a black. The article preceded the release of
``Mississippi Burning.''
   McDonald blames the movie for stirring up racial hostilities. He
said much of the contention has been directed toward him and his
McDonald's Security Service.
   Rainey offred to leave rather than cause problems for his boss.
   ``I really hate it for him,'' Rainey said. ``I offered to quit
or have him lay me off. He said, `No! No!'
   ``I think it will finally blow over if they ever quit playing
this movie in Meridian.''
   The Rev. Wardell Tanksley of Collinsville said the movie can't
be blamed for McDonald losing his church.
   ``I love him, but he made a mistake,'' Tanksley said. ``I'm not
saying he should fire him. All of us have to work. Evan should have
used better action. He should never have hired him.
   ``He (Rainey) was associated with something that's a smear on
Mississippi, a scar on the pages of history,'' Tanksley said.
   If his goal was to be more Christian, McDonald should have tried
to get Rainey to give speeches at black churches to defuse the
racial tension, said Tanksley, pastor of St. Paul Missionary
Baptist Church in Philadelphia.

</TEXT>
