<FIRST>r a PM-WomanAssaulted     04-24 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Woman Assaulted,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth In Central Park Attack Said It Was `Fun'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight teen-agers charged in the beating and rape
of a Central Park jogger have shown no remorse, and one called it
``fun'' in a confession, police said.
   Seven of the youths, ages 14 to 17, made videotaped statements
to police; the eighth gave a written statement, said Gerald
McKelvey, a spokesman for the district attorney's office.
   After hearing about the statements at their arraignment,
Manhattan Criminal Court Judge Charles Solomon ordered all eight
held without bail on charges of second-degree attempted murder,
first-degree rape and first-degree assault.
   The victim, a 28-year-old Wall Street investment banker whose
skull was fractured Wednesday by a pipe and a brick, remained in a
coma Sunday, said Richard Conte, an administrator at Metropolitan
Hospital.
   The attack came while the pack of youths was ``wilding'' in the
park _ their term for a rampage of random violence and thievery,
police said. The woman was attacked by at least 12 youths who were
hiding in the underbrush by a road in a northern section of Central
Park when she jogged alone after dark.
   Police said the group knocked her down with the metal pipe and
gagged her with her clothing. While some held her down and fondled
her, at least four raped her.
   The eight youths have shown no remorse, sang a rap song about
sex, ``Wild Thing,'' whistled at policewomen and laughed when
comparing what they had told detectives, according to published
reports.
   ``It was fun,'' one of the suspects, 15-year-old Yusef Salaam,
said in a written confession, according to McKelvey.
   All of the suspects are being tried as adults, but only two,
ages 16 and 17, could be sentenced as adults.
   Detectives investigating that attack believe that some of the
youths may have participated in a similar attack four days earlier.
   A roving gang of youths terrorized an East Harlem area on April
15 using tactics similar to those used Wednesday, The New York
Times reported today.
</TEXT>
