<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LotteryFever     04-24 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lottery Fever,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pa. Scrambling For $70 Million Pot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREAT BEND, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North American record lottery prize
sent gamblers and non-gamblers to lines to buy a one in 9.6 million
chance at winning at least $70 million.
   Across Pennsylvania, Super 7 Lottery tickets sold at a rate of
750,000 an hour this weekend.
   ``I wouldn't be an American if I didn't play,'' said Colleen
Marchiano, 34, who bought $10 worth of tickets at Beavers
Restaurant in Great Bend.
   Among those in line was Howard Hurst, 66, who drove three hours
from East Greenbush, N.Y. Did he come to buy a lottery ticket?
``No, I came for a hamburger,'' he said, shaking his head at the
question.
   What did he plan to do if he won? ``Spend it on lottery
tickets,'' he said, drawing laughs from those in line near him.
   Participants select seven numbers out of 80. The player wins if
those seven numbers are among the 11 that will be drawn Wednesday
night.
   The jackpot will be larger than the record-breaking $69.9
million won by four Illinois ticket-holders April 15. The largest
single U.S. lottery payout was $55.16 million won by a Florida
woman in September in that state's lotto game.
   ``It's a chance to buy a very large, life-changing prize with a
very small amount of money,'' said Pennsylvania Lottery Executive
Director James Scroggins.
   But a psychologist warned Sunday that many players are in for
depression when reality catches up with their dreams.
   ``This lottery fantasy syndrome really heats up when the lotto
jackpot climbs over $50 million,'' said Robert R. Butterworth, a
researcher at Contemporary Psychology Associates Inc. in Los
Angeles. ``People purchase a ticket, ignore the odds and start
thinking of the impossible.''
   At Beavers, however, the restaurant called in a police officer
to help control the line that totaled up to 500 at a time.
   ``They're out there freezing,'' Gary Conklin, the restaurant
manager, said of the crowd Saturday. ``As the line goes down, 30
more people replace them.''
   ``I've never seen anything like it since I've been around here,
and I've been here all my life,'' said Victor Welch, 60, a
patrolman with the Hallstead-Great Bend-New Milford Municipal
Police Department.
   ``It's exciting just to see them come in here,'' said Carlene
Haggerty, 40, a waitress at Beavers. ``They all have a dream.
Everybody has a dream.''
   Ms. Haggerty has a dream, too. She'd move to Nashville and try
to sell some of the country and western songs she's written.
   Like everyone else, she knew her chances were slim. But she's
written a poem that hangs on the wall of the restaurant.
   It begins: ``Lottery sold here says the sign on the door. If you
have a dream come in and find out more.'' It ends: ``Change your
life my friend if you care to spend a dollar. Where else can you
buy a dream for a dollar?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
