<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Teachers     04-24 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Teachers,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resignation Of Union Boss Could Speed Strike Negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The resignation of the leader of the
country's powerful teachers' union could help end a week-old
strike, but the striking teachers are still demanding higher wages,
their leaders say.
   In a two-paragraph statement issued Sunday, the Presidential
Palace said Carlos Jonguitud Barrios told President Carlos Salinas
de Gortari he was stepping down as head of the National Education
Worker's Union.
   Teachers had accused him of corruption and called for his ouster.
   The strike was called by the National Coordinate, a dissident
faction in the union that accuses union leaders of political
patronage, corruption and of neglecting the rank-and-file.
   The union, with a membership of more than 1 million, is among
the largest and most powerful in Latin America. The National
Coordinate claims about half the membership.
   The government news agency Notimex on Sunday quoted dissident
teachers as saying that Jonguitud's resignation should help
negotiations but that they would not give up their demands for a
100 percent salary increase and union reforms such as free
elections. Teachers now earn about $142 a month.
   The strike talks were to resume today after a weekend recess.
   The strikers also said they planned a mass march to Zocalo,
Mexico City's huge central plaza. A similar demonstration last week
rallied tens of thousands of people to the downtown plaza.
   Dissident teachers nationwide walked off the job one week ago,
shutting down thousands of schools and focusing national attention
on the union's internal battles.
   Previous administrations tried to ignore the dissident movement,
which has been growing for a decade.
   The Salinas administration reacted to the strike by organizing
talks between the union and its dissident wing and by offering a 10
percent salary increase.
   Jonguitud was closely allied to the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party and had been rewarded with a relatively free
hand in union matters.
   He had controlled the union since 1972.
   Dissidents teachers say Jonguitud used the post to enrich
himself while doing nothing to improve the lot of teachers.
</TEXT>
