<FIRST>r i PM-France-Arafat 2ndLd-Writethru a0472 04-24 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Arafat, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0472,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>May 2 Set As Date For First Official Arafat Visit To Paris</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with date confirmed. Picks up
4th pvs, `But Prime ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat will make his first
official visit to France next month, meeting with President
Francois Mitterrand and other government officials on May 2,
Mitterrand's spokesman announced today.
   The spokesman, Hubert Vedrine, did not provide other details and
did not say whether Arafat's visit would last more than one day.
   The principle _ although not the date _ of an official visit had
been announced two weeks ago, leading to criticism from Israel and
French Jews who contend the PLO remains committed to Israel's
destruction.
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas, interviewed Sunday on French
television, said France remains ``a close friend of Israel.''
   But Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel later said that he
sees the planned visit ``with gravity.''
   ``President Mitterrand presents himself as a friend of Israel,
but what he does today totally opposes any friendly treatment of
Israel,'' Shamir said in an interview with Israel army radio.
   Dumas said France takes into account Israel's concerns, but also
what he called ``the reality of the Palestinian people.''
   He said the actions of the Palestine National Council last
November in Algiers and statements by Arafat in Geneva accepting
the right of Israel to exist and renouncing terrorism made the
visit possible.
   Dumas noted that Arafat already has made official visits to
Greece, Spain and Italy and has been received by Pope John Paul II.
   Dumas and other French foreign ministers have met with Arafat on
several occasions, but never before in Paris.
   After Arafat's statements in Geneva, the United States dropped
its ban on all contacts with the PLO.
   Since then representatives of the group in Tunis, Tunisia, where
the PLO is headquartered, have met several times with U.S.
Ambassador Robert Pelletreau.
</TEXT>
