<FIRST>r a PM-BeringBridge     04-24 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bering Bridge,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska-Siberia Eskimo Protocol Signed Despite Poor Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blowing snow forced Alaska and Soviet
officials to meet over the telephone instead of on the Bering Sea
ice for a symbolic gesture aimed at easing travel restrictions on
U.S. and Soviet Eskimos.
   Gov. Steve Cowper and his counterpart from the Magadan region of
the Soviet Far East, Vyacheslav I. Kobets, signed a protocol Sunday
urging Soviet and U.S. officials to allow regular visits between
Eskimos in the two countries.
   Cowper and Kobets had planned to sign the document on the
international dateline, but bad weather grounded the mayor in Nome.
   He used a telephone to communicate with Kobets, whose delegation
made it by helicopter to Little Diomede Island on the U.S. side of
the dateline. Little Diomede is 2{ miles from Big Diomede Island on
the Soviet side.
   About 40 people jammed into a small office of a telephone
company switching station to watch Cowper sign the protocol. Cowper
and Kobets, who had been sent a copy of the document earlier,
talked through translators.
   The protocol calls for a border commission to oversee travel
between the two countries. Eskimos would not be required to obtain
visas, only to check in with the commission before traveling.
   Eskimos from Alaska and Siberia routinely visited each other
under a 1938 agreement, but the so-called Bering Bridge was closed
at the onset of the Cold War 10 years later.
   ``Even though this is perhaps not the best way to make this
agreement, it is a very significant step, we think,'' said Cowper,
apologizing for the weather. ``We believe it is a great and
important event.''
   Cowper said that he is uncertain when U.S. and Soviet diplomats
might complete their negotiations on the matter but that it could
be by summer.
   The signing was to have taken place at the site of the dateline
crossing Sunday by a U.S.-Soviet team of adventurers on a 60-day
trek aimed at calling attention to the common cultural heritage of
Bering natives.
   The group of six Soviets and six Americans is using skis,
dogsleds and Eskimo ``skin boats'' to travel 1,200 miles through
the Soviet Far East and Alaska. The expedition began in mid-March
in the Siberian city of Anadyr.
   Cowper told Kobets he would like to visit the Magadan region in
September, and asked, ``Should I bring my fishing rod?''
   ``You can bring your own, but we'll give you one,'' replied
Kobets, suggesting they swap poles.
   ``That is what we would call a deal,'' Cowper said.
   ``It's what we call a good deal,'' Kobets responded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
