<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--VolkswagenBirths     04-24 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Volkswagen Births,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Club Honors Babies Born In VW Models</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Being born in a VW Beetle may be a bizarre
way to begin life, but it doesn't bug Volkswagen of America, which
hands out $300 savings bonds instead of cigars.
   The automaker has cited 403 infants since it launched its
``Bonds for Babies Born in Volkswagens'' program in 1964, VW
publicist Tom McDonald said.
   Only 10 babies have been inducted into the club in the past five
years, McDonald said. Children believed to have been conceived in
VWs don't qualify.
   VW births haven't been limited to humans, McDonald said. One
Beetle owner wrote that his Great Dane bore a litter in the back
seat of the Bug.
   The canine received a case of dog food instead of a bond,
McDonald said.
