<HEAD>Soviet Diplomats Flee Angry Indian Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts throughout to tighten and clarify lead; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANTOSH BASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mob of jobless workers hunting for a
man who shut down two textile mills mistakenly chased six Soviet
diplomats and smashed their cars, police said today.
   The laid-off jute workers, led by Marxist trade unionists,
attacked a house where the Soviet envoys were attending a picnic.
   ``We are Russian Communists. Don't attack us,'' police quoted
the diplomats as saying when about 200 men armed with machetes,
homemade bombs and bamboo canes on Sunday raided the house in the
village of Dogacha, about 25 miles from Calcutta.
   They said none of the Soviets, who work at the Calcutta
consulate and included deputy trade commissioner A.V. Donocian, was
injured but their cars were smashed.
   A jute trader, Nabin Sur, had invited the Soviets to a picnic at
his father's house, police said.
   The mob was looking for the owner of two jute mills that were
shut down a year ago and mistakenly thought he was attending the
picnic, according to police, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``We want his head,'' the angry men chanted. The Soviets ran out
of the house pursued by the crowd but managed to find shelter in
nearby houses, the police said.
   The mob dispersed after Sur's father fired a gun in the air and
police arrived.
   Narayanan Krishnamurthy, chief secretary of Marxist-governed
West Bengal state, said six people, including a Marxist labor
leader, had been arrested.
</TEXT>
