<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-InaugurationBicentennial     04-24 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inauguration Bicentennial,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>First President Stand-In Questioned About Star Wars, Baseball</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The real George Washington surely didn't have to
answer questions about Star Wars, baseball and bad teeth the way
his stand-in did at ceremonies marking the 200th anniversary of the
first president's inauguration.
   As history buffs and tourists looked on, Washington's arrival in
New York was re-enacted Sunday at South Street Seaport, several
blocks from where the real Washington arrived for festivities
preceding his swearing-in on April 30, 1789.
   William Sommerfield of Philadelphia, an expert on the nation's
first president, stepped off a boat in a tri-corner hat and cape,
amid skyscrapers and the roar of traffic that he made a point of
ignoring.
   The ceremony kicked off a week of events marking the
bicentennial.
   ``A bold new experiment in government was launched on that day
in this great city,'' Mayor Edward I. Koch said. He welcomed
``George Washington, reincarnated, back to New York City.''
   Two centuries ago, the real Washington alighted from a barge via
carpeted steps as church bells pealed and cannons blasted.
Eschewing a fancy coach, he strolled up narrow Wall Street, bowing
and tipping his hat to cheering admirers who leaned out of windows
and looked down from rooftops.
   On Sunday, many in the crowd applauded as the mock Washington
walked by, and some asked the white-haired gentleman for an
autograph. But not 72-year-old Monte Schreck, who wanted to know
where Washington would take his wife.
   ``Are you going to take her to Shea Stadium for a Mets game?''
Schreck asked.
   ``I'm sorry sir, I am not familiar with your term. Is that a
political party, sir?'' asked Sommerfield.
   Later, someone asked, ``How do you feel about Star Wars?''
   ``Are you from another country, sir? I'm only a poor Virginia
farmer. You have to speak my language,'' Sommerfield said.
   When one impertinent reporter asked, ``How are your teeth at
this point?'', Sommerfield took the opportunity to remind listeners
that the old tale of George's wooden teeth was ``a fallacy. ...
They are made of bone and ivory.''
   With that a mock presidential aide stepped in and said,
``Gentleman, that's a rather personal question for the president.''
   A few people tested Sommerfield on controversial issues.
   ``What about slavery? Are you against slavery?'' a man shouted.
   ``I am totally against the trading of human species,''
Sommerfield said. ``And during my terms in office I will work
toward the elimination of slavery under the law.''
   The most difficult question may have had to do with the
president's seemingly poor eyesight.
   ``Did the skyscrapers and cars surprise you at all?'' someone
asked.
   ``Skyscrapers sir?'' the playfully bewildered Sommerfield asked.
   Minutes later he was driven away in a dented old Plymouth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
