<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Karajan 1stLd-Writethru   04-24 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Karajan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0503,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Karajan Resigns As Berlin Philharmonic Director</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more background, details</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert von Karajan, an internationally acclaimed
conductor who sold 150 million albums worldwide, resigned today
after 34 years as director of the Berlin Philharmonic.
   Karajan, whose chronic back problems have made it difficult for
him to walk to a podium, cited frail health as his reason for
resigning, said Anke Martiny, West Berlin's culture senator.
   She said she received a letter today from Karajan informing her
that he was stepping down immediately.
   Karajan was appointed ``conductor for life'' of the Berlin
orchestra in 1955, and his resignation leaves open one of the most
coveted conductor's posts. Many leading conductors have been
mentioned as possible successors since Karajan's health began to
deteriorate, but his resignation letter made no recommendation.
   Karajan, who turned 81 on April 5, was born in Salzburg and
keeps a residence in the Austrian resort. A child prodigy who made
his piano debut at age 5, he now earns an estimated $6.2 million
annually from his recordings.
   He joined the Nazi party while a rising young musical star
during Hitler's reign, and his involvement was still drawing
criticism more than 40 years after the end of World War II.
   Because of his Nazi links, the Allies banned Karajan from
performing for two years after the war and required him to undergo
a ``de-Nazification'' program. In an interview, Karajan once said
he had joined the Nazis so his would not be jeopardized but
insisted he had no sympathies for the group.
   In his letter of resignation read by Mrs. Martiny, Karajan said:
``I kindly ask you to note that as of today's date, I am ending my
work as artistic director and permanent conductor of the Berlin
Philharmonic.''
   ``The results of the medical examinations, which now have
stretched for weeks, make it impossible for me to fulfill my
obligations,'' the letter said.
   Mrs. Martiny, whose department in the West Berlin legislature is
in charge of the orchestra, said: ``I respect this decision by
Herbert von Karajan, which comes for health reasons.''
   ``Berlin thanks Herbert von Karajan for his long-time, excellent
and successful work,' she said.
   ``I hope that Karajan's friends in Berlin will have one more
opportunity to see him conducting the Berlin Philharmonic'' in a
farewell performance, Mrs. Martiny said.
   Karajan had major back surgery in 1976 and had to learn again to
walk properly after crushing nerves in his back two years later
when he collapsed at the podium in Berlin.
   His frail health forced him to cancel several performances with
the orchestra and earlier this year he said he was reducing his
1989 performances from 12 to six.
   His last performance in the United States was Feb. 28, 1988, at
Carnegie Hall with the Vienna Philharmonic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Sulfur-Climate     04-24 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sulfur-Climate,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists to Study Role of Sulfur in Climate Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international team of scientists will take
to the ocean in May to study the role played by sulfur gases in
changing the Earth's climate.
   Researchers from the United States and the Soviet Union will
take part in the study, focusing on sulfur gases released from the
water in the eastern Pacific Ocean, the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration said today.
   Sulfur gases are oxidized in the air and the resulting chemicals
are thought to influence the reflectivity of clouds in the sky,
according to Dr. Timothy Bates of NOAA's Pacific Marine
Environmental Laboratory in Seattle.
   Scientists are trying to determine the overall effect of clouds
in climate. That is because clouds reflect some of the energy from
the sun back into space, but at the same time they trap some of the
heat the Earth itself would radiate away. The balance of heat
trapped and that reflected varies with the reflectivity of the
clouds.
   The 12-day research trip aboard the NOAA Ship McArthur will
allow the scientists to measure the sulfur and nitrogen particles
in the air and better calculate their influence on clouds.
   At the same time, measurements of clouds themselves will be made
by aircraft from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration,
the University of Washington and Battelle Pacific Northwest
Laboratories.
   Other research organizations participating in the study include
the National Science Foundation, Department of Defense, Department
of Energy, Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute, University of
Arizona, Georgia Institute of Technology, University of Miami, the
Soviet Institute of Atmospheric Physics and the Soviet Institute of
Applied Geophysics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
