<FIRST>u a PM-RougeExplosion     04-24 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rouge Explosion,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast Rocks Ford Plant; Two Reported Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion rocked the underbelly of the
Ford Motor Co. Rouge Complex today, and two sewer workers were
reported missing.
   The 6:20 a.m. blast, apparently centered in the sewer system
near the main powerhouse, overturned cars, blew manholes into the
air and tore holes 20 feet to 30 feet in diameter in the parking
lot, said Ford spokesman Bill Carroll.
   ``It sent shock waves (through sewer tunnels) and vented itself
through these tunnels and into a parking lot,'' he said.
   Carroll said two workers cleaning the sewer system for an
outside company were missing. A few Ford workers were slightly
injured in the blast and were treated at a medical center in the
complex, he said. There was no fire.
   The cause of the explosion was not immediately known.
   The blast interrupted power to the complex, which contains a
steelmaking operation, an auto assembly plant and other Ford
operations.
   Carroll said that the blast shut down computers and other
operations but that it was unclear this morning how much of the
complex continued to operate.
   However, a United Auto Workers source who spoke on condition of
anonymity said the assembly plant, which builds the Mustang, a
glass plant and a stamping plant were shut down, mainly because of
a lack of compressed air to operate machinery.
   The source said 7,000 to 8,000 first-shift employees of the
17,500 workers in the complex were sent home.
</TEXT>
