<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Education     04-24 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Education,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Drugs Worst Problem Facing Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Drugs, drugs and drugs'' are the three worst
problems facing American schools because drug abuse affects morale
and discipline in the classroom, President Bush says on a program
being telecast tonight on most Public Broadcasting Service stations.
   Bush, interviewed for the last segment of a five-part series
called ``Learning In America,'' also said it is not up to the
federal government to ensure equity in education and said freedom
of choice in public schools could help ease that problem.
   Asked by PBS correspondent Roger Mudd to name the three most
pressing U.S. education problems, Bush replied, ``Drugs, drugs and
drugs... I hope that's not a frivolous answer, but I want to say it
that way because of the impact that drugs are having.
   ``They have it on the morale of teachers. They have it on
discipline in the classroom. They have ... the adverse impact on
the areas that need help the most.''
   Bush said the nation must find some way to signal to teachers
``that we respect those who choose that profession, and find ways
to encourage more to do it.''
   But he said he didn't really know the answer to the question of
how to reward teachers and acknowledged that ``they're never going
to have it made... in a financial sense.''
   On another education matter, Mudd asked if it is fair for a
child in a ghetto high school in Camden, N.J., to have less than
$4,000 spent on him while $7,000 is spent on a child in affluent
Princeton, N.J. ``Is that not a violation of civil rights?'' he
asked Bush.
   ``No, it is not a violation,'' Bush replied. ``Is it fair that
football coach makes 10 times as much as a high school teacher? Is
it far that a television announcer on the network news every night
makes 20 times or 30 or 40 times as much as a teacher that's trying
to keep your kid and mine out of narcotics?''
   ``I'm not sure everything is equitable, and I am sure, though,
that the federal government can't smooth out everything like this.''
   The president said the situation would improve if parents were
able to choose the public school their child attended. ``They might
not be able to move from Camden to Princeton, but if we have this
choice take hold, they can move into a school that is less heavily
impacted by drugs ...,'' he said.
   Mudd also told Bush that at least two governers _ Democrat Bill
Clinton of Arkansas and Republican James Thompson of Illinois have
run into opposition when they have tried to get their legislatures
to approve new taxes for education improvements.
   The interviewer attributed the legislative stone wall to Bush's
success running against new taxes last fall.
   Bush replied that the federal government should ``hold the line
on taxes and not create taxes that take away from the state's
resource base. And so I would let each state governor, obviously,
make his own decision or her own decision. But I will not
criticize, nor extend the read-my-lips (no new taxes) syndrome to
every governor that ... is mandated to balance budgets.''
</TEXT>
