<FIRST>r a PM-Harvard-ROTC     04-24 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harvard-ROTC,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvard Student Council Wants ROTC Back on Campus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after ROTC was driven off
the Harvard University campus, the student council wants it back.
   In a 41-24 vote Sunday, the Undergraduate Council asked the
university to negotiate with the military to bring back Reserve
Officers' Training Corps programs, which prepare students for
appointments as military officers.
   The military left Harvard in 1969 after the university withdrew
academic credit for ROTC and decided it should be an
extracurricular activity with no special privileges. The edict
followed a building takeover and a student strike.
   Now, the 150 or so Harvard students who take part in ROTC
programs do so at the nearby Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   Harvard spokeswoman Marjorie Heffron said a return by ROTC would
have to be approved by the faculty.
   ``If they try to get that through the faculty, there would be
quite a fight,'' Dr. Warren E.C. Wacker, head of the university's
health services, told the Harvard Crimson, the student newspaper.
   The student council vote followed two hours of heated debate.
The resolution was sponsored by two ROTC candidates and had the
backing of the council's leadership, the newspaper said.
   Joel Hornstein, a freshman who supported the measure, said it
wasn't intended as an endorsement of the military.
   ``I don't think there's anyone in ROTC who blindly supports
everything our government or our military does,'' he said.
   Army, Navy and Air Force ROTC programs provide financial aid to
participants.
</TEXT>
