<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-KCDeseg     04-24 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-KC Deseg,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Review Order Raising Property Taxes to Help Desegregate
Kansas City Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to review a
judge's order raising property taxes to help pay for racially
desegregating public schools in Kansas City, Mo.
   The justices said they will hear arguments that the judge
overstepped his authority when imposing the tax hike for all
property within the city's school district.
   A series of orders by U.S. District Judge Russell G. Clark that
would cost hundreds of millions of dollars to implement was
challenged in appeals by state and county officials and school
district taxpayers.
   Most of the judge's orders were upheld by the 8th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals last Aug. 19.
   The funding controversy dates back to a 1977 lawsuit seeking to
correct the physical decline of predominantly black schools in
Kansas City.
   Before 1954, Missouri law required schools to be racially
segregated. From 1954 to 1984 the percentage of black students in
Kansas City's school district climbed from 22.5 percent to 67.7
percent.
   In a 1987 ruling, Clark found that the city school district's
``physical facilities have literally rotted,'' and ordered the
state and school district to upgrade them.
   In upholding most of the judge's order, the 8th Circuit court
said, ``There are still vestiges of the dual school system
lingering in the (city school district), and the district and the
state have not met their obligations to disestablish that system.''
   The judge's orders called for two major remedies:
   _A ``magnet school'' plan providing that by the 1991-92 school
year every high school and middle school in the city, and about
half the elementary schools, will feature distinctive themes such
as foreign languages, performing arts or math and science.
   _A capital improvements program costing some $260 million, to be
completed by the fall of 1990.
   To enable the city school district to pay its share of the
desegregation plan's costs, the judge imposed a 1.5 percent income
tax surcharge and hiked school district property taxes to $4 per
$100 assessed valuation through the 1991-92 fiscal year.
   The state's appeal, granted review today, says the $4 per $100
levy represented a doubling of the local property tax.
   Clark ordered the tax increases because no money was available
to finance the construction of new schools. Between 1970 and 1983,
school district voters had turned down six proposals to increase
taxes for education.
   He also authorized the school district to issue $150 million in
20-year capital improvement bonds.
   The appeals court upheld the property tax hike but struck down
the income tax surcharge, which had raised some $30 million before
being invalidated.
   The state was ordered to pay 75 percent of the desegregation
costs; the school district the remaining 25 percent.
   The state appeal acted on today said the lower court rulings
``rest upon an unwarranted extension of this court's desegregation
cases.''
   The appeal said the magnet school remedy was, as ordered by
Clark, overbroad _ ``unlike any ever ordered by a federal court.''
   The appeal also said that ``the order imposing a tax increase is
outside the bounds of judicial authority.''
   In a brief order, the justices rejected two appeals filed in the
case, and limited review of the state's appeal to the validity of
the ordered tax increase.
   The cases are Missouri vs. Jenkins, 88-1150; Clark vs. Jenkins,
88-1194; and Jackson County vs. Jenkins, 88-1228.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Whaling     04-24 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Whaling,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whaling Ship Returns After Killing 241 Whales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whaling supporters welcomed home the mother ship of
Japan's whaling fleet today after a four-month hunt in the
Antarctic in which it dodged protesters and killed 241 whales.
   The Nisshin Maru No. 3's return marked the end of the second
year of Japan's research whaling program, which it launched after
officially ending commercial whaling in 1987 to comply with a ban
imposed by the International Whaling Commission.
   In a welcoming ceremony on the ship's long, rusted deck,
officials promised the 120 crew members they would seek an end to
the ban, which is to be re-evaluated in 1990.
   ``I understand that you had many difficulties on your voyage,''
Fukujiro Kikuchi, a Parliament member, told the crew. ``We're doing
our best in the hope that sometime, somewhere Japan will be able to
resume commercial whaling.''
   Below the 23,000-ton ship's deck were 241 minke whales already
prepared into meat in the vessel's processing plant.
   When Japanese whaling was at its peak in the early 1960s, whales
provided 23 percent of all meat consumed in the country. Declining
supplies since then have turned whale meat into a delicacy, but
Japan is still the world's largest consumer of whale flesh.
   Under the International Whaling Commission charter, member
nations may conduct research whaling at any time without permission
from the commission and then use the meat. Japan says it hopes to
show through its research that some whale species are plentiful
enough to allow a resumption of limited commercial whaling.
   Estimates of the current number of minkes, a smaller species,
range from 400,000 to 700,000.
   But international environmental groups such as Greenpeace have
charged that Japan is using the research provision as a ploy to
continue whaling, and that non-lethal research methods are
available.
   Greenpeace members used a ship and rubber rafts to try to block
the Nisshin Maru and its three catcher boats during their hunt in
the Antarctic, and had one minor collision with the mother ship.
   Hidehiro Kato, director of research on board the Nisshin Maru,
said the voyage had shown that the random sampling methods used in
the research could be applied to a broader research program.
   ``I'd prefer to use non-lethal methods, but they aren't able to
tell us age, reproductive status or condition of the whales,'' he
said. ``At this point, the best approach is a combination of lethal
and non-lethal research.''
   Japanese officials have said at least 825 whales must be caught
each season to make the research program scientifically accurate.
But because of strong international opposition, they reduced this
year's goal to 300.
   Kato said bad weather was primarily responsible for the fleet's
falling short of the goal, but that the protests ``had some
effect.''
   ``The research whaling was approved by the Japanese
government,'' said Hideyoshi Yoshida, a crew member. ``So I wish
people opposed to it would discuss it with the government, rather
than confronting us while we're whaling.''
   Yoshida sats he took a year off from a fisheries college for a
chance to work on the ship and visit the Antarctic.
</TEXT>
