<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Deposits     04-24 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Deposits,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Decide Issue of Taxing Utility Deposits in Indiana Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether the government may tax as income the deposits that utility
companies demand from customers to insure payment of future bills.
   The court said it will hear a Bush administration appeal in a
case involving an Indiana electric utility.
   Administration officials said a considerable amount of money
could be at stake. The Internal Revenue Service estimated that more
than 150 such cases involving over $300 million in potential taxes
are pending in the courts or before the IRS.
   The case acted on today stems from a deposit policy of the
Indianapolis Power and Light Co.
   The policy, as amended in 1976, required some electricity
customers to deposit up to twice their estimated monthly bills with
the company.
   The company required the deposits from new customers whose
creditworthiness was in doubt and from existing customers with a
record of late payment of their bills.
   The utility paid 6 percent annual interest on the deposits to
customers if it held the money for at least a year. The deposit was
refunded if the customer met a credit test, or if the customer's
bill was paid on time for nine straight months or for 10 out of 12
months.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last September upheld a
ruling by the U.S. Tax Court that the deposits were not a form of
advance payment, and thus the utility did not have to pay federal
income tax on them.
   The appeals court accepted the tax court's interpretation that
the money was meant as security for the utility, not advance
payment of a customer's bill.
   Justice Department lawyers, in urging the high court to overturn
the 7th Circuit court ruling, noted that another federal appeals
court has ruled the opposite way. The government's appeal urged the
justices to resolve the conflict.
   The case is Commissioner of IRS vs. Indianapolis Power, 88-1319.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Smog-Businesses     04-24 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smog-Businesses,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business Owners Gripe About Proposed Tough New Smog Controls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business owners are griping about tough new
anti-smog measures that could transform the way Southern
Californians live and work.
   They say the regulations are too costly and in some cases rely
on technology that is unavailable.
   The new anti-smog plan by the South Coast Air Quality Management
District touches virtually every aspect of everyday life, from
underarm deodorants and swimming pools to cars, drive-through
restaurants and backyard barbecues.
   Oliver Coury, who operates Coury &amp; Son Dry Cleaners in Redondo
Beach, said he wants more time to make changes.
   ``We all contribute to air pollution, so we don't know who is
doing what to what,'' Coury said. ``I believe in everybody
tightening up, but within limits of the equipment and costs we can
afford. But they're pushing the little people more than the big
people.''
   The agency would require dry cleaners to buy new all-in-one
machines to keep fumes from escaping when clothes are transferred
from washers to dryers. Coury said the machines cost up to $70,000.
   Those changes are in the first stage of a far-reaching proposal
approved in general March 17 by the AQMD. Each of the plan's three
stages still must be approved by the 12-member board after hearings
later this year.
   Stage One requires that readily available air pollution controls
be imposed over the next five years.
   Stage Two, to go into effect by 2000, would require significant
technological advances mostly to control motor vehicles and
producers of paint and solvents.
   Stage Three could be implemented in the next century with
long-range technological breakthroughs that are unavailable now,
such as advances in solar cells and superconductors.
   Don Burns, a lobbyist for the swimming pool and spa industry,
said many people see the demands as unrealistic. For example,
adding solar panels to heat pools and spas could add up to $14,000
to the price of a pool, he said.
   R.E. Robinson of the Southern California Paint and Coatings
Association said his industry doesn't know how to make paints and
other coatings that are as low in volatile organic compounds as the
district wants.
   ``We obviously don't know how to do that or how it's going to be
done right now. But who knows what's going to happen in 10 or 20
years,'' he said.
   Sandra Burton of the Barbecue Industry Association said her
industry can't reformulate charcoal starter fluid to give off lower
emissions.
   Auto spray paint shops worry about rules that would require them
to use less-volatile paints and improve nozzles so less paint is
blown into the air.
   ``It's going to be difficult, there's no denying that. Most
everyone is going to have to reformulate their paint,'' said Ray
Poulin, who supervises five Earl Scheib shops. ``It's going to be
expensive changing equipment we already have, like spray guns.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
