<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Parks     04-24 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Parks,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Consider Reinstating Death Sentence of Oklahoma Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
reinstating the death sentence of a convicted Oklahoma killer whose
jury was told to ``avoid any influence of sympathy.''
   The justices said they will review a ruling that the jury
instructions deprived Robyn Leroy Parks of a fair sentencing trial.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, by a 6-4 vote last Oct.
20, said Parks is entitled to a new sentencing trial.
   The October ruling, however, did not disturb Park's murder
conviction for the Aug. 17, 1977, shooting death of Abdullah
Ibrahim, an Oklahoma City gas station attendant.
   At Park's sentencing trial, the presiding judge told jurors,
among other things, ``You must avoid any influence of sympathy,
sentiment, passion, prejudice or other arbitrary factor when
imposing sentence.''
   The 10th Circuit court said that instruction ``undermined the
jury's consideration of the mitigating evidence'' _ factors
suggesting life imprisonment rather than death as the appropriate
punishment.
   The Supreme Court in 1987 upheld a California murderer's death
sentence even though jurors in that case were told they should not
be swayed by ``mere sympathy.''
   The justices, by a 5-4 vote, said in the California case that a
reasonable juror would ``understand the instruction not to rely on
`mere sympathy' as a directive to ignore only the sort of sympathy
that would be totally divorced from the evidence adduced during the
penalty phase.''
   In Parks' case, the appeals court noted that ``the anti-sympathy
instruction ... is not modified by the word `mere,' which (the 1987
Supreme Court decisions) considered crucial.''
   In the appeal acted on today, Oklahoma prosecutors argued, ``The
Constitution does not require sympathy in capital sentencing.''
   They added, ``No reasonable juror would interpret the admonition
to avoid the influence of sympathy as a secret code designed to
denigrate the defendant's case in mitigation.''
   The case is Saffle vs. Parks, 88-1264.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
