<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Pension     04-24 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Pension,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Won't Hear Appeal on Limiting Pension Benefits for Retired
Union Officer in San Francisco Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear an
appeal by a labor union seeking to limit pension benefits for one
of its retired officers.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the retired
official did not wait too long to file a federal lawsuit in San
Francisco seeking increased benefits.
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers (IAM) amended its retirement benefit plan effective Jan. 1,
1977.
   The change, designed to save money and protect the plan's
future, eliminated a so-called ``living pension'' feature.
   It had guaranteed retired union officials they would receive
pension increases equal to any future salary hikes for the position
from which they retired.
   The union, as employer, funds the pension plan.
   The elimination of the living pension feature was challenged by
Frank Meagher, who had been a union officer for 20 years when he
reitred July 1, 1977.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last September that
Meagher is entitled to the benefits of the living pension feature.
   The appeals court said the the elimination of the feature has
not taken legal effect under the federal Employee Retirement Income
Security Act because it never has been approved by the U.S.
Secretary of the Treasury.
   Therefore, the appeals court said, Meagher did not miss the
deadline for suing over the feature's elimination even though he
did not sue until May 13, 1986.
   The appeals court said Meagher is entitled to any pension
increases that would take effect under the living pension feature
from May 13, 1983, onward.
   IAM officials, who said Meagher is receiving a monthly pension
check of about $2,700, said the ruling could be extremely costly
and damaging for pension plans generally.
   Pension benefit plan changes ``made in good faith could be the
subject of expensive litigation decades after they were made,'' the
union said.
   The appeal acted on today was supported by several business
groups, including the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
   The case is International Association of Machinists vs. Meagher,
88-1427.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
