<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0502 04-24 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0502,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Shell Near Power Plant While French Tanker Unloads Fuel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with rockets falling near tanker;
picks up 2nd pvs: An aide...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian rockets exploded near a power
plant in Lebanon's besieged Christian heartland today as a nearby
French tanker unloaded fuel needed to reactivate Beirut's power
stations, police said.
   A spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the four
rockets hit 1.5 miles north of the power plant at Zouk.
   Despite the attack, no casualties or damage was reported as the
French naval vessel, the Penhors, unloaded the desperately needed
fuel oil at the Zouk port.
   Earlier, Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun ordered two
Cypriot ferries to stop sailing to Lebanon today, suspending the
Christians' only escape route while the Penhors unloaded its
precious cargo.
   An aide to Aoun said France demanded ferry service be halted
while the Penhors unloads the fuel needed to restore electricity to
Beirut after a nine-day blackout.
   ``That's the deal worked out by France to strip the Syrian army
and its Druse allies from any pretext for shelling the Christian
enclave,'' said the aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Aoun ordered the ferry service halted Sunday night as the
Cypriot-flagged Baroness M headed to the port of Jounieh, 12 miles
north of Beirut. An Associated Press reporter aboard the 4,000-ton
ferry said the vessel turned back to Larnaca, Cyprus.
   Baroness M and another Cypriot ship, the Larnaca Rose, have
shuttled about 15,000 people from Lebanon since the latest round of
fighting began March 8.
   At least 270 people have been killed and 975 wounded in fighting
between Aoun's 20,000-strong army and allied Syrian troops and
Druse militiamen. Residential areas in Beirut have been bombarded
by rocket and artillery attacks. Most of those killed or wounded
have been civilians.
   Asked how long the ferry service would be suspended, Aoun's aide
said: ``That depends on how long the Penhors will stay in Lebanese
territorial waters.''
   The French ship unloaded 2,000 tons of fuel at the Zahrani oil
harbor, 30 miles south of Beirut, on Sunday to restart a power
plant in nearby Druse-controlled Jiye.
   The tanker docked today at Zouk in the Christian heartland north
of Beirut to unload 4,000 tons of fuel for the power plant there.
   Mitri Nammar, the electricity authority director, said it would
take Penhors nine hour to unload the fuel at Zouk.
   He said the authority will rotate electric supplies among Beirut
districts, providing each with two hours of power every 24 hours.
He said he also expected the water authority to restart the pumping
system on a rotating basis.
   Beirut has been without electricity and water since April 16
when fuel tanks ran dry. Residents also are suffering from acute
shortages of food.
   Christian-controlled radio stations said Syrian gunners lobbed
18 artillery shells on the coast north of the Christian port of
Byblos overnight. They said there were no casualties from the
intermittent firing on the region 19 miles north of Beirut.
   Each side has accused the other of using the recent relative
lull in the warfare to prepare for a major escalation to coincide
with an emergency Arab League meeting on Wednesday in the Tunisia.
   The meeting was scheduled after three cease-fires called by the
Arab League failed to halt the fighting, which broke out after Aoun
clamped a blockade on illegal militia-run ports.
   Aoun, head of a military Cabinet vying for legitimacy against a
mostly Moslem Cabinet under acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, had
said the bloackade was designed to restore state authority eroded
by 14 years of civil war.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party,
which fields a 7,000-strong militia, responded to the blockade by
shelling Christian residential areas.
   The Syrian forces later joined in the shelling, allied with the
Druse.
</TEXT>
