<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     04-24 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirteen Killed in Factional Fighting near Durban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three days of factional
fighting and firebomb attacks in black townships left 13 dead and
three injured, police said today.
   Three men died Friday in Kwamashu, 12 miles from the Indian
Ocean port of Durban, while in the adjoining township of Inanda,
police on Sunday found the bodies of nine men with head and stab
wounds, according to a police report.
   Also near Durban, a 26-year-old man was apparently stabbed to
death in Taylor's Halt, a black community in Pietermaritzburg,
according to the report issued in Pretoria, the capital.
   In Inanda, two men and a woman were hospitalized in critical
condition with stab wounds, the report said. In the same city,
shops and a bus were set alight in firebombings and two men were
arrested after police traded gunfire with black activists.
   The violence occurred near KwaZulu, where more than 1,000 Zulu
tribesmen have died in fighting among black groups.
   Monitoring groups say, in all, more than 4,000 blacks have died
since unrest against the apartheid race segregation policy broke
out in 1984.
   Durban police said Monday a third group, the Sinyoras gang,
entered the factional fighting during the weekend. The Sinyoras,
named for a song performed by South African singer Brenda Fassie,
reportedly fought United Democratic Front followers who were
protesting the fatal stabbing of a colleague.
   On Sunday, Inkatha leader and KwaZulu black homeland leader,
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, called for a foreign-funded peace campaign to
end fighting between his followers and militant anti-apartheid
groups. The United Front and allied African National Congress view
Buthelezi as a conservative who weakens the struggle for black
rights.
   Both Inkatha and the Democratic Front oppose the apartheid
policies that enable South Africa's 5 million whites to dominate 28
million blacks. But their strategies differ markedly.
   In its early stages, the factional feud focused on allegations
that Inkatha engaged in forced recruitment drives and that
Democratic Front followers sometimes coerced people into joining
anti-apartheid boycotts. More recently, killings have been revenge
attacks or pre-emptive strikes.
</TEXT>
