<SECOND>PM-Cat Woman,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Police Believe The Cat Woman Burglar Is Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burglar known as Cat Woman, who has visited the
city annually for a decade and lifted about $1 million in cash,
jewelry and heirlooms from a half-dozen homes last year, may be on
the prowl again, police say.
   ``She called me last month and said she'd be back in town
soon,'' Detective R.L. Lindsey said. ``She said she would stop by
to see me, but she hasn't.''
   The woman, whose many aliases include the name Alice L. McGraw,
is known for her bold style, impeccable taste in other's jewelry
and a steady alibi if caught _ she tells people she's looking for
her lost Siamese cat.
   She's been caught several times and convicted once, in 1983, but
was deported to her native Canada instead of being sent to jail,
police said.
   Police said the 35-year-old woman prefers to enter homes that
are open, usually looking for people working outside who haven't
bothered to lock up, but she's not above breaking in.
   Last year, police suspected her in at least six burglaries, but
she was never picked up.
   ``She comes this way in the springtime, when people are outside
in their yards,'' Lindsey said.
   In two cases since April 13, a woman matching the description of
the Cat Woman was seen near homes that had been broken into or
burglarized.
   Elizabeth Evins said she returned home and saw a woman walk
calmly down her driveway, pause to pull a leaf off a tree, then
turn a corner and walk out of sight. Then Ms. Evins got out of her
car and heard her burglar alarm.
   Ms. Evins found her back door pried open but nothing disturbed
inside.
   ``She is just as bold as you please,'' Ms. Evins said. ``She
walked right by me and didn't even flinch. She's a cool customer.''
</TEXT>
