<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0511,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seventeen Palestinians Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with 10 more injruies, clash
with settlers; picks up 4th pvs: In Jerusalem...; DELETES grafs 15-19 pvs,
`Hospitals in ... on Sunday.' to eliminate older material and tighten;
no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers wounded 17 Palestinians in the
occupied lands today, hospitals reported, and Arab residents said
Jewish settlers smashed windows in the West Bank city of Hebron
after their buses were stoned by youths.
   An army spokesman confirmed ``a couple of Israelis'' attacked
cars and shops in Hebron after the settlers' buses were pelted by
stones during a visit to a Jewish religious site in the area.
   Arab reporters said windows were smashed in at least 15 cars,
and a Hebron shopkeeper, Marwan Abu Ghalyoun, said six stores in
the city were damaged by settlers.
   ``Some youths stoned the bus, and most of the settlers in the
buses got out carrying clubs and iron bars and started smashing the
cars parked in the street,'' he said. ``I went to one settler and
tried to stop him from smashing my car, but one soldier ordered me
back to my shop so I turned back.''
   An army spokesman, who is not identified under military
regulations, said soldiers tried to break up the confrontation and
were themselves attacked by the Israelis. He said several Israelis
were arrested.
   There were no injuries in the incident, he said, but the army
declared a curfew on the city of 79,000.
   Most of the gunshot wounds reported by Arab hospitals today came
from clashes in five refugee camps in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   Six of the injuries came in early morning clashes, and the rest
later in the day, hospital officials and Arab reporters said. The
confrontations with soldiers followed a day of widespread clashes
Sunday in which 53 Palestinians were reported shot and wounded.
   Military officials could not confirm any of the injuries today,
but reported that soldiers killed a Palestinian late Sunday during
a raid on a West Bank village. The army confirmed four of the 53
wounded reported Sunday by Arab hospital officials.
   In Jerusalem, a Cabinet minister from the left-leaning Labor
Party today praised the PLO for blocking efforts by radical
Palestinian factions to further incite last week's rioting in
neighboring Jordan.
   Moshe Shahal, minister for energy, told army radio today that
the PLO blocked the distribution of leaflets aimed at undermining
King Hussein. Eight people were killed in Jordan during four days
of rioting over government price increases.
   Shahal said the action shows the PLO plays a central role in the
occupied lands, and in Jordan and Lebanon, and called on Israel to
formulate a clear response to the aims of the Palestinians.
   His comments reflect a split in Israel's coalition government
over whether to negotiate with the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir says Israel will never hold talks
with the PLO but several Labor Party ministers recently have urged
a change in Israel's stand.
   Shamir has called for holding elections in the West Bank and
Gaza to choose Palestinians to negotiate an interim peace treaty
with Israel.
   The PLO reportedly has countered with a proposal for elections
in the occupied lands for members of the Palestine National
Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile.
   This would amount to indirect recognition of the PLO.
   The army today confirmed the death of 24-year-old Amjad
el-Mamani from the village of Deir Sudan near Ramallah. Arab
reporters said he was killed Sunday night when soldiers fired on
youths throwing stones.
   An army spokesman said: ``There was a search for weapons and
people engaged in terrorism. Three were captured and escaped, and
in the course of recapturing them, one was killed.''
   The death brought to 444 the number of Palestinians killed in
the uprising. Eighteen Israelis also have been killed.
</TEXT>
