<FIRST>u a PM-UMW-Pittston     04-24 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UMW-Pittston,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 1,000 Block Mines As UMW Strike Widens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 United Mine Workers
blocked two mines and a coal plant today as the union escalated its
3-week-old strike against the Pittston Coal Group. The union also
walked off the job at a second company.
   UMW officials said miners, their spouses and retirees who began
blocking the Pittston mine and plant entrances before dawn would
remain until removed by police.
   ``We're going to let our rear ends touch the asphalt and we're
not going to move,'' said Marty Hudson, executive assistant to UMW
Vice President Cecil Roberts. ``We're going to let the county feed
us awhile.''
   Also today, about 750 miners stopped work at Westmoreland Coal
Co. by opting en masse to take days off allowed in their contract,
the union said.
   UMW District 28 President Jackie Stump said union President
Richard Trumka called the work stoppage at Westmoreland's Virginia
mines, in part because the company is suspected of filling coal
orders for strike-hobbled Pittston.
   Some 1,400 Pittston employees in Virginia and 300 in West
Virginia went on strike April 5, accusing the company of unfair
practices during contract talks. The miners had been working
without a contract since February 1988.
   ``Each and every company is going to be looked at whether or not
they're filling Pittston's orders,'' Stump said. ``If they are, we
consider it to be a conspiracy to break the union.''
   Steve Anderson, spokesman for Westmoreland, said the mass use of
personal days was ``unfortunate.'' He denied Westmoreland was
filling Pittston orders.
   ``We and Pittston are highly, highly competitive with each
other,'' Anderson said. ``It's highly unlikely that Pittston would
ask us to fill their contracts.''
   The union said the stoppage at Westmoreland would last through
Wednesday as each miner takes three personal days off. Under their
contract, each worker gets 10 a year.
   Outside the Pittston plant and mines, many strikers rid
themselves of all forms of identification to prepare for arrest.
   State Police and company guards looked on from across the street.
</TEXT>
