<HEAD>Thunderstorms Diminish After Causing Tornadoes, Hail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead and SUBS 7th graf, `Advisories for...', with 2 grafs
to UPDATE with detail on early morning low temperatures.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold-weather records fell this morning along the Atlantic Coast
and in the Ohio Valley. Rain and thunderstorms were scattered
across the country after spawning tornadoes in the Plains and
pelting California and Illinois with hail.
   Eight tornadoes touched down in Kansas and Nebraska on Sunday
afternoon, and storms winds caused some minor damage near McCook,
Neb. There were no reports of injuries.
   Other storms dropped three-quarter inch hail near Dongola, Ill.,
and at Honcut, Calif.
   The storms diminished in strength during the evening.
   By this morning, showers and thunderstorms were continuing in
parts of Texas, South Carolina, Montana, Alabama and northern
California. Rain and occasional thunderstorms were scattered from
central Tennessee across parts of Kentucky, Illinois, Iowa,
Minnesota, Montana and Oregon.
   Snow was scattered over central New Hampshire, but no
significant accumulations were reported.
   Overnight low temperatures dipped to the 20s and 30s, and even
the high teens in places, from the upper Great Lakes and Ohio
Valley to the Atlantic Coast from New Jersey to New England.
   Record low temperature records for the date were set this
morning in Atlantic City, N.J., where it dipped to 26, 8 degrees
below the 1956 recrod; and Youngstown, Ohio, where it was 27, 1
degree under than the 1980 record.
   Temperatures were expected to soar again in Texas and the
Plains, where the nation's hot spot Sunday with a high of 105
degrees was Salina, Kan.
   Today's forecast called for showers and a few thundershowers
from the central Pacific Coast to the northern Rockies, with snow
over higher elevations of Montana. Showers and thunderstorms were
expected to be scattered from the middle Mississippi Valley across
the lower Ohio Valley to the North Carolina coast. Widely scattered
showers and thunderstorms were expected to develop during the
afternoon and evening from west central Texas to the lower Missouri
Valley.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 60s, 70s or 80s across much of
the nation; in the 50s from the northern half of California to the
northern Rockies, and from the upper Great Lakes to southern New
England; in the 40s over much of Nevada, north central Montana and
northern New England; and in the low to mid 90s from the Rio Grande
Valley to the central Plains.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 20 degrees at Watertown,
N.Y., to 85 degrees at Altus, Okla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 65 partly cloudy; Boston 39 cloudy; Buffalo 34
fair; Charleston, S.C. 64 foggy; Cincinnati 51 fair; Cleveland 31
fair; Detroit 37 partly cloudy; Miami 72 fair; New York 40 fair;
Philadelphia 40 fair; Pittsburgh 38 fair; Portland, Maine 30 fair;
Washington 47 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 58 cloudy; Chicago 50 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
70 windy; Denver 50 fair; Des Moines 60 foggy; Indianapolis 52
fair; Kansas City 66 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 55 partly cloudy;
Nashville 64 partly cloudy; New Orleans 61 fair; St. Louis 62 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 62 cloudy; Anchorage 41 cloudy; Las Vegas 62
windy; Los Angeles 52 partly cloudy; Phoenix 71 fair; Salt Lake
City 46 fair; San Diego 59 partly cloudy; San Francisco 49 partly
cloudy; Seattle 49 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 34 cloudy; Toronto 27 fair.
</TEXT>
