<SECOND>PM-Jordan-Unrest, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0515,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordan's Riot Debris Is Swept Away, But Not Complaints</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates 6th graf pvs ``They blame...'' with King Hussein reportedly
accepting prime minister's resignation.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of burnt cars and shattered
window frames are being cleared from the streets of Jordan's
riot-swept southern towns.
   But people say the anger that brought four days of violence last
week because of government-imposed austerity measures will not
disappear so easily.
   Jordan has in recent years escaped most of the Middle East's
turmoil so last week's outbreak of discontent came as a shock.
   ``The rioters want things to get better in Jordan,'' said a
25-year-old man from the city of Kerak who said he was among the
stone-throwers who attacked government buildings and banks.
   Residents interviewed during a two-day tour of the south said
they want a rollback on the price increases that set off the riots,
a new government and an investigation into corruption.
   They blame Prime Minister Zaid Rifai for the economic crisis and
have called for his ouster. Sources said Rifai offered to step down
and King Hussein today accepted his resignation. There was no
official announcement.
   The riots, in which least eight people were killed, started in
Maan. The city's downtown area is now a blight of twisted
electricity pylons, severed tree limbs and burnt rubber tires.
   Soldiers in armored personnel carriers enforce the calm. There
have been no recent confrontations and a 24-hour curfew has been
eased to allow people to buy food.
   But authorities are still cautious.
   Vehicles passing on the main north-south Desert Highway are all
flagged down, and a reporter who turned off the road was escorted
back.
   Elsewhere in the region, soldiers riding jeeps mounted with
machine guns patrol the streets of the larger towns.
   Government institutions at even the smallest crossroads were not
spared in the outbreak of violence. The eight-room schoolhouse in
the hamlet of Athween was sacked, its little desks spread out in
the dirt courtyard outside.
   In Buysara, a burned Toyota Land Cruiser and dirt roadblocks
marked the village entrance.
   The roads around the town of Shobak were studded by uprooted
roadsigns and boulders rolled into place by protesters.
   Residents of Shobak said they were particularly angered when
local press reports passed off the first riots, in Maan on Tuesday,
with a one-sentence reference to a demonstration by taxi drivers
against the 25 percent increase in the price of gasoline.
   ``The government first said it was just the drivers' problem.
The drivers' problem is one out of 100,'' said Ibrahim, a
government employee who did not want to use his family name.
   The government raised prices between 10 percent and 50 percent
on cigarettes, gasoline and other commodities as part of an
agreement with the International Monetary Fund to help reschedule
Jordan's $6 billion foreign debt.
   Shobak residents said the riot started with three or four
villagers on the main street denouncing the price increases. The
three or four swelled to three or four hundred, and the anger
mounted.
   Town headman Hussein Tayat expressed the citizens' feelings this
way: ``They (the government) are thieves.''
   In the town of about 14,000, at least 40 percent of the people
are without a regular source of income, he said, adding: ``How can
they live?''
   Young men gathered behind the headman chimed in as he talked.
   ``Put the embezzlers before the judge.''
   ``Bring the money back from Geneva.''
   ``We are not against the king, just the corrupt policies.''
   Said Ibrahim: ``We had so much money coming into the country,
where did it go?''
   Residents discount charges that the riots were fomented by
underground opposition to the government.
   ``The beginning of the riots were from the people, not political
movements,'' said the Kerak resident.
   There was no need to organize, said a telephone clerk in
Buysara. ``The prices went up in all places.''
   He said government employees living on an average of 100 dinars
($185) a month were painfully aware of each price increase.
   The rioters are a little ashamed of the damage, but as the Kerak
man put it, it was necessary ``to scold the government.''
   Elsewhere in Jordan, shock was mixed with support.
   ``It's strange for Jordan, it's a small country, it's all one
family,'' said Abdul Razak Tubeshat, mayor of the northern town of
Irbid. ``We discuss, we don't destroy.''
   But an Amman man who would not give his name enumerated his
grievances at living on 80 dinars ($148) a month.
   ``I feel like rioting,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
