<FIRST>r i AM-Kadar     04-24 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kadar,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Party Leader's Health Worsens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The health of former Communist Party
leader Janos Kadar has worsened, the foreign minister said Monday,
without disclosing the nature of the ailment.
   Kadar, 76, was replaced as party leader by Karoly Grosz in May
1988 after 32 years in power. Kadar was given the honorary post of
party president.
   Foreign Minister Gyula Horn said on Hungarian state radio that
Kadar's ``physical and mental state of health had worsened.'' He
was quoted as saying the ailment was ``an irreversible process.''
   On Saturday, Minister of State Rezsoe Nyers said Kadar was not
able to perform his functions in the honorary post.
   He said his appearance at a recent Central Committee session may
have been Kadar's ``last such appearance,'' according to the news
agency MTI and state TV.
   Kadar has come increasingly under criticism for halting
Hungary's reforms in the 1970s and for his role in the 1968 Warsaw
Pact invasion that crushed Czechoslovakia's ``Prague Spring''
reforms.
</TEXT>
