<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0557 04-24 1078</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0557,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Decries `Declinists;' Says America Won't Be Reined In</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 4 grafs from Q&amp;A after 16th graf pvs, Quayle said</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice president Dan Quayle, leaving on a whirlwind
trip to Australia and Southeast Asia, said today the United States
intends to remain a Pacific power despite arguments by
``declinists'' that the nation ``must pull back from our global
commitments.''
   Rather, he told the annual meeting of The Associated Press, the
challenge for the United States is to advance ``our strategic and
economic interest in Asia while maintaining our continuing
commitments to Europe.''
   He said that in the United States and its Pacific allies, there
is an undercurrent of gloominess, with some observers _ he did not
name any _ predicting a grim future for the United States.
   ``The United States, they say, is a nation in decline. The
budget deficit and the trade deficit are symptoms of a deeper
malaise. ... If we are to avoid disaster, we must pull back from
our global commitments.
   ``In a nutshell, this ... is the argument of the so-called
`declinists.'''
   So, Quayle said, an important purpose of his 12-day trip ``is to
address these concerns head-on. I will be reminding our Asian
friends that the current wave of declinist thought in the United
States is hardly a new phenomenon.''
   Yet, Quayle said, when Americans express doubt about the health
of the American society, ``it's usually a sign of renewal, not of
decline.'' By recognizing the country's problems, the United States
is spurred to take remedial action, he said.
   As for defense, Quayle said the United States will continue to
``pursue a vigorous security role in Asia.''
   He said the Soviet Union, recognizing the failure of its
economic system, is looking toward Asia. Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev is due to visit China next month for the first
Sino-Soviet summit meeting in 20 years.
   ``We recognize the Soviet interest in sharing in Asia's economic
boom and in increasing its access to the region. But Moscow has a
long way to go to achieve this goal,'' he said.
   He said Moscow continues to modernize its military force
capabilities in Asia and the Pacific, where the largest of the
Soviet fleets remains stationed.
   With the emergence of Asian nations, Quayle said, the challenge
to the United States is to advance ``our strategic and economic
interests in Asia while maintaining our continuing commitments to
Europe.''
   He said, ``I'm going to the Pacific because the United States is
a great power, because the United States is a Pacific power and
because we intend to play an important role in the Pacific.''
   He told the AP meeting that, ``like the president, I recognize
that our future, and the future of the Pacific rim nations, are
closely entwined. That is why the United States is focusing on the
region as never before.''
   He noted that the Asian nations have thriving free enterprise
economies, with the members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations making up what would be the United States' seventh largest
trading partner.
   Quayle said the United States will engage in bilateral efforts
necessary for opening foreign markets to U.S. goods and services.
Open and free trade are the hallmark of a U.S. policy needed to
``promote our competitiveness and the welfare of the American
people,'' he said.
   Answering questions after his speech, Quayle said his biggest
surprise since taking office was how much he enjoys overseas travel.
   The vice president, who visited Central and South America soon
after he was inaugurated, said most of his trips as senator had
been back home to Indiana.
   He also said he had been in daily close contact with President
Bush. ``I see how he formulates his policies,'' Quayle said. ``I'm
there to give my opinion.''
   And, asked if embattled House Speaker Jim Wright should step
down while fighting ethics charges, Quayle answered, ``Jim Wright
will make that decision.''
   On his trip to Asia, Quayle will mix substantive policy
discussions, particularly dealing with trade and defense, with
ceremonial duties and tourism.
   Flying to Asia, he wil pay a courtesy call on former President
Reagan in Los Angeles. On the return trip, the vice president plans
to tour Alaska's wildlife-rich Prince William Sound to see for
himself the cleanup efforts following the Exxon Valdez oil spill.
   Besides Australia, Quayle will visit Indonesia, Singapore and
Thailand.
   Quayle, accompanied by his wife, Marilyn, will spend five days
in Australia representing President Bush at this year's celebration
of Australian-American Friendship Week.
   In talks with Australian officials in Canberra, the vice
president will explore bilateral issues such as trade, defense and
space cooperation, aide David Beckwith said. said. As chairman of
the National Space Council, Quayle is charged with promoting
advancement of the U.S. space program.
   The Quayles will also do some sightseeing, visiting the Great
Barrier Reef, the coral reefs that abound with marine life off
Australia's northeast corner. The site is one of the country's most
popular tourist attractions.
   The visit to Jakarta, Indonesia, is mostly a chance for Quayle
to get acquainted with the heavily populated island nation, which,
like Singapore and Thailand, is a member of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations, Beckwith said.
   Trade issues are at the top of Quayle's list in talking with
leaders of the ASEAN nations, Beckwith said. In the past, the
United States has urged Asian nations to end the high tariffs and
import restrictions that stifle free trade.
   The vice president also plans to meet with Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, Cambodia's former head of state and leader of one of four
factions vying for power in that country, in his 1{ days in Jakarta.
   Indeed, a key theme on Quayle's agenda is Cambodia, a
war-ravaged country whose future remains uncertain. The United
States is weighing whether to provide military assistance to
non-communist factions after Vietnam ends its 10-year occupation of
the country this fall.
   ``We're talking Cambodia heavily in Thailand and to some extent
in all the countries because if there is any policy development
it's going to be in the Cambodia position because it's wide open
now,'' Beckwith said.
   In Thailand, the vice president will tour a Cambodian refugee
camp populated by people who fled their country, some during the
brutal Khmer Rouge regime between 1975-1978.
   Earlier this year, Quayle, a former Indiana senator, visited
several countries in Latin and Central America on his first foreign
mission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
