<FIRST>r a PM-ColoFires     04-24 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colo Fires,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heat, Wind Worsen Rash Of Forest And Brush Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters in sweltering Colorado mopped up hot
spots today after a weekend of wildfires, but one blaze continued
to burn out of control.
   Denver hit a record high Sunday of 85 degrees, and the heat,
coupled with strong wind and low humidity, heightened the danger of
fire, officials said.
   The Forest Service on Sunday banned campfires on 2.1 million
acres of the two national forests on the Front Range south of
Denver.
   ``It's just extremely dry,'' said Charlie Knight, a Forest
Service fire information officer. ``Until we get some rain, people
have just got to be careful or we're going to have a tragedy _
either loss of life or loss of structures.''
   Since Friday, six brush or forest fires broke out from Pikes
Peak west of Colorado Springs to Boulder County northwest of Denver.
   Five fires were reported contained or nearly contained Sunday
and had caused no injuries or damage to buildings. The largest
blaze was an 872-acre forest fire near Monument. ``There is not
even a wisp of smoke coming up now,'' Knight said.
   However, a blaze that charred some 50 acres near Morrison
continued to burn out of control today, Knight said. The Jefferson
County Sheriff's Department said visitors to nearby Mount Falcon
State Park were asked to leave.
   Authorities said that a 600-acre brush fire in Denver may have
been set and that the other blazes may have been caused by humans
unintentionally.
</TEXT>
