<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--Old-GrowthTimber     04-24 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Old-Growth Timber,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giant Log For Conservation Drive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-ton log from a tree that started growing
more than 700 years ago is being hauled across the country and back
to call attention to the plight of the nation's old-growth forests.
   The Ancient Forest Rescue Expedition set out Saturday with the
731-year-old Douglas fir log on a month-long journey to Washington,
D.C., and then back to Portland, Ore., by May 19.
   Rick Bailey of Joseph, Ore., who will do most of the driving,
said he hopes the log will inspire people to pressure political
leaders into protecting old-growth forest. He said less than 10
percent of Oregon's old-growth timber remains.
   ``This thing was growing there in the forest before Marco Polo
set sail for China,'' said expedition organizer Mitch Friedham of
Bellingham, Wash.
   The 20-foot log, more than seven feet wide, was legally cut on
U.S. Forest Service property on the Olympic Peninsula.
Environmentalists later bought it for $3,950.
</TEXT>
