<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Malawi-Flooding     04-24 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Malawi-Flooding,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>Renewed Flooding Hits Northern Malawi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New flooding in northern Malawi
destroyed the homes of tens of thousands of people, washed away
crops and drowned livestock, the government said Monday.
   About 200,000 people are homeless following storms since January
in this nation in southern Africa, according to the Disaster
Preparedness Committee.
   In one northern district, people took refuge on makeshift
platforms built on roofs of their flooded houses.
   Government officials and international aid agency
representatives visited the worst-hit province of Karonga, which
borders Tanzania.
   Torrential rains in January and Februrary left 115,000 people
homeless, mainly in southern provinces, the government said. At
that time, flooding destroyed crops, roads, bridges and rail lines,
and the government appealed for $28 million in foreign aid for
emergency repairs and food.
</TEXT>
