<FIRST>r a PM-MarketShooting     04-24 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market Shooting,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Man Convicted in Supermarket Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted today of murdering five
people during a 1987 supermarket hold-up by two gunmen who police
say posed as a cleaning crew to get in after hours.
   Donnie Blankenship, 27, was found guilty of five counts of
second-degree murder, robbery, unlawful use of a weapon and
receiving stolen property. He could receive up to 30 years in
prison on each murder charge.
   The jury, which began deliberating on Saturday, refused to
convict him of first-degree murder, which carries a possible death
penalty.
   Six store employees and a security guard were shot as they lay
on the floor during the robbery. Two of the employees who had been
left for dead survived and testified.
   In September, Marvin Jennings, 27, of Overland, was convicted in
the slayings and was sentenced to five consecutive life terms
without parole for first-degree murder. Prosecutors had sought the
death penalty.
   In his closing arguments, special prosecutor Garrett L. Randall
called Blankenship a ``cold-blooded killer.''
</TEXT>
