<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-North     04-24 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-North,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Dismisses Speculation about Whether He Would Pardon North</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD AIR FORCE ONE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday he has
not talked with anyone about whether he would pardon fired White
House aide Oliver North and that any suggestions about what he'll
do are ``stupid'' and ``idiotic''
   Bush said he has not had any conversations, direct or indirect,
about whether he would pardon North, who is awaiting a verdict from
jurors on charges stemming from the diversion of Iran arms sales
profits to the icaraguan Contras.
   The president made the comments in a question-and-answer session
with five reporters accompanying him on a flight from Norfolk, Va.
to Chicago.
   In the past, Bush has called North a hero and said he hoped
North would be acquitted.
   He was asked about a report in Newsweek magazine quoting sources
close to him as predicting he would never pardon North, onetime
aide on the National Security Council in Ronald Reagan's White
House.
   ``That's interesting speculation,'' Bush said. ``It shows how
stupid some reports are because that matter has never been
discussed with me by anybody, including my wife.
   ``It shows you how idiotic speculation is. If it was given any
credence as having come from me or as if somebody had discussed it
with me, they simply haven't,'' he said.
   Told that the report quoted sources as merely predicting what
Bush would do, he said, ``Oh well, that's a different story.
   ``I haven't discussed it nor shared my thoughts with anybody. I
don't have any thoughts until I get the facts,'' Bush said.
   A reporter suggested that as a practical matter, the president
might be reluctant to get involved while the legal process was
going forward.
   ``That's got it. You've got it,'' he said.
   Asked if he would talk about the matter after a verdict, Bush
said ``Maybe ... when everything's over.''
</TEXT>
