<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Karajan     04-24 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Karajan,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed Conductor Resigns From Berlin Philharmonic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert von Karajan, the renowned
conductor of the Berlin Philharmonic for 35 years, announced Monday
he was resigning because of failing health.
   In a letter to West Berlin authorities, the 81-year-old maestro
said his medical problems ``make it impossible for me to fulfill my
obligations'' and complained that Berlin officials had failed to
make clear what they expected of him.
   Berlin's cultural affairs senator, Anke Martiny, said Karajan
informed her of his decision in a letter received Monday from his
home in Salzburg, Austria, where the conductor has been confined by
his illnesses.
   ``The results of the medical examinations, which now have
stretched for weeks, make it impossible for me to fulfill my
obligations,'' he said in the letter released in Salzburg, where he
was born.
   Karajan's resignation leaves open one of the most coveted
conductor's posts in the world.
   ``I respect this decision by Herbert von Karajan, which comes
for health reasons,'' Ms. Martiny told The Associated Press.
   ``I hope that Karajan's friends in Berlin will have one more
opportunity to see him conducting the Berlin Philharmonic'' in a
farewell performance, Ms. Martiny said.
   Karajan's letter said that despite repeated requests, the former
Berlin administration had failed to make clear what his rights and
responsibilities as ``conductor for life'' involved.
   ``I must also point out that for years I have asked your
predecessors to finally make clear my duties and rights,'' Karajan
wrote to Ms. Martiny, a Social Democrat who has been cultural
senator for two months. ``Although I have asked repeatedly, to date
this has not come forth.''
   Ursula Vogel, an aide to Ms. Martiny, said the decision on a
successor would be made by the orchestra administration, with the
choice to be confirmed by Berlin officials.
   No one at the Berlin Philharmonic office was available to
discuss possible replacements for Karajan, said a man who answered
the telephone Monday.
   Two names Karajan himself has mentioned as potential successors
are Soviet-born Semyon Bychkov and Italy's Carlo Maria Giulini.
   Karajan has long been in poor health, having suffered a stroke,
failing vision, chronic back problems and circulatory problems. He
has undergone at least five operations in the past 12 years and has
been visibly hindered since undergoing surgery in 1983.
   He walks with difficulty and has required a supporting chair
behind the conducting pulpit for more than two years.
   He has canceled a number of performances over the past few years
and become increasingly reclusive, venturing from his Salzburg home
infrequently.
   The absences exacerbated criticism of the conductor, who has
long been the subject of controversy because of his Nazi Party
membership during Adolf Hitler's Third Reich and the reputedly
lavish terms of his contract.
   The West German weekly magazine Der Spiegel has said Karajan
earns more than $6 million a year from his recordings, as well as
his salary from the state-supported Berlin Philharmonic.
   Karajan wrote to Berlin authorities in February asking that they
ease his contractual obligations because of his poor state of
health.
   The cultural affairs department agreed to reduce the conductor's
schedule from 12 concerts per year to six. But Karajan has not
returned to Berlin to conduct the orchestra since the revision was
agreed to.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
