<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Education     04-24 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Education,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Drugs Preeminent Problem Plaguing Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in a television interview
broadcast Monday night, said the three most pressing problems
facing America's school are ``drugs, drugs and drugs.''
   ``I hope that's not a frivolous answer,'' he said, ``but I want
to say it that way because of the impact that drugs are having.
They have it on the morale of teachers. They have it on discipline
in the classroom. They have ... the adverse impact on the areas
that need help the most.''
   Bush was interviewed for the fifth and last segment of
``Learning In America,'' a television series that concluded Monday
night on most Public Broadcasting Service stations.
   Bush said he intends to be ``the education president'' despite
limited federal resources, mainly by giving moral support to the
teachers, parents, states and cities that run the nation's schools.
   ``A lot of what a president can do is hortatory, encourage the
people that have the ... main responsibility for education,'' Bush
told PBS correspondent Roger Mudd.
   The president said he is trying to leave his mark on education
despite the limits on federal aid and authority in the area because
``education holds the key. It holds the key to a better life for
our young people, and it holds the key to the United States being
competitive in world markets. And it holds the key to whipping the
problem of drug abuse.''
   Bush said that teachers are ``never going to have it made... in
a financial sense'' but added that the nation must find some way to
show them ``that we respect those who choose that profession, and
find ways to encourage more to do it.''
   In response to other questions, Bush promoted his education
agenda, which calls for greater accountability on the part of
schools, more liberal teacher certification policies and letting
parents choose which public school their children attend. He said
giving parents that choice could help eliminate inequities that
affect children in disadvantaged areas.
   Bush's comment came after Mudd noted that a child in a ghetto
high school in Camden, N.J., has less than $4,000 spent on him
while $7,000 is spent on a child in affluent Princeton, N.J.
   ``The federal government can't smooth out everything like
this,'' Bush said. But he added that parental choice is one answer
to such inequities. ``They might not be able to move from Camden to
Princeton, but if we have this choice take hold, they can move into
a school that is less heavily impacted by drugs...'' he said.
   Mudd also told Bush that his presidential campaign slogan of
``Read my lips _ no new taxes'' has been picked up by state
legislators. He said at least two governors have hit a stone wall
in seeking new taxes to pay for education improvements .
   ``So now we have the phenomenon of an education president being
used as a cover to refuse to raise taxes to improve education,''
Mudd said.
   Bush replied that the federal government should ``hold the line
on taxes and not create taxes that take away from the state's
resource base. And so I would let each state governor, obviously,
make his own decision or her own decision. But I will not
criticize, nor extend the read-my-lips syndrome to every governor
that ... is mandated to balance budgets.''
</TEXT>
