<FIRST>u a PM-Fusion-Utah     04-24 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion-Utah,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fusion Team To Address Congressional Panel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Utah chemist who claimed
to have achieved nuclear fusion in a jar of water said he and his
British colleague plan a new round of experiments to expand on
their findings.
   B. Stanley Pons said one experiment will be five times larger
than the table-top apparatus he and Martin Fleischmann used.
   ``I think this round of experiments will bring up a host of new
data,'' Pons said before leaving for Washington, where he and
Fleischmann were to address a congressional committee about their
work.
   The two stunned the scientific world and provoked deep
skepticism March 23 when they announced they had developed a fusion
apparatus that produced four times the energy needed to power it.
   Fusion, the process behind the sun and the hydrogen bomb,
releases energy by fusing atoms together. Nuclear fission, the
process used in nuclear reactors, splits them apart.
   Scientists have long believed that fusion requires staggeringly
high temperatures. If Pons' claim of room temperature fusion is
borne out, it could open the door to a cheap and virtually
unlimited source of energy.
   Groups of scientists around the world have claimed to have
duplicated at least part of the experiment.
   Pons said up to 20 experiments would begin over the next two
weeks. Among them will be tests of different metals than the
palladium used in the original experiments and new designs for the
apparatus.
</TEXT>
