<FIRST>r w AM-US-NewZealand     04-24 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-New Zealand,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Zealand Leader Says He Won't `Buy' White House Invitation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Zealand Prime Minister David Lange said
Monday he is not willing to ``buy'' an invitation to the White
House at the expense of compromising his country's anti-nuclear
policies.
   Lange, on a six-day visit to the United States, said from New
Haven, Conn., that he is not coming to Washington ``because the
(U.S.) administration has been very straightforward. It's said that
the price of coming to Washington is having nuclear vessels in New
Zealand ports.''
   Lange, speaking on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show before speaking at
Yale University, said ``New Zealand would welcome (a) political
contact, but not so as to buy our route to the White House. We will
not pay the price of having a nuclear policy in New Zealand. We
won't have nuclear weapons in New Zealand.''
   New Zealand has banned visits by ships carrying nuclear weapons
or powered by atomic reactors, leading the United States in 1986 to
suspend security guarantees for the Pacific nation under terms of
the ANZUS alliance between Australia, the United States and New
Zealand.
   The United States refuses to confirm or deny the existence of
nuclear weapons on its ships and planes, a policy which has
strained its relations with several allies, including Denmark.
Lange said he was certain the U.S. measures toward New Zealand were
designed to deter other countries from adopting similar
anti-nuclear policies.
   ``I'm sure that that was the concern of the United States,''
Lange said.
   The United States ``continues to view New Zealand as a friendly
country, but not an ally,'' said a State Department official who
requested anonymity.
   In addition to the diplomatic cooling, Lange said, the United
States has stopped sharing military intelligence information with
New Zealand.
   But ``at most practical levels, we have an extraordinarily good
relationship with the United States. I relish coming here. A lot of
Americans relish going to New Zealand,'' Lange said.
   In fact, trade between the two countries, including U.S.
military sales, has increased, he said. Figures provided by the
State Department show U.S. exports to New Zealand rose from $933
million in 1986 to $1.19 billion in 1988; imports rose from $908
million to $1.23 billion in 1988.
   But department officials said the increase was independent of
strains in diplomatic relations and the United States had made a
point of not allowing general relations to be soured by the
political disagreement.
   Asked for his explanation of the strengthening economic ties
between New Zealand and the United States, Lange said ``you don't
have to have the blessing of the United States and approval of your
defense policies to make a living in this world. I think the Soviet
Union has demonstrated that.''
</TEXT>
