<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may not be in church, but it will be
a kosher wedding for a couple who plan to exchange vows before
thousands of people at the North Carolina Pickle Festival at Mount
Olive.
   Amy Rebecca Smith, 19, didn't relish the idea from her fiance,
an employee of Chas. F. Cates &amp; Sons Inc., which makes a dozen
varieties of pickles.
   ``She wanted an old-fashioned church wedding,'' said Timothy
Grady Gautier, 23.
   But the two entered a contest that sought a couple willing to
get married April 29 during the pickle festival.
   Only six couples applied, including a woman who said she would
use cucumber vines and sprigs of dill in her wedding bouquet, Miss
Smith said.
   Miss Smith's application said the two have stayed together
through hamburgers and pickles. Gautier helped Miss Smith, who
worked past midnight at her father's restaurant, Smitty's Big Tee
Chicken &amp; Burgers. He would then get up early to go to work in the
pickle-packing plant.
   ``The wedding itself is going to be traditional,'' Miss Smith
said. But jars of pickles and baskets of cucumbers will decorate
each side of the wedding platform and steps.
   William L. Hennessee Jr., president of Cates; Johnny Walker,
president of Mt. Olive Pickle; and D.F. Odom, mayor of Mount Olive,
will sign the marriage certificate as witnesses.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ Students hung up on homework can call a hot
line to plug into a teacher ready to help.
   The Jersey City School District started the hot line a year ago.
   ``I felt it was something that would be a benefit, especially
because we have so many latchkey children who don't have parents
who can help them when they come home,'' said Elaine White, the hot
line's founder and the district's affirmative action officer.
   The hot line handles queries from students in the third through
sixth grades.
   ``Math is the No. 1 question and it usually is math
computations,'' said Ms. White. ``A lot of it has to do with times
tables and what you're doing to get the answer.''
   A $20,000 state grant pays for H.E.L.P. _ the Homework and
Education Line for Parents and Students. Four teachers, including
one who speaks Spanish, field calls from 4 p.m. to 7 p.m. Tuesday
through Thursday.
   Last year the program operated from April through mid-June,
logging as many as 40 calls a day initially, said Ms. White. It
resumed in February.
   The consulting teachers are paid $14.50 an hour.
</TEXT>
