<FIRST>u i PM-Jordan 3rdld-Writethru a0512 04-24 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jordan, 3rd ld - Writethru, a0512,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hussein Accepts Prime Minister's Resignation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs, TV announces acceptance of resignation.
Picks up 5th graf pvs ``The four days... ''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein accepted the resignation of
Prime Minister Zaid Rifai and his government today following bloody
rioting over price increases.
   The monarch did not name a new prime minister, the official
Jordan Television said.
   The TV report carried an official statement saying Hussein
assigned secretaries-general of government ministries, second in
rank to appointed ministers, to run the departments until a new
government is formed.
   Sources said earlier today that Rifai, prime minister since
1985, had offered his resignation and that Hussein accepted it.
   The four days of riots, in which at least eight people died,
began Tuesday in the southern city of Maan and spread to dozens of
cities and villages throughout the kingdom.
   The official Jordan News Agency reported Sunday that Hussein had
``expressed his intention to deal with the roots of the problem and
all the reasons and causes of the latest incidents within a short
period of time.''
   Many rioters chanted slogans calling for Rifai's ouster. They
also shouted their support for the king.
   Rifai has been widely blamed for falling living standards in
Jordan. The annual per capita income has slumped from about $2,000
in the mid-1980s to about $1,200.
   The government last year imposed import controls and austerity
measures to help deal with mounting payments on a $6 billion debt.
   The rioting was triggered by 10 percent to 50 percent increases
in the prices of gasoline, cigarettes and other commodities. The
price increases were carried out under an agreement with the
International Monetary Fund to pave the way for rescheduling the
debt payments.
   Rifai, 52, was a boyhood friend of King Hussein who became one
of his most trusted advisers.
   No Jordanian prime minister served longer than Rifai. Besides
the term that began in April 1985, he also was prime minister from
1973 to 1976.
   Educated at Columbia and Harvard, Rifai earlier served as
ambassador to Britain and as chief of the royal court.
   His father, Samir, served six terms as prime minister in the
1940s, 1950s and 1960s, for a total of less than four years.
</TEXT>
