<FIRST>r a AM-KmartExplosion     04-24 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-K mart Explosion,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Who Lost Hand In Bombing To Be Hospitalized Another Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old girl maimed in a pipe bomb
explosion at a discount store a week ago probably will not be
released from the hospital for at least a week more, a hospital
spokesman said Monday.
   David Richards, a spokesman for Methodist Hospital, said Erin
Bower was in satisfactory and stable condition and eating solid
food.
   Erin's left hand was amputated after it was severely damaged
April 17, when a bomb concealed in a toothpaste container exploded
as she picked it up from a shelf at a K mart store.
   The explosion also injured Erin's left eye, but doctors said
they hoped she would regain partial vision in it.
   Surgeons planned to examine the eye again this week before
determining when Erin can return home to her parents, Kevin and
Maureen Bower of Indianapolis. Richards said it probably would be a
week to 10 days before she can leave the hospital.
   ``This past weekend, she was cheerful,'' Richards said. ``She
went to the playroom and played. Her grandparents and parents
visited with her on Sunday.''
   Meanwhile, investigators still were trying to identify two men
seen leaving the store moments after the bombing.
   ``We're still following up the 300 to 400 phone calls mentioning
names or incidents,'' said Lt. Joie Davis of the Marion County
Sheriff's Department.
   The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms planned to
bring in six out-of-state investigators this week, bringing the
total number of detectives working full time on the case to 20.
   Also, fragments from the bomb are being analyzed at a federal
crime laboratory in Rockville, Md.
   Rewards totaling more than $35,000 have been offered for
information leading to the arrest and conviction of a suspect, and
a fund also has been set up for the child.
</TEXT>
