<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MushroomWars     04-24 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mushroom Wars,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Officials Prepare For Mushroom-Picking Onslaught</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBBY, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forest fires last summer followed by a wet
winter mean a big mushroom crop, and the U.S. Forest Service says
it's working to forestall ``mushroom wars'' among pickers lured by
the potential of $600 a day.
   ``We are expecting anywhere from 3,000 to 5,000 pickers to show
up,'' said Mike Johnson, a forest service employee at the Kootenai
National Forest in the remote northwest corner of Montana.
   An experienced picker who finds a good stand of the popular
morel mushroom can take in up to 120 pounds of them a day, and gets
about $5 per pound. With that kind of money as a draw, officials
say, trouble is possible.
   When the Umatilla National Forest in Oregon had a good mushroom
crop two years ago, for example, Grant County deputies investigated
shot-up vehicles, threats and fights, said Grant undersheriff Jim
McNellis.
   ``It turned into a real zoo in some places,'' he said.
   To keep the same thing from happening in Montana this year,
Kootenai and Flathead national forest officials said they will have
more patrols out and issue permits for mushroom pickers ($5) and
buyers ($500) who set up shop in the forest.
   ``Permits will give us a little control over what is going on
and help pay for some of the increased patrols we are planning,''
Johnson said.
   Mushrooms should start sprouting in the next two to three weeks,
and the peak of the season is the end of May. The season can wrap
up as early as June, but if if it's a wet summer, it can extend
into fall, Johnson said.
   Forest fires act as catalysts for production of edible
mushrooms, primarily morels, he said. A fire in the Kootenai forest
last summer burned 13,000 acres near here, while another fire
burned about 10,000 acres in the nearby Flathead forest.
</TEXT>
