<DOCNO> AP890424-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-DaleyInauguration     04-24 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Daley Inauguration,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daley Follows Father's Footsteps</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley was sworn in as this city's 45th
mayor Monday _ his 47th birthday _ and promised he would be a
conductor who would orchestrate harmony in the city his father led
for 21 years.
   ``The old ways of doing things simply aren't adequate to cope
with the new challenges we face,'' said Daley, whose victory over
two black politicians earlier this year split voters sharply along
racial lines.
   Monday's ceremony was at Orchestra Hall, and Daley used the
setting as a theme for his speech. He said the patchwork of a city
is like a collection of instruments that can make beautiful music
only when working together.
   ``Today, I have been handed the conductor's baton, and to the
people of Chicago, wherever you live, let me assure you that your
voices will be heard,'' he said.
   Daley was sworn in by Senior U.S. District Judge Abraham Lincoln
Marovitz, who performed the same service for the late Richard J.
Daley six times before the elder Daley died in office in 1976.
   Daley, a Democrat, later took a congratulatory call from
President Bush, who was in the city to address the annual meeting
of The Associated Press.
   With Daley in office, Chicago became the largest U.S. city in
which voters have replaced a black mayor with a white.
   Daley was elected April 4 to complete the last two years of the
second term of the late Harold Washington, the first black mayor in
the nation's third-largest city. Daley succeeds Eugene Sawyer,
named acting mayor by the City Council following Washington's death
in office 17 months ago.
   Sawyer, who also is black, lost to Daley in the Democratic
primary Feb. 28. In April, Daley easily defeated black third-party
candidate Timothy Evans and Democrat-turned-Republican Edward
Vrdolyak.
   Daley's father ran a political machine fueled by Democratic
patronage, but Daley said those days are gone.
   ``You don't hand down policies from generation to generation,''
he said. But he said he shared with his father ``a love for our
city and a zest for public service.''
   Black civil rights leader Jesse Jackson, who warned while
campaigning for Sawyer and Evans that Daley would revive machine
politics, said Daley struck a positive chord in his inaugural
speech and in naming a multi-racial group last week as his first
Cabinet nominees.
   ``He appears to be using a reconciling approach as opposed to a
polarizing Daley acknowledged that he faces challenges, includeing
the tasks of providing affordable housing and running the city on a
thin budget.
   ``We can't in two years solve every problem or cure every social
ill,'' he said. ``We can only begin.'' approach, and that is
good,'' Jackson said.
   Daley and his wife have three children _ Nora, 15, Patrick, 13,
and Elizabeth, 5. A fourth child, Kevin, died of the crippling
defect spina bifida when he was 2.
   Daley served three terms in the Illinois Senate and was elected
to his third term as Cook County state's attorney last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
