<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSPORT, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-soap star Michael Damian says
he's not out to change the world, but he hopes his anti-drug
efforts will change a few young minds.
   Damian, 26, who stars on ``The Young and the Restless,'' spent
Sunday afternoon at Hills department stores signing autographs for
hundreds of fans who turned out to greet him. He was in town to
promote the chain's participation in the ``Just Say No'' program.
   ``I'm not preaching anything, but if kids see that I'm behind it
maybe they will be too,'' he said.
   Damian has recorded a remake of the song ``Rock On'' and has
been on the TV daytime drama since he was 17.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sweden's royal couple will get a new
airplane after Queen Silvia complained their old one was too
cramped for her hats and lacked adequate mirrors to fix her make-up.
   King Carl XVI Gustaf ordered a Swedish-built SAAB 340 B,
outfitted with a telephone, telex and a spacious wardrobe, palace
spokeswoman Elisabeth Tarras-Wahlberg said Monday.
   The Queen refused to fly any more in the old royal plane, a
Fairchild Metro III, Mrs. Tarras-Wahlberg said.
   ``She got fed up with the old plane, which she claimed was
uncomfortable, noisy and cramped. It even lacked mirrors so the
Queen had problems checking her make-up before leaving the plane on
state visits,'' she said.
   The commercial model of the propeller-driven SAAB normally seats
up to 50 passengers. The royal plane, which will cost over $11
million, also will be used by members of the government.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 900 people who hope to see Durham
become a national jazz center turned out for a benefit for the
Thelonious Monk Jazz Institute.
   Thomas Carter, national executive director of the Monk
Institute. Carter said Monday afternoon he had just put the last
guest celebrity, actress Bea Arthur, on a plane and had not had
time to check the receipts.
   But he said, ``It was very much a success, both from a dinner
standpoint and a student standpoint.''
   Officials staged the benefit Sunday to raise money to plan for
the institute, named for the late Rocky Mount native and pianist
known as the ``High Priest of Bebop.''
   ``Durham is where this should be,'' said Thelonious Monk Jr.,
the performer's son. ``The cultural community of the golden
Triangle is incredible _ New York is relatively dead compared to
here.'' He referred to the Raleigh, Durham, Chapel Hill area.
   The institute, planned as the first four-year undergraduate
school of jazz in the world, is to open in downtown Durham in 1991.
It will be affiliated primarily with Duke University.
   Trumpeter Wynton Marsalis headed a group of performers at
Sunday's concert featuring jazz greats Dizzy Gillespie, Hank Jones,
Slide Hampton and others. Bea Arthur and Rue McClanahan of NBC's
``The Golden Girls'' were hosts.
   About 300 dinner guests paid $250 each and 600 college and high
school students bought tickets to the event at $10 each.
   Upcoming in New York and Los Angeles are benefits for the
institute with the premiere of the Clint Eastwood movie
``Theolonious Monk: Straight, No Chaser,'' which was the title of
one of Monk's works.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher's ex-bagel baker boyfriend received no
jail time for smashing a photographer's camera, but was placed
Monday on two years' probation and sentenced to perform 300 hours
of community service and pay $1,175 in fines and court costs.
   Rob Camilletti, 24, was accused of trying to run down free-lance
photographer Peter Brandt on July 27 outside Cher's home.
   He pleaded no contest Feb. 28 to two counts of vandalism. A
reckless driving charge was dismissed at sentencing.
   Camilletti was not present in West Los Angeles Municipal Court
for the sentencing by Judge Ronald Schoenberg.
   During a news conference after the incident, Cher and Camilletti
angrily denied he tried to run down the photographer. The actress
blamed pesky paparazzi and the frustration of living in the
spotlight for the flare-up.
   Cher, 42, who won a best actress Oscar in 1988 for her role in
``Moonstruck,'' has since moved out of the Benedict Canyon home
where the incident took place.
   Camilletti, who met Cher at a New York nightclub on her 40th
birthday, could have been sentenced to one year in jail and fined
$2,000.
