<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Celeste poked fun of himself
at a ceremony Monday opening a new press room and choosing the best
cartoon of the governor.
   Kirk Walters of The Toledo Blade, whose drawings of Celeste as a
modern-day King Louis XIV of France _ with over-the-shoulder curls
and spectacles _ won first place in a ``portrait'' competition
judged by Statehouse reporters.
   Celeste referred to a half-dozen political cartoonists who
entered the nonsense competition as ``my pals around the state, who
like to skewer me.'' He said they have studied his features ``and
know me best.''
   He said he knows his features are tempting caricatures. ``If you
have a good chin, you might as well use it,'' he laughed. Walters
said Celeste, with jutting chin, has a profile ``that is easy to
draw . . . a half-moon face.''
   Gary Ness, director of the Ohio Historical Society who joined in
the one-liners, said it was the first time a governor ``ever called
such attention to himself, at least consciously.''
   Celeste held the event in a news conference room in the new
state office building, across the street from the Statehouse. He
moved his office from the capitol to new building several weeks ago.
