<FIRST>r i AM-Armenians     04-24 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armenians,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenians Hold Memorial for 1915 Genocide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Armenians on Monday observed a day of
mourning in memory of a 1915 massacre, the first time that April 24
has been recognized by the government as a holiday, Tass said.
   ``Men, women, old men and children have been marching in an
unending stream since early morning toward Tsitsernakerberd Hill,
where the memorial of sorrow and the revival of the Armenian people
rises over Yerevan,'' Tass said.
   The Supreme Soviet recently approved legislation making April 24
an official day of remembrance and a day off for workers, the news
agency said.
   ``It is for the first time this year that April 24 was marked in
Soviet Armenia officially,'' Tass said. ``Under the law of the
Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic `on denouncing the 1915 genocide
of Armenians in Osman Turkey,' the parliament of the republic has
decreed this date the day of remembrance of the victims of
genocide,'' it said.
   Armenians say more than 1.5 million people died in the massacres
in the waning days of the Ottoman empire from 1915 to 1918. Turkish
officials have disputed the 1.5 million figure, saying there were
only 1.4 million Armenians living in Turkey at the turn of the
century. They claim that 300,000 Armenians were killed in the
turmoil of deportations and local reprisals. Historians have
estimated 600,000 dead.
   Armenia was incorporated into the Soviet Union in 1920.
   ``Residents of Soviet Armenia today remembered the victims of
the 1915 genocide in which more than a million and a half innocent
people perished,'' Tass said.
   Special memorial services in Yerevan were attended by thousands
of people, including foreign specialists who are in the Armenian
capital doing relief work in the aftermath of the Dec. 7 earthquake
that killed 25,000 people, Tass said.
   On Tsitsernakerberd Hill, mourners ``laid flowers and wreaths to
the symbolic grave of their ancestors over which the eternal flame
has been glowing and sober music playing for many years,'' Tass
said.
</TEXT>
