<FIRST>r i AM-Walters     04-24 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walters,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Ambassador Takes Over Amid Disagreements With West Germans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vernon A. Walters, a veteran diplomat
with a reputation for candor, took over as U.S. ambassador to West
Germany on Monday as the two nations try to work out thorny
disagreements.
   Walters refrained from mentioning one of the most pressing
issues ruffling U.S.-West German relations: short-range nuclear
weapons.
   But Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher heightened debate on
that issue by insisting Washington change its mind and begin early
negotiations with the Soviets on reducing the short-range weapons.
   A military honor guard welcomed Walters at Villa Hammerschmidt,
the palatial residence of President Richard von Weizsaecker.
Walters entered the villa without talking to reporters.
   Walters is viewed as more experienced and outspoken than his
predecessor, Richard Burt, and West German observers have predicted
that could heighten disputes between the two countries.
   In a copy of an address by Walters to von Weizsaecker during the
ceremonies in which he officially became ambassador, Walters
refrained from directly mentioning the short-range missiles.
   But he said NATO's nuclear weapons must be kept up to date and
warned against any move to abandon the weapons as a key part of the
alliance's defense strategy.
   ``At a time when East-West relations are changing for the
better, NATO will still continue to require conventional and
nuclear forces that are effective and credible,'' said Walters.
   Genscher and Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg flew to
Washington on Monday to state their case for talks on the
short-range weapons even though U.S. officials a day earlier
indicated they won't be changing their position.
   Officials in Bonn also want NATO to postpone making a decision
to modernize the short-range weapons.
   The United States fears new negotiations might lead to
elimination of the weapons and says that would increase the threat
to Western Europe from superior Warsaw Pact conventional forces.
   Before leaving for Washington, Genscher said NATO already has
decided there should be negotiations on the short-range arsenals
and that this decision should be carried out.
   ``We would like to see this intention put into practice,''
Genscher said on Deutschlandfunk radio.
   In his address, Walters referred to some other issues that have
troubled U.S.-West German relations, such as complaints by West
Germans of NATO ground and air maneuvers.
   There has been increasing resentment among West Germans to the
400,000 foreign troops stationed on their soil amid a growing
perception that the Soviet bloc is no longer a military threat.
   But U.S. officials have warned that NATO cannot afford to let
its guard down and new developments in the East bloc _ such as
disarmament initiatives _ should be viewed with caution.
   On the issue of NATO maneuvers, Walters said ``I well understand
that the presence of nearly 1 million soldiers, German and allied
... means a special burden for the German population.''
   He added, ``We are working continually with your government to
seek ways to minimize the disruption of the daily lives of Germans.
We will continue to do this.''
   Walters did not mention what those measures were.
   The 72-year-old Walters last served as chief U.S. delegate at
the United Nations.
</TEXT>
