<DOCNO> AP890424-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RareRhinosFound     04-24 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rare Rhinos Found,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's Rarest Rhinos Found In War-Ravaged Region Of Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small population of the world's rarest
rhinoceros has been found in a war-ravaged region of Vietnam not
far from Ho Chi Minh City, officials said Monday.
   The Javan rhinoceros somehow survived decades of war and
defoliation in the eastern part of Vietnam's Song Be province, said
George Schaller, director of Wildlife Conservation International, a
division of the New York Zoological Society.
   The rhinos had been thought extinct in Vietnam since the 1960s,
except for about 50 living on the western tip of the island of Java.
   ``It was suspected that some still survived in Indochina, but
there was no definite evidence of them,'' Schaller said in a
telephone interview.
   The dark gray Javan rhinoceros is roughly similar to the African
black rhinoceros, but is chunkier and has heavy skin folds that
give it an armored look. An adult weighs 3,500 pounds, stands 5{
feet tall and is up to 11{ feet long.
   Live animals themselves were not sighted, but a dead one was
found and there were fresh tracks, Schaller said.
   The size of the rhino population is not known, but ``my guess
would be no more than 10 to 15,'' Schaller said.
   Schaller, who has tracked endangered animals all over the globe,
most recently in China and Tibet, found the rhinos' tracks during
an expedition to Vietnam in February and March.
   He was there with Vo Thanh Son of the University of Hanoi and
Nguyen Yuan Dang and Le Dinh Thuy of Vietnam's national research
council to make the first wildlife survey of Vietnam's southern
forests.
   The tracks were found along the Dong Nai River, about 75 miles
northeast of Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon.
   The find is important not only because it improves the survival
odds for the Javan rhinoceros, but also because the rhinos can be
used to encourage preservation of wilderness in Vietnam, Schaller
said.
   ``You may well say that the rhino is a national treasure of
Vietnam,'' he said. ``But the real treasure is the habitat there,
the forest.
   ``Many of these ... charismatic species are in effect symbols,
flagship species, in that they arouse emotions. They motivate a
government to protect an area, because they get popular support.''
   The region where the rhinos were found is a hot, humid patchwork
of forest, native tribesmen's fields and huge expanses of bamboo up
to 40 feet tall, Schaller said.
   ``The Vietnamese are real conscious of conservation, and I think
they'll make an effort'' to protect the rhinos, Schaller said.
   He recommended stiff penalties for killing rhinos and selling
them, and the enlargement of a wilderness reserve near where the
rhinoceroses were found. In Vietnam, as elsewhere in Asia, rhino
horn is used as a constituent of many different medicines, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1908EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Rescue     04-24 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Rescue,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescue Ships Halted, Stranding Christians in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE BARONESS M (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capt. Dionysis Palanicoloatos took
his ferry toward the coast of Lebanon, where hundreds of people
were waiting to escape their daily dose of fear.
   With the big Baroness M just 25 miles away from the
battle-scarred Christian heartland, a call came in from the ship's
agent in the port of Jounieh.
   Turn around and go back, the agent told the skipper.
   ``It's frustrating not to go in after coming all this way, but
we can't put anybody at risk,'' Papanicolatos, a 45-year-old Greek,
said as he turned the vessel around Sunday.
   What the agent did not say is that a French tanker was
delivering much-needed fuel oil to the Christian enclave north of
Beirut. Earlier, it made a similiar shipment to the Moslem sector.
   The Christian cabinet, led by army commander Gen. Michel Aoun,
had ordered the ferry service suspended while the fuel was unloaded
at Journieh, which has been the target of steady shelling by Syrian
forces.
   The interrupted journey of the Baroness M was a momentary cut in
the only escape route for the beleaguered Christian residents,
whose enclave is surrounded on three sides by hostile forces and
the fourth by the sea.
   The Baroness M is one of two Cyprus-based ferries making the
regular 112-mile trip from the island nation to Lebanon. They have
carried out an estimated 13,000 Christian refugees in the past six
weeks as fighting between Christian forces and Syrian and Druse
allied troops has intesified.
   In recent days, the ferries have had to anchor outside Lebanon's
12-mile territorial waters because of the Syrian shelling.
   Papanicolatos had planned to move in to within 15 miles to pick
up around 1,000 Christians coming out of fishing boats under cover
of darkness if the shelling didn't look too bad.
   But the way it turned out, the Christian families were left
stranded, not knowing when they will be able to flee to safety.
   Leaving Lebanon can be as treacherous as living there. Shipping
sources in Larnaca, Cyprus, said a Syrian shell hit a fishing boat
carrying people to the other ferry, the Larnaca Rose, on Saturday
night. The sources said there were many fatalities.
   Sources in Jounieh said they had no information to authenticate
that report.
   But Artine Himidian, a Lebanese aboard one of the fishing
smacks, said: ``We were shelled all the way out to the Larnaca Rose.
   ``The skipper steered a zig-zag course so it would be more
difficult for the gunners' radar to track us ... Women and children
were screaming as the shells crashed around the boat,'' he said.
   Walid Barake, another of the Lebanese on the Larnaca Rose, said
he spent several hours hiding from the bombardment in a casino
basement in Jounieh before they managed to get to the ferry.
   He said about 4,000 Christians were waiting to be evacuated from
Jounieh, which the Syrians are shelling daily, to make the
nine-hour voyage to Cyprus.
   ``We were waiting for the bus to take us to a small port to get
on the fishing boat. The shells were falling almost continously,''
he said.
   About 70 passengers who left Larnaca aboard the Baroness M
Sunday morning, mostly businessmen going to Lebanon to see their
families, had to return to Cyprus.
   ``I don't how I'll get back to Beirut if the ships aren't
running. I'm worried about my wife, she gets very anxious in the
bombing,'' said Jean-Pierre Burat, a French national who runs a
shipping company in Beirut.
   Most passengers seemed relaxed as they sunbathed and chatted or
leafed through magazines. Some played blackjack for hours in the
ship's casino.
   As the Baroness M sailed off the southern coast of Cyprus, three
musicians played Lebanese songs and some passengers danced until
the early hours.
   ``It's always the same, they're sad for an hour, then they're
dancing,'' said purser Irma Hage.
</TEXT>
