<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Lahd     04-24 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lahd,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldier Accidentally Fire On Lahd's Car</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli soldier in south Lebanon mistakenly
opened fire on cars from an Israeli-allied militia, nearly killing
militia commander Gen. Antoine Lahd, a military source said Monday.
   The shooting occurred Sunday night when a convoy of South
Lebanon Army cars driving at high speed neared an army patrol in
Israel's security zone above the border, an army spokeswoman said
on condition of anonymity.
   The commander of the Israeli patrol, believing he was under
guerrilla attack, fired several shots, first in the air and then at
the wheels of the approaching vehicles, she said.
   There were no casualties and the officer apologized to Lahd
after the shooting, she said.
   A military source said, however, that Lahd's car was damaged by
bullets that came close to hitting the militia leader.
   The shooting was in the central sector of the security zone,
Israel's self-proclaimed buffer strip along the border patroled by
Lahd's South Lebanon Army. The mainly Christian militia of about
2,500 men is trained and financed by Israel.
   The 6- to 10-mile-wide security zone was established by Israel
in 1985 when it pulled most of its forces out of the area, ending a
three-year occupation. About 1,000 Israeli soldiers reportedly are
still stationed in the Lebanese south.
   In November, the 61-year-old Lahd survived an assassination
attempt by his wife's 21-year-old dance instructor, who shot him in
the arm and chest at his home in Marjayoun in southern Lebanon.
   Lahd was released from an Israeli hospital in January, and his
assailant is still believed jailed by his militia in South Lebanon.
</TEXT>
