<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AirTraffic     04-24 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Traffic,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Board Looking Into Southern California Air Traffic Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal safety officials will consider changes
in air traffic control for much of southern California on Tuesday,
after investigation of incidents in which airplanes were flown too
close to each other.
   The National Transportation Safety Board is meeting to consider
the results and recommendations from a staff investigation into the
``loss of standard separation'' between a British Airways jumbo jet
and an American Airlines jetliner on Feb. 13 over Westminster,
Calif.
   The planes came within 1.9 miles of each other, both at 9,000
feet, and Federal Aviation Administration officials at the time
said the British Airways pilot had to make a hasty turn to avoid a
collision.
   Although the planes were not close enough for the incident to be
considered a ``near miss,'' FAA rules say they should have been at
least three miles apart horizontally and 1,000 feet vertically.
   The British jet, a Boeing 747, was carrying 286 people from Los
Angeles to London. The American Airlines plane, a British Aerospace
146 with 70 people aboard, was landing at Ontario International
Airport after being diverted from John Wayne International Airport
at Santa Ana, which had been closed due to a power failure.
   The investigation was expanded to cover seven other operational
errors over the past year at the Coast Terminal Radar Approach
Control Facility at John Wayne. The traffic control operation
handles about half a million flights a year in the area between Los
Angeles and San Diego, one of the busiest flight areas in the
country outside major airport control zones.
   The safety board's inquiry is its first major investigation into
an air traffic control operation since it recommended upgrading at
Chicago's O`Hare International Airport after operational errors
increased in 1986. O'Hare had more than 30 flight-handling errors
in 1988, and the FAA has ordered several changes, including the
hiring of additional controllers.
   The staff report on the Feb. 13 California incident recommends
several changes at the Santa Ana facility.
   Among proposals to be voted on by the board are increases in
staffing and training of personnel, some improvements and expansion
of the facility itself and several technical changes, according to
a board source who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The board meeting on Southern California air traffic control
problems comes two days after two reported near collisions
involving airliners in the New York area.
   A TWA jumbo jet coming in from London and a commuter plane were
reported to have come within about 100 feet as they approached
Kennedy International Airport on Sunday, and 45 minutes later a Pan
Am Boeing 727 en route from LaGuardia Airport to Boston reported
coming within 400 yards of a small plane near Westchester County
Airport.
   The five-member board could expand its recommendations to cover
other facilities if it decides any problem is widespread, but only
conditions at the Santa Ana facility are on the agenda.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FBI-CrimeStatistics     04-24 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI-Crime Statistics,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violent Crime Up 5 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of violent crimes rose 5 percent
last year, the FBI said Monday, with aggravated assaults up 7
percent.
   The FBI's preliminary Uniform Crime Report for 1988 showed
overall that reported crimes rose 3 percent from 1987 to 1988.
   Murders increased 3 percent and robberies were up 4 percent from
1987, according to the statistics released Sunday. Rapes went up 1
percent and motor vehicle thefts increased 11 percent.
   Despite the general rise in killings, the number of murders
declined in three of the nation's largest cities.
   Homicides reported to police dropped 8.8 percent in Los Angeles,
4.4 percent in Chicago and 8.3 percent in Detroit.
   Murders rose 64 percent in Washington, where authorities are
blaming the dramatic increase in killings on warring drug dealers.
   The Bush administration has detailed extra FBI and Drug
Enforcement Administration agents to the nation's capital to help
local police fight the drug-spawned crime wave.
   Murders increased 36 percent in Houston, 27.8 percent in
Indianapolis; 27 percent in Jacksonville, Fla.; 21.6 percent in
Memphis, Tenn.; 13.3 percent in New York City, and 12.9 percent in
Dallas, the report said.
   Murders were up 9.7 percent in Philadelphia and 4.8 percent in
Atlanta.
   Pittsburgh recorded a 51 percent decline in murders reported to
police.
   A 3 percent rise in crime last year followed a 2 percent
increase between 1986 and 1987 and a 6 percent jump between 1985
and 1986, the report said.
   The crime index records the number of selected crimes reported
to state and local police agencies. The FBI also tallies the number
of burglaries, larcenies, motor vehicle thefts and arsons reported
to authorities.
   Final tabulations for 1988 are expected to be released this
summer, the FBI said.
   The index showed reported crimes increased 4 percent in the
Northeast and the South and 3 percent in the West. There was no
change in the Midwest crime index, the bureau said.
   By region, murders were up 11 percent in the Northeast, 4
percent in the South and 1 percent in the West.
   There was a 3 percent decline in the number of murders in the
Midwest.
   Small cities showed a 7 percent jump in violent crime, including
an 8 percent increase in rapes and a 6 percent increase in
aggravated assault. Homicides, however, dropped 7 percent in
smaller cities, the report said.
   Cities with populations over 50,000 reported a 5 percent hike in
violent crime and a 6 percent increase in murders.
   Arson increased 1 percent. A 3 percent incease in larger cities
was offset by declines elsewhere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
