<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Strike     04-24 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Strike,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide General Strike Cripples Transport, Factories, Ports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASSAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1.5 million workers nationwide
staged a 24-hour general strike Monday over wages, closing ports
and factories and halting bus service.
   Police were deployed outside government buildings to keep the
peace. Workers marched in the capital's commerical district.
   The workers sought a cost-of-living increase of 60 percent; they
have rejected a government offer of a 10 percent increase that was
scheduled to begin in July.
   Police said there were no reports of violence in the strike,
which was called by a group representing more than 20 trade unions
nationwide.
   In the southern ports of Chittagong and Khulna, loading and
unloading was stalled but ship movement was maintained, officials
said.
   Dhaka public transport employees did not show up for work and
many people kept off the streets fearing violence, the United News
of Bangladesh reported. Tricycle rickshaws, which were allowed to
operate after midday, were almost the only transport on the roads,
according to Nurul Islam, president of the Trade Union Center.
   But government officials said public transportation was not
substantially affected by the strike.
   ``Trains, ferry and air services were almost normal and road
transport was partially disrupted in the morning,'' said Syed
Deedar Bakth, the information minister.
   Islam said the only factories that remained open were some in
Demra and Khulna.
</TEXT>
