<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearMissiles     04-24 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Missiles,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mixed Reax To Mixed Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's decision to develop both the
MX and Midgetman nuclear missiles drew a mixed reaction Monday on
Capitol Hill with some lawmakers faulting the administration for
failing to make a choice while others called the plan the next-best
option.
   ``It's the same thing _ the `all of the above' choice,'' said
Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee. ``They never have the guts to make a decision.''
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney had recommended moving the
nation's 50 multiple-warhead, MX missiles from silos to deployment
on railroad cars rather than developing the single-warhead
Midgetman. But Bush opted for quick deployment of the MX and
research-and-development for the Midgetman.
   Congressional Republicans over the years have favored the MX
while many Democrats prefer the Midgetman.
   Cheney, in a television interview Sunday, announced the
president's decision as well as administration plans to cut
spending on Star Wars to $4.6 billion from the $5.9 billion
proposed by former President Reagan for fiscal 1990 and a proposal
to delay work on the B-2 stealth bomber.
   The defense secretary is expected to detail the cuts Tuesday
when he appears before the House Armed Services Committee.
   The ranking Republican on that panel, Rep. Bill Dickinson of
Alabama, said he urged Bush and Cheney to choose the MX and ignore
the Midgetman, but they felt they had to ``placate the liberal
Democrats and keep this thing alive,'' he said.
   ``The main thing is to preserve and protect the assets we got
which is MX in silos, and then go forward and make them mobile,''
said Dickinson, who described the MX-Midgetman decision as his
``second choice.''
   But another Republican, Sen. Pete Wilson of California, said he
was disappointed with Bush's decision, citing the cost of
research-and-development of the Midgetman.
   Pentagon officials have indicated that funding for the Midgetman
would come out of the MX budget, which is $2.4 billion in the
current proposal.
   ``This will be the fourth year in a row that the defense budget
has been cut in real terms,'' said Wilson, a member of the Senate
Armed Services Committee. ``... Further development of the
Midgetman wastes funds that are sorely needed for other defense
programs.''
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the
committee and a backer of the proposal, said it was his opinion the
plan ``will move through the Hill reasonably, smoothly,'' because
of its support in both parties.
   ``Sen. Nunn and I and Congressman Aspin have been of like mind
on this issue. It goes way back to last year when the three of us
urged President Reagan to retain enough money in the budget'' so
Bush could make a choice, said Warner.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., is chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee. Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., is chairman of the House Armed
Services Committee.
   Warner said the decision now on the MX and Midgetman avoided a
``serious deadlock'' that would have left other defense-related
issues unresolved.
   ``It's the axle around which other decisions will be made,''
Warner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
