<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Drought     04-24 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Drought,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ershad Orders Nationwide Prayers For Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad on
Monday ordered his people to pray for rain to end a 2-month-old
drought that has wiped out much of the country's important rice
crop.
   Ershad's order calls for 15 minutes of mass prayers to be held
nationwide Wednesday on playgrounds and in mosques, said press
secretary Toab Khan.
   The drought that has parched Bangladesh follows heavy floods
late last year that submerged three-fourths of the nation and
killed hundreds of people.
   Ershad plans to attend the prayer session of Dhaka's main Moslem
congregation. An estimated 100,000 people are to recite verses from
the Koran, the holy book of Islam.
   Rains, which were expected around the first week of March, are
not likely for another week, the weather office said.
   The drought has destroyed rice crop in more than 15 districts in
northern Bangladesh, the most severely affected area, officials at
the Agriculture Ministry said.
   Nearly half of the Boro variety rice crop will be lost this
season, said an official, speaking on condition of anonymity. He
said the loss may multiply if the drought persists.
   The country annually produces 17 million tons of foodgrains to
feed its 110 million people. The target of Boro rice crop this year
was set at 4.6 million tons.
   Crops in Bangladesh depend mostly on rains for irrigation. Some
areas have irrigation pumps but most were dry as groundwater levels
had plunged, news reports said.
   Bangladesh imports about 2 million tons of foodgrains a year to
meet the shortfall of 1.5 million tons in production and build an
emergency reserve.
   The drought followed devastating floods last year that claimed
more than 1,400 lives and washed away about 2.5 million tons of
grain.
   The floods forced the government to plan an import of 3 million
tons of food grains this year and the drought-induced loss may push
the imports further up, the Agriculture Ministry said.
   Crop losses has sparked a steep hike in food prices in several
remote areas of northern Bangladesh, United News of Bangladesh news
agency said.
   But the government ruled out a possibility of famine saying it
had a reserve stock of more than 800,000 tons of food grains.
   Two years of natural disasters have inflicted damage totalling
$1.1 billion in damage to the country, according to a joint
estimate by the United Nations and Aid Group for Bangladesh.
   The aid group, at a meeting Wednesday in Paris, committed $2.2
billion in new aid for fiscal year 1990 to Bangladesh. Donors
include Britain, France, Japan, the United Nations, the
International Monetary Fund and the United Nations Development
Program.
</TEXT>
