<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Bald Kids,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Specialists Question Findings on Baldness in Soviet City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign doctors challenged a Soviet diagnosis that
children in a Ukrainian city lost their hair after being exposed to
a chemical used in rat poisons, Tass reported Monday.
   Dr. Gerar de Groot of the Toxicological Center in the
Netherlands told the official news agency the quantities of
thallium found in patients could not have caused the reported
consequences. But he and other experts said they did not know what
made more than 160 children in the city of Chernovtsy to lose their
hair since autumn.
   In February, Tass quoted Soviet doctors as saying the chemical
might have been carried to the city in the form of acid rain from a
nearby Romanian chemical plant. Chernovtsy is near the Soviet
border with Romania.
   As a result, town streets were washed more frequently, and only
local drivers were allowed into the city center. Traffic was banned
altogether one day a week, Tass reported in February.
   The mysterious ailment, the last case of which was discovered in
November, afflicted primarily children under 14, Tass said. The
children suffered no long-term health effects, the agency quoted a
doctor as saying.
