<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     04-24 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Urges Open-Minded Attitude to Palestinian Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Monday urged Israelis and
Palestinians to keep open minds about an evolving plan for
elections in the Israeli-occupied territories and to stop a recent
escalation of violence between them.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the United
States is deeply concerned over the increase in casualties over the
past few days in clashes between Israeli troops and Palestinians
protesting Israel's rule of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``The increase in tensions runs directly counter to the cause of
peace,'' she said. ``We strongly urge both sides to exercise
restraint. We remain determined to work with all parties to break
out of the current confrontation and to replace violence with
political dialogue and accommodation.''
   Discussing the possibility of Palestinian elections as a first
step toward a peace settlement, Ms. Tutwiler said the United States
will work closely with all parties in the region.
   The goal, she said, is to create conditions for direct
negotiations and peace.
   ``If elections are to fulfill their potential in this regard, it
will be essential that they be free and fair in the best tradition
of democracy. All those truly committed to peace should demonstrate
that commitment by keeping an open mind to proposals that can
advance the process,'' she said.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has proposed a plan for
elections in the West Bank and Gaza to choose Palestinians to
negotiate an interim peace treaty with Israel.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization has been reported to have
countered with a proposal for elections in the occupied lands for
members of the Palestine National Council, the PLO's
parliament-in-exile.
   Shamir says Israel will never hold talks with the PLO but
several Labor Party ministers recently have urged a change in that
stand.
   Tutwiler cautioned that discussions of an election format had
just begun in the Middle East, following presentation of the plan
to the Bush administration during Shamir's visit here this month.
   ``Obviously, during the course of these discussions, there will
be many and varied views on the issue, some workable, some not,''
she said.
   Ms. Tutwiler also defended the State Department against
accusations by some Lebanese Christian leaders and U.S. editorials
that the United States is ignoring the suffering in Lebanon.
   She said the government has for the past two years been
supplying $14 million in food annually to some 135,000 Lebanese
families, both Christian and Moslem, although supplies have been
interrupted by the heavy Syrian bombardments of Christian enclaves
in Beirut in recent weeks.
   President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III have
issued several statements expressing their concern over the
deteriorating situation in Lebanon, she said, and Baker attended a
church service Sunday in Washington ``to show his support for the
suffering of the people in Lebanon.''
   The fact that the United States has not sent ships or personnel
to Lebanon, as France has done, ``does not mean that the United
States does not care,'' she said.
</TEXT>
