<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Nicaragua     04-24 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels, Opposition Ask for U.N. Observers in Nicagagua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra rebels and Nicaraguan opposition
parties asked the United Nations on Monday to send monitors to
ensure that the presidential campaign is democratic.
   The leftist Sandinista government made its own request on March
16 that the international body send poll-watchers for the election,
set for Feb. 25, 1990.
   The government agreed to the elections and other democratic
reforms last February in a pact among five Central American
presidents. In exchange, the leaders said they would arrive at a
plan by mid-May to disband the Contras.
   Spokesmen for the rebels and the political opposition, which
ranges from conservative to communist, said they made their request
Monday during a 2{-hour meeting with Alvaro de Soto, an aide to
U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Joining the Contra envoys were officials from the Social
Democratic Party, Conservative Party, Conservative Party of
Nicaragua, Conservative Democratic Party, Socialist Party, Social
Christian Party, the Private Enterprise Council, and the Communist
Party, which is separate from the Sandinistas.
   Contra leader Aristedes Sanchez said the rebels, who are armed
and living in camps in neighboring Honduras, and the opposition
groups would honor the results of ``a free election.''
   However, the two groups said they still had misgivings about the
attitude of the leftist Sandinista government in Managua.
   The rebels and political opposition have been suspicious about
whether the Sandinistas will allow the national election commission
and the country's news media to function impartially.
   The Sandinista Party controls both the government and the media
in Nicaragua.
   However, the rebels and political leaders on Monday expressed
their commitment to participate in the election.
   ``This is an opportunity to rebuild the nation,'' said Bosco
Matamoros, another Contra leader.
   The Contra and Nicaraguan political leaders did not discuss
specific proposals after their meeting with de Soto.
   But they said they want the United Nations to verify that the
campaign is free and fair. Matamoros stressed what he called ``the
necessity of international support, guarantees and verification.''
   Perez de Cuellar has said his aides are reviewing whether to
send observers to Nicaragua. He has notified the General Assembly
to be ready to approve funds if the mission is approved.
   About 12,000 Contra fighters are believed to be in Honduran
border camps. U.S. military aid to the Contras ended 11 months ago,
and they now receive only humanitarian aid.
   In April, the Contras declared a truce until the February
elections.
</TEXT>
