<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Subversion     04-24 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Subversion,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader, 4 Others Acquitted of Subversion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge acquitted a union
leader and four other black activists of subversion Monday,
describing boycotts they organized as legal protests of poor living
conditions.
   Jubilant supporters lifted Moses Mayekiso, leader of a metal
workers' union, on their shoulders and carried him from the Supreme
Court to the nearby Central Methodist Church.
   Police ordered the crowd to stop singing and chanting. They also
told journalists to leave the area.
   Mayekiso said at a news conference later he and the other his
defendants would resume their activities and rebuild the community
organizations authorities had alleged were subversive.
   ``We're going to start where we left,'' Mayekiso said. ``The
message we have been given is that the structures are legal.''
   Mayekiso, 48, was charged with attempting a political takeover
in 1985-86 of Alexandra, an impoverished black township adjoining
some of Johannesburg's most luxurious white suburbs.
   He had been jailed for 30 months until Judge P.J. van der Walt
freed him on bail in December.
   Van der Walt said Monday the state presented no direct evidence
that the defendants, their Alexandra Action Committee or the
outlawed African National Congress had planned unrest, attacks on
police, the resignation of township council members or the
establishment of people's courts.
   The judge said he had toured the township and seen the poor
conditions. He said the community had developed a lack of faith and
trust in authorities.
   According to van der Walt, the boycotts were intended to improve
living conditions, not make the township ungovernable.
   International attention was attracted to the trial because
because Mayekiso leads the National Union of Metalworkers of South
Africa, the country's largest union of metal workers, and because
many activists viewed the prosecution as an attempt to stifle
peaceful anti-apartheid activity.
   In the United States, United Auto Workers president Owen Bieber
called the prosecution ``malicious and outrageous.''
   ``The South African authorities knew all along that Mayekiso had
committed no crime, but they jailed him for 901 days and subjected
him to a long and costly trial,'' Bieber said in a statement.
   Van der Walt criticized the state for first charging the
defendants with treason. After acknowledging treason could not be
proved, prosecutors substituted the lesser charges of subversion
and sedition.
   In the trial, van der Walt asked the prosecutor whether rent and
consumer boycotts were illegal in 1985-6. The prosecutor
acknowledged they were not, but the government has imposed
emergency decrees since that outlaw the organization of boycotts.
   During that period in Alexandra, dozens of people were killed in
clashes with security forces and in attacks by crowds on township
council members and black policemen. The entire council resigned
and most black policemen moved out of Alexandra.
   Since then, the government has detained or restricted leaders of
the Alexandra Action Committee and undertaken a $45 million
redevelopment program to provide sewage, electricity and paved
streets to most of the 100,000 residents.
   Those acquitted with Mayekiso were Paul Tshabalala, 38; Obed
Bapela, 30; Richard Mdakane, 30, and Mayekiso's brother, Mzwanele,
24.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
