<DOCNO> AP890424-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-StadiumDisaster     04-24 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stadium Disaster,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Tragedy, Social Scientists Examine Soccer Crowds</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB GLOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social scientists are debating what turns English
soccer fans into tribal mobs as a shattered nation buries its dead
from the Sheffield stadium tragedy and awaits its share of the
blame for an earlier disaster.
   Researchers are trying to explain why soccer stadiums become
breeding grounds for racism and violence, and why blue-collar males
are attracted to hooliganism the way youngsters in Los Angeles are
drawn to inner-city gangs.
   They also are exploring why many young fans shun the comfort of
seated areas and choose to stand for hours on a cold, crowded
concrete terrace _ the scene of the April 15 crush that killed 95
Liverpool fans in Sheffield.
   Days after that tragedy, England is readying itself for another
reminder of the stains on its image of polished civility. A Belgian
judge will issue his verdict Friday in the case of 26 Liverpool
fans accused of causing the 1985 Heysel stadium riot in which 39
people died.
   The Sheffield disaster was caused less by outright hooliganism
than by overcrowding, but it quickened the debate on such questions
as what causes a crowd to become belligerent or to stampede;
whether the game itself is to blame, and whether outdated stadiums
turn people into animals.
   Violence by sports fans is not new. Chariot race hooligans
caused a riot in sixth century Rome that reputedly led to 30,000
deaths.
   Today, political scientists are focusing on the unequal
distribution of wealth and jobs in England, particularly in
industrial cities such as Liverpool, and the role that class
distinctions play in treatment of crowds.
   Commentators are accusing the soccer establishment of showing
contempt for fans by providing inadequate facilities and neglecting
safety.
   Social scientists are concentrating on human behavior and the
way it reacts to the environment. They point to degrading
conditions on the terraces of 19th-century stadiums, in which
comfort and sanitation are ignored.
   ``The more you treat them like animals, the more it's likely to
be a self-fulfilling prophecy,'' said criminologist Eugene
Trivizas, a specialist in hooligan behavior.
   Psychologist David Canter accuses clubs of ``almost literally
getting away with murder for the last 10 years or so'' by skimping
on stadium facilities.
   Despite the discomfort on the terraces, researchers say young
urban males prefer the ``shared ordeal'' of packing together like
sardines, because it offers them anonymity and a sense of power.
   ``Young males in urban populations lack any kind of group
identity and this is what football (soccer) gives them,'' said
Desmond Morris, author of popular anthropological studies like
``The Naked Ape.''
   ``It offers them a chance to belong to a group and express their
joys and fears through that group. Young males need to express
themselves in some way that involves risk-taking and honor,'' he
said in an interview.
   Bolstered by alcohol and machismo, they press their bodies
against one another and sway to team songs just as their fathers
and grandfathers did. They yell racial epithets at players, crude
insults at women.
   ``Working classes are less likely to express emotion in subtle
verbal forms,'' said Canter, whose book ``Football in its Place''
is to be published in May. ``It's more likely to be some sort of
physical representation, such as jumping up and down and shouting.''
   Trivizas said absorption in a crowd dismisses personal
inhibitions because fans believe ``it is difficult to be held
responsible or to be identified if they misbehave.''
   ``There is an impression of universality. If other people are
doing what you are doing, then you think what you're doing cannot
be wrong. People think they can behave with relative impunity.''
   In his 1981 book ``The Soccer Tribe,'' Morris likened soccer
fans to religious zealots and warned that the tribal element could
be eradicated by forcing fans to sit comfortably and quietly in
stadiums and ``turning this symbolic event into Disneyland fun.''
   ``Perhaps the greatest dilemma facing the Soccer Tribe today is
the question of whether its main activity is a sacred ritual or a
social entertainment,'' he wrote. ``Should the ancient traditions
of Spartan suffering give way to theater comforts and modern
razzmatazz?''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HeartHelp     04-24 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heart Help,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Procedure Seen As Transplant Alternative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a third of those needing heart
transplants eventually may be candidates for new surgery in which a
flap of back muscle is wrapped around the ailing heart to help it
pump, doctors said Monday.
   ``The candidates, ideally, will be people who are heading toward
a heart transplant, but still have enough reserve left,'' said Dr.
George Magovern, chairman of surgery at Allegheny General Hospital.
   The experimental procedure was performed last month using a
special pacemaker that stimulates the transplanted back muscle in
multiple bursts, unlike conventional, single-pulse pacemakers. The
muscle is thus able to contract with the heart over longer periods
of time.
   It was the first time the 3\-ounce cardiomyostimulator,
manufactured by Medtronic Inc. of Minneapolis, had been implanted
into a patient in the United States, Magovern said. Allegheny
General is the only hospital with U.S. Food and Drug Administration
approval to use the device in clinical trials.
   The patient, Ralph Beilstein, 57, an interior decorator from
nearby Sewickley, said he feels ``marvelous.'' He had suffered from
chronic heart failure since 1964.
   His left latissimus dorsi muscle was partially removed March 20
and wrapped around his heart three days later. The pacemaker was
implanted during the March 23 operation below the left side of his
rib cage and turned on March 31. He was discharged Wednesday.
   ``I just generally feel better, psychologically as well as
physically,'' Beilstein said at a hospital news conference attended
by his wife, Virginia, and their four daughters and eight
grandchildren.
   He was able to avoid a heart transplant, a riskier procedure
that can involve lengthy waits because of the scarcity of donor
organs.
   The muscle-flap operation was first performed in the United
States by Magovern in 1985. The procedure had been performed only
once before, about six months earlier in Paris.
   By Jan. 1, the muscle-flap operation had been performed about 40
times around the world, six of them at Allegheny General, said Dr.
Ignacio Christlieb, who assisted in Beilstein's operation.
   The cardiomyostimulator was used in about three-quarters of the
cases, all overseas.
   In each case, doctors detach the left latissimus dorsi muscle
from the patient's back, except for a small portion remaining
attached by an artery and nerve under the arm. About 2 inches of
one rib is removed, and the muscle flap is pushed through and
wrapped around the heart.
   A 1{-foot-long wire woven through the muscle flap is attached to
the implanted pacemaker, which is run by a lithium battery.
   One system of insulated wires sends signals from the heart to
the pacemaker. Another sends signals to electrodes in the muscle
flap, enabling the muscle to beat in tandem with the heart.
   Skeletal muscle, such as the latissimus dorsi, lacks the natural
electrical conduction system of heart muscle and therefore requires
a precisely timed and controlled burst of pulses to stimulate
contraction.
   Beilstein said he is not limited physically as a result of his
removed muscle. The muscle has been removed and used in the past in
breast reconstruction and repairing leg fractures.
   ``It's a muscle the body can spare,'' Heckler said.
   Doctors say they're not sure how long the muscle will be able to
function around the heart.
   ``It's like you're training an athlete to perform a given
task,'' Christlieb said. ``If you take that training continuously,
the nutrition is good and there's no additional disease, it (back
muscle) could go on for a lifetime.
   ``What we don't know for sure is which is the ideal electric
current to do this, and that's part of our ongoing
investigations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
