<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     04-24 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Asks United Nations to Put Vice on Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Monday urged the U.N. Security Council to
pressure Iraq for concessions in the floundering peace talks aimed
at a permanent settlement of the Persian Gulf war.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran made the call after
both sides reported no progress in their fourth round of
U.N.-sponsored talks, which ended Sunday in Geneva.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said he will seek
a new meeting between Velayati and his Iraqi counterpart, Tariq
Aziz, in June.
   However, Velayati told a news conference Monday that ``it is
difficult to continue such a situation.''
   He called on the five permanent Security Council members,
including the United States and the Soviet Union, to put pressure
on Iraq.
   ``They should help the secretary-general; otherwise, I don't
know what will happen,'' he said.
   For his part, Aziz said Iran ``refrained from the correct manner
of conducting negotiations'' but did not elaborate.
   There has been little progress since the talks began last Aug.
25, five days after a U.N.-supervised truce took effect.
   At least 1 million people were killed or wounded in the war,
which began with several border skirmishes and an Iraqi invasion of
Iran in September 1980. Iran has demanded a full withdrawal of
Iraqi troops from its territory. Iraq has said the Shatt-al-Arab
waterway, its only sea outlet, must first be cleared of war debris
and silt.
   Perez de Cuellar, who chaired the latest round of talks, said
both sides renewed their commitment to the cease-fire and to more
talks.
