<FIRST>r a AM-LAGangs-Justice     04-24 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Gangs-Justice,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation's Top Crime Fighter Says Resources To Fight Gangs Are Slim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh denied
Monday that the city is being shortchanged on federal funds and
resources to fight violent street gangs and drug trafficking.
   ``Do you have enough? No. Will you ever have enough? Never,''
Thornburgh said.
   He was in town to be briefed on the Los Angeles Gang Drug Task
Force, a multiagency group organized six months ago to target major
drug distributors affiliated with street gangs.
   ``We have become the principal center for distribution of
cocaine in the United States,'' said U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner.
``Los Angeles right now is distributing more than half of the
nation's cocaine.''
   The gangs are responsible for distributing crack or rock cocaine
to 47 cities outside Los Angeles and are the prime suppliers to the
Washington, D.C., area, Bonner said.
   Thornburgh recently chose the nation's capital for a test
project in which federal law enforcement will focus efforts there
to curb its rampant drug problem.
   At a news conference later, Thornburgh was asked why Los Angeles
wasn't chosen for the experiment since authorities here say it's
the nation's major drug center.
   ``The problem is not confined to Los Angeles. I assure you it is
a major priority,'' he said.
   Thornburgh added that 24 prosecutors have been added to the U.S.
Attorney's Office here and the government has tripled its
allocations to local and state governments to fight the growing
national drug problem.
   ``We never have enough in terms of resources ... the notion that
we're writing off this effort is nonsense,'' he said, stressing
that the national and international drug problem is the priority of
federal law enforcement.
   John Zienter, head of the Drug Enforcement Administration office
in Los Angeles, said that within the last six months the task force
arrested more than 150 people and seized more than $5 million worth
of drugs, cash, weapons and property, including exotic cars and
expensive houses.
