<FIRST>r i AM-HamadiTrial     04-24 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hamadi Trial,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Hears Final Testimony In Trial Of Confessed TWA Hijacker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony in the trial of
confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi drew to a close Monday,
and final arguments are to begin later this week.
   Hamadi is charged with murder and air piracy in the June 1985
hijacking of a Trans World Airlines jet in which U.S. Navy diver
Robert Stethem was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage 17
days.
   Hamadi, 23, has admitted participating in the hijacking but
denied he shot Stethem.
   Final arguments are set for Friday in the trial that began last
July.
   During a brief session Monday, British Broadcasting Corp.
reporter John Simpson told the court what he observed when TWA
Flight 847 was forced to land in Algiers, Algeria during the ordeal.
   During the hijacking of the Athens-to-Rome flight the jetliner
was forced to land in Beirut three times and twice in Algeria.
   Simpson, 44, told the court he was in Algiers with a BBC
televison crew on June 14, 1985, but police prevented them from
filming the hijacked TWA plane from the airport tarmac.
   ``We were detained for about 30 minutes. Later we were allowed
to film the plane from a waiting room'' at the airport, Simpson
said.
   He said the waiting room provided only a view of the right rear
side of the aircraft, so there was no chance to film the left side
of the plane where the Boeing 727's doors are located.
   Defense attorneys had called Simpson to testify, hoping to show
that no passengers were threatened while the plane was on the
ground in Algiers.
   A West German federal investigator said earlier that the
hijackers opened one of the plane's doors and held a gun at the
head of a passenger to force Algerian officials to provide fuel for
the jetliner.
   Hamadi denied that any passengers were threatened to obtain fuel
in Algiers.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, claims his accomplice in the
hijacking, identified in court records as Hassan Ezzeddine, killed
Stethem, 23. Ezzeddine remains a fugitive.
   After Simpson's testimony, Hamadi's defense lawyers asked the
court to view videotape they said showed military attacks carried
out by Israel in Lebanon in 1982.
   Attorney Hans-Burkhardt Steck said the video was obtained from a
group in the area and would show the conditions that motivated
Hamadi to take part in the hijacking. He did not give the name of
the group.
   The court allowed the tape to be played, and it showed scenes
from war-torn Beirut and from Palestinian refugee camps.
   Prosecutor Peter Korneck objected after the tape was shown,
calling it propaganda and saying it should not be entered into
evidence.
   ``If it is, then I would like a video of (terrorist) attacks in
Paris to be shown,'' Korneck said, referring to bombings in the
French capital, including five in September 1986, that killed eight
people.
   The court did not rule immediately on the objection.
</TEXT>
