<HEAD>Student Protesters Occupy Second UMass Building In A Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 70 students occupied a University
of Massachusetts building Monday in the second takeover in a week
to protest Defense Department-funded research.
   Campus police sealed off Memorial Hall after about 70 protesters
entered around 1 p.m., said university spokeswoman Stacey Chase.
Police allowed students out of the building, but not in.
   No attempt was made to arrest or remove the protesters from the
building, Chase said. ``Whether action comes later remains to be
seen,'' she said.
   The protesters, calling themselves People for a Socially
Responsible University, presented administrators with a list of
demands including a halt to all Defense Department research on
campus and the withdrawal of charges against seven students
arrested Wednesday in a similar occupation at another university
building.
   The seven arrested last week on trespassing and disorderly
conduct charges were among those occupying Memorial Hall on Monday,
Chase said.
   Army-funded research at the university on the disease anthrax
will be the topic of a hearing before the Amherst Board of Health
that has been scheduled for Wednesday.
   Members of the local chapter of the American Friends Service
Committee contend the research is dangerous to the town, promotes
militarism and should be banned.
   The university says the purpose of the research is peaceful and
that the strain of bacteria used is non-virulent and has been under
study at the school for 23 years without incident.
