<FIRST>r a AM-Super7Fever     04-24 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super 7 Fever,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-Stakes Lottery Game Not Just for Pennsylvania Anymore</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The push to get a piece of the lottery
action has spread, sending Wednesday's jackpot soaring to $83
million, as out-of-staters grab up tickets and cajole airline
employees to make buys for them.
   The Super 7 drawing has an $83 million jackpot, a North American
record, lottery officials said Monday afternoon. They also said the
figure continues to climb.
   The jackpot kept growing after six drawings yielded no winning
ticket. It is now being boosted by sales of blocs of tickets and
sales to people living in other states. Last week's jackpot was for
$46 million. Unclaimed, it grew to $62 million Thursday. It hit $70
million by the weekend. All gains after $62 million were based on
ticket sales.
   Super 7 players pick seven numbers out of 80. The lottery bureau
will draw 11 numbers Wednesday evening, and any ticket with seven
of them qualifies for the big prize. If one person wins, the annual
payout would be nearly $3.2 million a year for 26 years.
   ``Weekends are normally slow sales days, but this past Saturday
and Sunday, we did $13.7 million in Super 7 sales alone,'' lottery
executive director Jim Scroggins said Monday.
   At Philadelphia's airport, the lottery ticket line was 30 deep
at lunchtime.
   ``People are talking about it on the planes. Some of them want
to give the flight crews money to buy tickets,'' said Susan Antoine
of Richmond, a stewardess who said she planned to buy 50 tickets
for herself.
   Fantasies abounded in line.
   ``If I win I'll buy Donald Trump's yacht and invite him to go
for a ride on it,'' said Louise Henshaw of Hammonton, N.J.
   ``I'd start with a new orange juicer,'' joked Cathy Reuben of
Boston, who got serious: ``What I'd really want is to rent Carnegie
Hall for my sister, who's a pianist.''
   ``I'd take a vacation for the rest of my life,'' said Paul
Kreczko of Chicago, an American Airlines employee who made a
special trip to buy 777 tickets.
   ``Let's see, there's the pool at work, there's tickets for my
family, there's the pool for the people at the bar where I throw
darts, there's the pool for the people we throw darts against _ it
comes to 77 people.''
   Kreczko missed one plane back to Illinois while waiting for his
tickets. He didn't mind.
   ``I think we're going to be lucky,'' he said. ``With 777 tickets
and 77 people, how can we miss?''
   Residents of other states don't have to travel to Pennsylvania
or know somebody in the state to buy a ticket. Tickets Plus, which
mostly sells concert tickets, is selling lottery chances to
out-of-staters willing to pay double the $1 ticket price.
   The outlet has shipped 50-ticket Super 7 packets to California,
Georgia, Michigan, Minnesota and Washington, company officials said.
   ``It's hard to keep up with it. In fact, it's tremendous,'' said
Gary Zurenda, owner of the company in Exeter.
   Zurenda placed ads in newspapers around the country offering to
act as a ticket broker. Customers must buy a minimum of 50 tickets
at $2 apiece, and they also have to pay $10 for overnight mail
delivery.
</TEXT>
