<DOCNO> AP890424-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Relief     04-24 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Relief,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relief Convoy Safely Retraces Route Taken By Ambushed Trucks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. relief convoy safely reached
rebel-held Torit on Monday, six days after a deadly ambush halted
the United Nation's first overland effort to deliver food to the
southern Sudanese town.
   The 31-one truck convoy carried nearly 440 tons of corn on its
14-hour trip from the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army base of
Kapoeta, 100 miles to the west, said spokesman Paul Mitchell of the
U.N. World Food Program.
   Attackers ambushed the first U.N. convoy from Kapoeta to Torit
last Tuesday, killing eight rebel escorts and destroying the lead
vehicle. Mitchell said organizers of the U.N. Operation Lifeline
Sudan hoped the overland route now would be used regularly.
   The $132 million U.N. operation is trying to to prevent 100,000
famine deaths in southern Sudan by stocking food and supplies in
the war-torn region before heavy annual rains begin in mid-May.
   U.N. officials say they probably will fail to meet their goal of
moving 115,500 tons _ the amount needed to stave off widespread
starvation. Last year, as many as 500,000 southern Sudanese died
because of flood- and war-induced famine.
   The United Nations on Friday began airlifting relief supplies to
Torit, which it says has a swelling population now numbering 25,000
people. A recent visitor, however, estimated only about 3,000
people were taking refuge in the town, with many others farming
normally on its outskirts.
   Mitchell said a French-financed Transall C-160 cargo plane on
Monday joined the C-130 already delivering food and that a second
Transall funded by the West Germans was expected to join the
airlift this week.
   Operation Lifeline Sudan began April 1 after the rebel army and
Sudan's government agreed to allow the relief supplies move
unhampered to both rebel-held and government-controlled towns.
   The Sudan People's Liberation Army took up arms against Sudan's
Moslem-dominated government in 1983, demanding greater autonomy and
economic development for the predominantly Christian and animist
south.
</TEXT>
