<FIRST>r w AM-HomelessSuit     04-24 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Suit,1st ld-writethru, a0597,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>eds: CORRECTs spelling of Gasch throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the homeless have accused the
Bush administration of violating a federal court order to make
surplus government property available for the homeless.
   The National Coalition for the Homeless filed a motion late
Friday with U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch in Washington charging
that the Department of Health and Human Services is refusing to
accept or process applications for properties the coalition
contends are suitable for the homeless. HHS was designated as the
agency to process the applications, the coalition said.
   Gasch ruled in a suit by the group last December that the
federal government must review hundreds of surplus federal
properties across the country for possible use by the homeless.
   The coalition contends that under the 1987 McKinney Homeless
Assistance Act passed by Congress, properties determined suitable
by the Department of Housing and Urban Development must be made
available to states, local governments and non-profit groups to use
as facilities to shelter or assist the homeless.
   The motion charges that HHS has limited its review to properties
designated ``excess'' by the agency holding the property,
regardless of HUD's determination. That excludes 87 percent of the
1,415 properties HUD has determined suitable, it contends.
   Amy Brown, spokeswoman for the Justice Department, said the
government will file a response next week. ``The government
believes that it has been in compliance with the December 1988
court order and the McKinney Act,'' she said.
   Maria Foscarinis, counsel for the homeless coalition, said it
asks the judge to order HHS to immediately accept and process
applications and to freeze any sales or transfers while the
applications are being reviewed.
   The coalition said local groups have unsuccessfully sought to
use buildings and land in Los Angeles; Huntsville, Ala.; St. Paul,
Minn.; and Seattle.
</TEXT>
