<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Factions     04-24 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Factions,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Vows Crackdown on Embattled Black Faction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government pledged Monday
to crack down with an ``iron fist'' on a banned anti-apartheid
group involved in black factional fighting that killed 13 people
over three days.
   The battles have been fought mainly between the banned United
Democratic Front and members of Inkatha, which backs KwaZulu black
homeland leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi. The front is the country's
largest anti-apartheid coalition and a political ally of the
outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement.
   Residents around KwaZulu, near Durban and Pietermaritzburg in
Natal Province, have accused both black groups of firebomb attacks
on homes, mob beatings and killings.
   But Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok said in a speech to
Parliament Monday that security forces would concentrate on the
United Democratic Front.
   ``We know that alternative structures such as `street
committees,' `people's courts,' `civic associations,' are chiefly
responsible for the unrest and violence .... We are going to root
them out.''
   All those groups are associated with the United Democratic Front.
   ``In the process, we will be acting against people, against
activists and radicals .... We will grab them and they are going to
kick up a big fuss again. We will not be deterred. I want to warn,
we are going to use the iron fist, regardless,'' Vlok said.
   His only reference to Inkatha was his report that he had spoken
to Buthelezi. He said the homeland's leader was just as concerned
about the violence as he is.
   Factional fighting has killed 1,000 Zulu tribesmen in that
homeland over the past year. The white-led government set up the
network of black homelands to relieve pressure from domestic and
international critics.
   The front and Inkatha both oppose the apartheid policies that
enable South Africa's 5 million whites to dominate 28 million
blacks. However, the front views Buthelezi as a conservative who
weakens the struggle for black rights.
   One opposition leader accused the government of taking sides in
its reaction Monday.
   ``By heaping blame on one side only, the minister places in
doubt the neutral role of the police,'' said Peter Gastrow, the
Democratic Party's member from central Durban. ``Mr. Vlok presents
a one-sided and oversimplified version of what is happening on the
ground in Natal.''
   He blamed the violence on a complex mixture of factors involving
the two groups, gangs, vigilantes, warlords, poverty, and a loss of
confidence in authorities.
   Vlok said a police general and teams of senior detectives were
being sent to the area. He said security would be stepped up with
more vehicles and semi-permanent police stations spread over a
wider area. He said the army would be called in to assist if
necessary.
   In reporting on the fighting from Friday through Sunday, police
said Monday three people were injured in addition to the 13 men who
were killed in black townships near KwaZulu.
   Monitoring groups say more than 4,000 blacks have been killed in
clashes with police and between rival black groups since 1984.
   Violence has subsided under emergency regulations imposed by the
government nearly three years ago, but fighting has persisted
between Inkatha and the United Democratic Front.
</TEXT>
