<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BlackHealth     04-24 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Health,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed Improvements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of black health care
professionals, educators and community leaders Monday recommended a
series of steps to improve the health of blacks and other
minorities, including a uniform and expanded Medicaid program and a
reallocation of health-care dollars.
   Dr. David Satcher, president of Meharry Medical College in
Nashville, Tenn., said members of the coalition were concerned
about the gap in the health status of minorities compared with
white Americans.
   The infant mortality rate for blacks is twice the rate for
whites and the life expectancy of blacks is declining while it is
increasing for whites, Satcher said, citing recent studies.
   ``We feel it's a crisis we face in this nation,'' Satcher said
at a news conference, where he was joined by Rep. Louis Stokes,
D-Ohio.
   Satcher said about 40 members of the coalition presented their
recommendations to Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan. Satcher described the secretary as ``very receptive, very
concerned.''
   The recommendations included:
   _Making the Medicaid program uniform throughout the states and
expanding it so that anyone within 200 percent of the federal
poverty level is eligible.
   _Reallocating health care dollars by shifting funds from some
procedures and organ transplants that are not proven effective into
disease prevention and primary care. They did not recommend a
specific amount of money.
   _Making sure that blacks and other minorities are
``appropriately'' represented at HHS agencies whose dealings affect
minorities disproportionately, such as agencies that deal with AIDS
and substance abuse.
   _Allocating more aid for black and other minority students in
the health care fields because they are more likely than white
Americans to work in low-income areas.
   In comments before his meeting with the coalition members,
Sullivan reiterated his intention to give special emphasis to
``closing the gap in health status'' between white Americans and
black and minority Americans.
</TEXT>
