<DOCNO> AP890424-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 2ndldwritethru a0674 04-24 1032</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd ld writethru, a0674,1070</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 6 grafs at end to update</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Quayle-AP Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a chilly airplane hangar, President Bush
choked back tears Monday as he comforted grief-stricken relatives
of the 47 sailors killed on the battleship Iowa and offered ``the
sympathy and appreciation of all the American people.''
   Greeting relatives one by one, the president wore a nervous
smile as he shook hands, moving briskly from person to person
waiting along rows of folding-back chairs.
   Some of the relatives showed him a picture of their lost ones.
``This was our only son, this was our only boy,'' Bush recalled one
couple as saying. Several women stopped him for a comforting hug.
   It was an emotional beginning to the president's four-day swing
across the country as he nears the 100-day milestone of his
administration.
   Later, addressing the annual luncheon of The Associated Press,
Bush spoke of the loneliness of the office when it comes to dealing
with situations like the deaths of U.S. military personnel or the
holding of Americans hostage abroad.
   ``I vowed, when I came into the presidency, not to talk about
the burden of the presidency, the loneliness of the job or the
great toughness that nobody understands,'' Bush said. ``I learned
that from my immediate predecessor.''
   But, said Bush, ``when you do take that oath of office, you do
feel perhaps a disproportionate concern for a fallen sailor or an
individual held hostage against his or her will anywhere in the
world.''
   On Air Force One, en route to Chicago, Bush told reporters that
the Norfolk ceremony had been one of those difficult moments.
   ``Tough day down there, it was so moving,'' Bush said,
explaining that his smile had belied the emotions he felt.
   ``The Bush family is not very good at that kind of thing,
anyway. This was tough,'' he said.``But you've got to deal with it,
you've got to show them concern.''
   Bush said, ``You know how you get through it? You pray for
strength.
   ``Although I did choke up at the end there, I did feel kind of
an inner peace about the thing. I had to represent our country.''
   Accompanied by his wife, Barbara, the president flew to Norfolk
at the start of a long travel day, with stops later in Chicago for
a speech before the Associated Press annual luncheon, a
tree-planting ceremony during a centennial celebration in Bismarck,
N.D. and an overnight in San Jose, Calif.
   The 100-day mark of his administration falls on Saturday and
Bush was expected to beat the drum for his presidency in a
succession of out-of-Washington engagements. Before returning to
Washington on Thursday, Bush will make appearances in California,
Texas and Florida.
   In Chicago, Bush defended the progress of his administration and
took time to telephone newly installed Chicago Mayor Richard Daley
to wish him well and congratulate him on his April 4 victory.
   During a question-and-answer session aboard Air Force One en
route to Chicago, Bush addressed a number of issues, including
speculation about whether he would pardon fired White House aide
Oliver North, now awaiting a jury verdict in the Iran-Contra
affair. In the past, Bush has called North a hero and said he hoped
North would be acquitted.
   A Newsweek magazine report quoting sources close to him as
predicting he would never pardon North shows ``how idiotic
speculation is,'' Bush said. ``If it was given any credence as
having come from me or as if somebody had discussed it with me,
they simply haven't.''
   Bush also refused to discuss a published report that he had
authorized spending $10 million for the Panamanian opposition in
the May 7 elections. The United States has been frustrated in its
efforts to oust strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``I don't discuss intelligence matters,'' Bush said. ``We're
involved in encouraging the elections to be free and fair and
open.''
   On another matter, Bush said he had expressed concern to West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who has been reluctant to modernize
short-range missiles in Europe.
   ``My appeal to the Germans has been that we keep NATO together,
stay together.'' Bush said Kohl ``knows my view. There must not be
any unilateral fait accompli.''
   On a personal note, Bush complained that he was two or three
pounds overweight and was going to do something about it. He said
his wife, Barbara, who is suffering from an overactive thyroid, was
doing well. He said there was ``nothing out there any different
than what you've been told.''
   But the emotional peak of the day clearly was Norfolk, where
Bush, a former Navy pilot, said the sailors had ``served the Navy
as shipmates and friends and left the Navy as brothers in eternity.'
   Cameramen with telescopic lenses said Bush had tears on his
cheek as he returned to his aircraft.
   Bush told the gathering at the Norfolk Naval Air Station, ``I
hope that the sympathy and appreciation of all the American people
provide some comfort. But true comfort comes from prayer and
faith.''
   In delivering his remarks, Bush omitted a line of his speech
that said as a Navy veteran, he had ``stared at the empty bunks of
lost shipmates and asked, `Why?''' He explained later that ``I
thought it was a little too subjective.''
   The Norfolk ceremony was marred by a foulup about the relatives
that Bush was supposed to personally greet. After consoling people
in the first four rows of the audience, Bush turned and left,
ignoring three rows of family members.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater explained later
that a military escort had turned Bush aside after four rows,
saying he had greeted all members of the immediate family.
   Fitzwater said Bush was distressed by the episode. ``He said,
`That's really a tragedy,''' Fitzwater said. ``He could see they
were distressed.''
   In Bismarck, Bush planted a 12-foot Elm tree during a ceremony
to mark the state's centennial.
   ``Around the world there is a growing recognition that
environmental problems respect no borders,'' Bush said.
   He said, ``We do not have to accept as inevitable the spoiling
of our air, our rivers our wetlands and our forests.''
</TEXT>
