<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1821EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     04-24 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Unveils Platform for June Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Solidarity-led national opposition
announced an election platform on Monday urging Poles to vote in
June and ``change this system'' toward democracy.
   But the Citizens Committee also stressed it has no illusions
that democracy has already been achieved, and it does not recognize
the elections as being fully free.
   The platform was adopted Sunday at a Citizens Committee meeting
and was released Monday.
   An agreement reached April 5 between communist authorities and
the opposition, led by Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa, established
the framework for elections for the national parliament, including
a new 100-member Senate.
   The opposition is allowed to run candidates for all of the
Senate seats and for 161 seats in the 460-member Sejm, the existing
parliament.
   On Sunday the committee approved 252 candidates and announced
plans to name the nine other candidates Wednesday for the 261 total.
   Walesa, who presided at Sunday's meeting, said again he would
not be a candidate and wanted to remain above the political fray to
lead Solidarity.
   Voting is set for June 4 with a runoff election on June 18.
   Solidarity activists and advisers including Bogdan Lis,
Bronislaw Geremek, Adam Michnik and Jacek Kuron are among those in
the race.
   The opening section of the platform notes that the opposition
supported boycotts of previous elections and calls for all eligible
citizens to vote this time.
   The legislative elections will be the first to be open to
opposition candidates since balloting in 1947 that critics said was
fraudulent.
   ``We appeal to everyone to take part in the elections because we
can see the advantage that Poland can achieve by the participation
of independent forces in the Sejm and the Senate,'' the platform
states.
   ``By running in the election we are not closing our eyes to the
undemocratic character of the system of ruling the country and we
are not going to make it credible.
   ``We want to change this system, achieving this on the road on
evolutionary transformations.''
   Among the platform's 26 points:
   _Changing the constitution to remove the ``leading role'' of the
Communist Party and to allow fully democratic elections in four
years.
   _Expanding the right to form associations.
   _Ending censorship and the party's control of television and
radio.
   _Reducing military and police expenditures and using the savings
to increase old-age pensions.
   _Raising pay levels so that a 42-hour work week would be
sufficient to maintain a family.
   _Making housing loans more widely available to individuals and
trimming back the monopolistic state housing enterprises.
   _Academic freedoms: No propagation of atheism or ideological
pressure in schools, freedom of association for young people and
the right to form private or parochial schools.
</TEXT>
