<FIRST>r i AM-Mauritania-Senegal     04-24 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mauritania-Senegal,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Land Dispute Leads To Mob Violence In Mauritania, Senegal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobs angered at a land dispute
with Senegal sacked homes and market stalls belonging to Senegalese
on Monday, and similar attacks on Mauritanians broke out in
neighboring Senegal, officials reported.
   The attacks took place the same day officials from both
countries reportedly began investigating the April 9 shooting death
of two Senegalese, which prompted the violence. Two others have
died in violence since then.
   Bands of roving vandals roamed the streets of Nouakchott and the
Senegalese capital of Dakar on Monday, smashing cars and destroying
market stalls.
   There was no confirmation from either capital of injuries or
deaths.
   In the southern outskirts of Nouakchott, angry mobs of up to
several hundred people smashed windows, overturned cars and sacked
Senegalese homes. Senegalese were pulled from cars and beaten.
   In the border village of Rosso, Mauritania, mobs carrying
homemade weapons rampaged through the market searching for
Senegalese vendors and beating them. At least one of the small
market stands burned, and police said it belonged to a Senegalese.
   In Dakar, police said bands of vandals sacked Mauritanian
businesses and broke into homes. About a dozen Mauritanians took
refuge in a Dakar police station, the French news agency Agence
France-Presse reported.
   During the weekend, cars in Dakar bearing Mauritanian diplomatic
plates were hit by rocks and one diplomat was injured, AFP reported.
   The two African countries have been disputing a band of fertile
land near the Senegal River, which forms their border. Mauritania
has complained that Senagalese are farming the Mauritanian side of
the border.
   Mauritanian authorities killed the two Senegalese peasants April
9 in the border village of Diawara, Senegal. The same day, Senegal
captured 13 Mauritanians, who were later released.
   Dakar police said two people _ a Mauritanian and a Senegalese _
have been killed in violence since then.
   A Mauritanian government source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said a joint committee investigating the Diawara
shootings began work Monday to determine exactly who fired the
shots.
</TEXT>
