<FIRST>r i AM-Belgium-Miners     04-24 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Miners,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Miners Battle Police, 28 Policemen Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUTHALEN, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas Monday to
disperse thousands of angry miners protesting plans to close
Belgium's two remaining coal pits.
   A police official, not identified in line with regulations, said
28 policemen were injured and nine were hospitalized. He said
several miners also were injured but he had no figures.
   The miners were protesting plans to close the two mines by 1993.
Earlier plans would not have shut down the mines until 1996.
   Miners said early closings would endanger their social benefits.
   The protesting miners first went to the headquarters of the KS
coal firm, where some entered the building and smashed windows and
furniture.
   Later they blocked a main road in the mining region of the
eastern province of Limburg, and fighting erupted when police moved
in to disperse them.
   Many miners were armed with iron bars, stones and chains. Police
used tear gas and water cannons.
   As the miners retreated one policeman, standing beside an
injured colleague, drew his pistol and fired into the air.
   ``About four shots were fired, but nobody was injured in the
incident,'' the police official said.
