<DOCNO> AP890424-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CatastrophicCare     04-24 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Care,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Against Health Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in a letter released Monday,
said it would be ``imprudent to tinker'' with the Medicare
catastrophic insurance plan even in light of an unexpected surplus
in the program's revenues.
   The letter, released by Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., said that
based on the most recent projections, financial reserves for the
program ``are not excessive'' and may actually be ``too thin.'' The
projections, Bush said, are based on estimating uncertainties in a
program that is only a few months old.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, last week raised the possibility of a reduction of up to
16 percent in the surtax paid by many older Americans to finance
the insurance program, which provides extended coverage for a major
prolonged illness.
   Bentsen said that revised revenue estimates from the
Congressional Budgt Office and the Joint Committee on Taxation show
the government may be collecting more money than it needs for the
program. The figures, he said, indicate a $4.9 billion surplus for
the period 1989-1993.
   Bush confirmed that the revenue estimates project more money
than had originally been anticipated. But he noted uncertainties in
the program remain, including a projection by the Reagan
administration that the portion of the program that will pay for
drug benefits was underfunded. The cost of that portion of the
program is to be reestimated this summer, he said.
   ``It would be imprudent to tinker with Medicare catastrophic
insurance literally in its first few months of life,'' Bush said in
the letter. ``We should not now reopen the legislation.''
   Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, embraced Bush's statement and urged his colleagues ``to
carefully consider the points raised by the president before
pursuing legislation to amend the act.''
   He noted that premiums collected under the program are used to
pay only for benefits in the program or to reduce premiums in
future years.
   ``If premium collections do exceed our original expectation, the
amounts collected will still go to serve the beneficiaries and for
no other purpose,'' he said.
</TEXT>
