<FIRST>r w AM-JusticeBlackout     04-24 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice Blackout,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Power Problems Keep Officials in Dark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the nation's top law enforcement
officials worked in the dark, so to speak, Monday because
construction crews couldn't connect an emergency generator
supplying power to part of the Justice Department.
   Electrical power to the southwest portion of the Justice
Department building was knocked out last week when a power cable
was severed by construction crews installing anti-terrorist
security barriers on the west side of the building, said
spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade.
   Power was restored about 6 p.m. but the outage inconvenienced
many top officials for most of the business day.
   A large generator inside a tractor-trailer was plugged into the
building to provide power. But crews had trouble reconnecting the
generator Monday, leaving the office of Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh and some of his top deputies without power, she said.
   ``We are fortunate this occurred on a day the A.G. is in sunny
California,'' said David Runkel, an aide to Thornburgh, who was
meeting with Drug Enforcement Administration officials in Los
Angeles.
   Runkel said the blackout played havoc with the telehone system
in the attorney general's office, making it impossible to transfer
calls.
   When Thornburgh calls to check in, ``the secretary comes down
the hall and we gather at a phone where he is available,'' Runkel
said.
   Downstairs in the criminal division, the phones were not ringing
because of the power outage. ``Some of the secretaries are picking
up phones at random,'' said spokesman Joe Krovisky. ``They have
caught or 10 calls that way.''
   To reach John C. Keeney, deputy assistant attorney general,
criminal division lawyers were told to dial his beeper. Keeney then
returned telephone messages received on his beeper, Krovisky said.
</TEXT>
