<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-NATO     04-24 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-NATO,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Chief for Missile Modernization; Bush Talks to Thatcher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Manfred Woerner of NATO said
Monday the alliance must modernize its short-range nuclear
missiles, an issue that has divided the members, but he also said
compromise is possible.
   A British official said privately that President Bush telephoned
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and that they discussed the
question for 20 minutes.
   He said Bush telephoned on Saturday, a day after West Germany
urged early negotiations between the superpowers on eliminating
short-range missiles. Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of
West Germany and Gerhard Stoltenberg, the defense minister, flew to
Washington on Monday for talks with U.S. officials.
   A spokesman in Mrs. Thatcher's office at 10 Downing St. gave no
details of her conversation but said she and Bush ``concentrated on
the short-range missile issue.''
   Woerner, a former West German defense minister, said at a
luncheon meeting of the American Correspondents in London that
NATO's ``nuclear and conventional weapons have to be kept up to
date.''
   Possible compromises between West German resistance and U.S. and
British pressure to modernize include a reduction by NATO in its
nuclear artillery shells after the short-range missiles are
modernized, he said.
   ``That could be part of a solution,'' Woerner told the
journalists, ``but I'm not pleading now for negotiations on nuclear
artillery.''
   Polls in West Germany, where the short-range Lance missiles are
based, show strong opposition to modernizing them.
   Woerner also confirmed, in answer to a question, that Mrs.
Thatcher's government is considering deployment in Britain of more
U.S. F-111 bombers, which are capable of firing air-launched cruise
nuclear missiles.
   That would help compensate for the removal of land-based cruise
and Pershing 2 rockets under a U.S.-Soviet agreement to remove
intermediate-range missiles from Europe.
   In an apparent reference to fears by Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
center-right coalition government of losing the 1990 election if it
agrees to modernize the missiles, Woerner said: ``It is the task of
a government not to follow public opinion, but to lead it.''
   He was the West German defense minister in the early 1980s when
NATO deployed the cruise and Pershing 2 missiles despite much
public opposition.
   Bush's call to Mrs. Thatcher underlined U.S. and British concern
about the latest West German move.
   Agreement to modernize, with a delay, was reached in Brussels
last week by the alliance's Nuclear Planning Group. A few hours
later, West Germany urged that the United States and Soviet Union
negotiate the elimination of short-range nuclear missiles.
   Britain and the United States say there can be no East-West
negotiations on short-range missiles until agreements are reached
on conventional and chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
