<HEAD>Soldiers Wound 21 Palestinians, Israelis Smash Arab Property</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE injured from 19 to 21, SUB lead and 14th graf, `The
19...' Adds 4 grafs on threats, attacks by Israeli extremists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israelis wielding clubs and iron bars smashed
Arab cars and shops after their buses were stoned Monday in the
West Bank. Arab reports said soldiers wounded 21 Palestinians
during clashes in the Gaza Strip.
   It was the second report in two days of Israelis carrying out
revenge attacks on Palestinians in the West Bank.
   In Washington, a State Department official said the United
States was deeply concerned over a recent increase in casualties in
the 16-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   An army officer, meanwhile, was convicted of stoning Palestinian
vehicles in the West Bank village of Beit Sahour where he was
posted as a lookout, the army announced Monday. An army spokesman
would not give the officer's name and rank or say what his
punishment was. Army radio said he was given a 42-day suspended
sentence.
   The army confirmed ``a couple of Israelis'' attacked cars and
shops in Hebron after Palestinian youths threw stones at their
buses during a visit to a Mearat Hamakhpela, a cave believed to be
the burial cite of biblical Jewish leaders.
   The cave also is a sacred site to Moslems.
   Arab reporters said the Israelis smashed all the windows in at
least 15 cars and a Hebron shopkeeper said six stores in the city
were damaged.
   ``Some youths stoned the bus, and most of the Israelis in the
buses got out carrying clubs and iron bars and started smashing the
cars parked in the street,'' said the shopkeeper, Marwan Abu
Shalyoun. ``I went to one man and tried to stop him from smashing
my car, but a soldier ordered me back to my shop.''
   An army spokesman, who cannot be identified under military
regulations, said soldiers trying to break up the confrontation
were attacked by the Israelis. He said several Israelis were
arrested.
   Israel army radio said the Israelis were hikers from the Tel
Aviv suburb of Petah Tikva.
   There were no injuries in the incident, the spokesman said, but
the army declared a curfew on the city of 79,000 people.
   The incident followed a reported attack Saturday by 15 Jewish
settlers from Nili who allegedly burned and shot up Palestinian
buildings in the village of Harbata in response to a stone-throwing
attack.
   The settlers, who have denied their involvement, were ordered to
report for questioning Monday.
   The 21 Palestinians reported wounded Monday in clashes with the
army were from six Gaza Strip refugee camps and a Gaza City
district, Arab doctors said.
   Army officials said did not confirm any of the reported
casualties Monday but confirmed four of 53 Palestinians that Arab
hospital officials said were wounded the day before.
   The army reported soldiers killed a Palestinian on Sunday in a
raid on the West Bank village of Deir Sudan. Arab reporters said he
was killed Sunday night when soldiers fired on youths throwing
stones.
   The death brought to 444 the number of Palestinians killed in
the uprising. Eighteen Israelis also have been killed.
   Palestinian reporters said Arab shepherds found the body of a
22-year-old Palestinian from the West Bank village of Tamoun who
had been stabbed to death and his eyes gouged out. Villagers said
Rifhi Mohammed Oude was seen being led from his home Sunday night
by masked Palestinians, but it was not clear why he had been killed.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutweiler
said: ``The increase in tensions runs directly counter to the cause
of peace. ... We remain determined to work with all parties to
break out of the current confrontation and to replace violence with
political dialogue and accommodation.''
   Extreme rightists were blamed for threats or attacks aimed at an
Israeli publisher and two left-wing politicians.
   Terrorists set fire to the door of an apartment belonging to
Amos Shocken, a publisher of the Haaretz and Hadashot newspapers.
Israel radio reported an anonymous telephone caller said the attack
was carried out by the Sicarites, a Jewish underground group,
because ``Shocken harms the morals of the Israeli people.''
   Hadashot said Yossi Sarid, a member of parliament from the
Citizens Rights Movement, receivewd several death threats Sunday
from a caller claiming to be a member of the Sicarites. Sarid has
recommended negotiations with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Avraham Zimmerman of the leftist Mapam party said assailants
slashed the tires of his car and plastered it with stickers from
the anti-Arab Kach Party of Rabbi Meir Kahane.
</TEXT>
