<FIRST>r a AM-EcclesiaTrial     04-24 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecclesia Trial,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Beaten 500 Times, Prosecutor Alleges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 8-year-old daughter of the leader
of a disciplinary group for ghetto children was beaten more than
500 times as an example to others before she died, a prosecutor
alleged Monday.
   Dayna Broussard was beaten in a garage used by the Ecclesia
Athletic Association after she defied adults who tried to punish
her for taking food from another child's plate, said Alfred J.
French III, a deputy Clackamas County district.
   French, delivering his opening statement in the manslaughter
trial of four group members, said the punishment intensified over a
one- to two-hour period until the child was left gasping for
breath. When adults finally took the child to a fire station for
help early Oct. 14, she was dead.
   French said the victim's older brother was forced to count the
strokes as the punishment was administered with a rubber hose, an
electric cord, a piece of plastic pipe, a bamboo pole and a
weightlifting belt.
   More than 50 other children in the group were forced to watch,
he said.
   And at one point, defendant Constance Jackson bit the girl on
the cheek, and, with her teeth, lifted her from the cement floor
``and shook her like a dog,'' French said.
   Monday's opening arguments followed 11 weeks of jury selection
in one of the most highly publicized criminal cases in Oregon
history.
   The father of the dead girl, Eldridge Broussard Jr., is expected
to testify for the defense. Broussard was in Los Angeles when his
daughter was killed.
   Broussard has said he formed the association to divert
inner-city children from a life of drugs and crime through
athletics and tough discipline.
   In their opening statements, attorneys for two of the four
defendants reminded jurors that Ecclesia's home base, the Watts
Christian Center, was surrounded by violence in the Los Angeles
ghetto.
   Jack Bernstein, the attorney for defendant Frederick P.
Doolittle, said members of the mostly black group were different
from the all-white jury because of their race and because of the
way they had to live among drug dealers and prostitutes in the
crime-ridden Watts district.
   Separate trials before a single jury are being held for
Doolittle, 28, Jackson, 38, and Brian J. Brinson, 31, all of Los
Angeles; and Willie K. Chambers, 35, of San Diego. The trial went
on in Oregon City after Circuit Judge John Lowe refused to move it
to another county.
   Dayna Broussard was one of more than 50 children brought to the
foothills of Mount Hood, east of Portland, last year while the
Watts Christian Center was being renovated.
</TEXT>
