<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     04-24 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evening On Rushdie Postponed Due To Bomb and Murder Threats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers on Monday postponed a
discussion on the novel ``The Satanic Verses'' after participants
received bomb and murder threats, a spokesman said.
   In Paris, a writer has published a pirated translation of the
novel by British author Salman Rushdie and said Monday he will
personally deliver a copy to the Iranian Embassy on Tuesday.
   ``Death threats, I couldn't care less,'' Jean-Edern Hallier told
a news conference.
   Some Moslems say Rushdie's novel blasphemes Islam because it
includes a brothel scene in which the prostitutes take the names of
the prophet Mohammed's wives and because it suggests Mohammed wrote
the holy Koran instead of receiving it from God.
   On Feb. 14, Iran's revolutionary patriarch, Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, called for Rushdie to be put to death. The Indian-born
author has been in hiding since then.
   Monday's discussion in Vienna, entitled ``Salman Rushdie, The
Satanic Verses, Opposition and Liquidation'' was to include a
reading from the book and a discussion including Iranian
participants and a representative of the human rights group Amnesty
International, organizers said.
   Wolfgang Weiss, a spokesman for a university students union
sponsoring the program, said the Iranian participants had received
death threats and the university adminstration had received bomb
threats.
   A statement issued by the organizers said that the event was
being postponed because it was no longer possible to guarantee the
safety of the audience or participants.
   It gave no date for the event to be rescheduled.
   Hallier, who distributed typed copies of the book to reporters,
said he published a French translation of ``The Satanic Verses'' to
``save the honor of French publishing.''
   He accused publisher Christian Bourgois, who holds French rights
to the work, of dragging his feet out of fear of reprisal from
Moslem fanatics.
   Following the death sentence pronounced on Rushdie, Bourgois
announced he would not publish the book. He later changed his mind
and said the book would appear.
   On a request filed by attorneys representing Bourgois, a court
in the southern French city of Montpelier ordered copies of the
pirated book seized from a printer on Saturday. A Paris court has
ordered the immediate seizure of any copies of the pirated book
that appear on newsstands.
   But Hallier said 1,000 copies that were printed at another
location would be distributed Tuesday, including one he would
deliver Tuesday to the Iranian ambassador to France.
   He said he planned a countersuit against Bourgois and that
50,000 more copies of the manuscript would be distributed
throughout Paris Wednesday as a supplement to his magazine, ``Idiot
International.''
   The book has caused protests worldwide, and demonstrations over
its publication have led to the deaths of at least 19 people in
Pakistan and India.
</TEXT>
