<FIRST>u a AM-Lawyer-MachineGun     04-24 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lawyer-Machine Gun,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney Contends Authorities Trying To Entrap Him Into Betraying
Clients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURANGO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer accused of receiving a stolen Uzi
submachine gun sought to have the charge dismissed Monday,
contending he was the target of an entrapment scheme by authorities
to force him to betray his clients.
   Attorney Robin Auld's lawyer, Hal Haddon, asked Montrose
District Judge Richard Brown to dismiss the charge because of
``outrageous misconduct'' by District Attorney Victor Reichman and
other law enforcement officials.
   Auld, 43, contends Reichman and law enforcement officials set
him up, arrested him Oct. 29, and later offered not to file charges
if he would agree to help them set up his own clients.
   Haddon has said the case is crucial to the attorney-client
relationship in Colorado.
   According to documents filed in the case, undercover Sheriff's
Deputy Brent Pace, posing as ``Colton Young,'' asked Auld, a
criminal defense lawyer, to represent him in a case.
   Auld won dismissal of the charges. The undercover officer
offered to pay Auld for his services with drugs, but the attorney
declined. Pace then offered him the Uzi, saying he told Auld it was
stolen. Auld said he agreed to hold the gun as security for the
money Pace owed him, according to the documents.
   The charges against ``Colton Young'' were false.
   Durango police Sgt. John Ball testified at Monday's pretrial
hearing that authorities were concerned about making false
statements to a court, ``but we never expected it would get that
far.''
   Reichman and Ball, who were questioned extensively by Haddon,
gave contradictory testimony.
   Reichman denied that he offered criminal suspects deals in
return for information on Auld. Ball, however, said Reichman agreed
not to file drunken driving charges against an informant in
exchange for help in the Auld investigation.
   Haddon also requested greater access to law enforcement files,
and sought to have tape recordings of conversations between Auld
and Pace thrown out.
   Under questioning, Reichman said there were no tape recordings
or notes on conversations he had with federal authorities about the
case.
   The district attorney said taping a federal prosecutor would be
highly inappropriate. ``I wouldn't think of such a thing,'' he said.
   Asked by Haddon how he felt about taping a conversation between
an attorney and a client, Reichman said, ``that would depend on the
circumstances.''
   The hearing was scheduled to continue Tuesday. Auld's trial is
scheduled to begin May 22.
   Haddon has also filed an intent to sue Reichman and others on
behalf of Auld for at least $1 million.
</TEXT>
