<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says International Crimes Financed Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators of Pan Am Flight 103, destroyed by a
bomb over Scotland, believe they have uncovered a series of
international crimes whose proceeds finance terrorists, The Times
of London reported Monday.
   It said the investigators found links between robberies that
netted $11 million in Denmark and the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine- General Command, which some accuse of
planning the Dec. 21 bombing that killed 270 people.
   Detectives are trying to trace the source of tens of millions of
dollars hidden in secret accounts that have made some terrorists
``enormously rich and powerful,'' The Times reported.
   Inspector Thomas McCulloch of the international investigation
based in Lockerbie, Scotland, said: ``We're aware of an ongoing
investigation by the Danish and it would be quite improper for us
to comment any further at this time.''
   Investigators believe the money has been used to ``create
terrorism schools, to buy sophisticated equipment and explosives
and develop new ways of beating airline security systems,'' The
Times reported.
   The paper said police found links between terrorists arrested in
West Germany in October, with radio-cassette players rigged as
bombs like the one that destroyed Flight 103, and the $11 million
stolen in Denmark. It said the money went to the Popular Front.
   Seven people were arrested, including two of Middle East
extraction, in Copenhagen but Danish courts have not confirmed the
theories, according to the report.
   Samuel Skinner, the U.S. transportation secretary, is expected
to discuss airport security with Paul Channon, his British
counterpart, when Skinner arrives Thursday at the end of a
week-long tour of Italy, West Germany, Switzerland and France.
