<TEXT>
   Longer version moved on the business
wire.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines would slash daily service by 29
percent and sell $1.8 billion in assets under a new business plan
presented to creditors of the strike-crippled airline Monday.
   The proposal, which must be approved by creditors and a federal
bankruptcy court, calls for Eastern to reduce its fleet size to 157
aircraft from the present 255 and the number of cities served to 77
from a pre-strike 102.
   The number of daily scheduled flight hours would be cut to 1,473
from 2,076 under the plan.
   Eastern has been flying substantially reduced schedules since a
March 4 strike by its Machinists, which was joined by Eastern's
pilots and flight attendants unions. The company sought bankruptcy
court protection from creditors on March 9.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent Texas Air Corp., said
last week he would reorganize the airline by slashing pre-strike
operations and selling a substantial number of assets.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes would not specify all the cities
where Eastern would cut service, but he told a press briefing the
company would sell its Philadelphia hub, a total of 117 unspecified
airport gates and 28 landing slots. Eastern would also de-emphasize
some foreign routes.
   Bakes said Eastern would keep its Atlanta hub, which accounts
for 35 percent to 40 percent of total revenue, in addition to
traditional Northeast-to-Florida routes. It would also maintain
some service to the Caribbean.
   Employment at the scaled-down Eastern would total some 17,000
workers, down from a pre-strike 30,000, Bakes said. The total would
include 1,700 pilots, down from 3,600 before the strike, he said.
   Paul Dombroski, a spokesman for the Machinists in Miami, said
the plan was similar to one used by Texas Air carrier Continental
Airlines in 1983, ``and it didn't work over there. ... We in the
Machinists union don't feel they can make it work at Eastern
Airlines either.''
   Eastern indicated that by yearend under the plan it would have
$1.8 billion in net cash from asset sales, giving it a net cash
balance of $774 million.
   Lorenzo has insisted he no longer is interested in selling all
of Eastern, following the collapse of a proposed $464 million deal
with a group led by former baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland and Eastern's unions
have been pushing for a sale.
   Separately, a bankruptcy examiner said Monday that further bids
to acquire Eastern could be made as early as this week by suitors
who include hotel executive Jay Pritzker and Trans World Airlines
Chairman Carl C. Icahn.
   Examiner David I. Shapiro said at a bankruptcy court hearing
that he had ``numerous interviews'' with parties interested in
buying the airline from Texas Air and confirmed earlier reports
that Pritzker had been given access to confidential financial data
concerning the airline.
   Shapiro also said TWA officials had expressed interest in
getting access to the financial data.
   Shapiro told Lifland at a hearing that in addition to Pritzker
and Icahn two major financial institutions had emerged as new
serious bidders for Eastern, but he declined to give details.
   The two institutions could submit bids this week or next,
Shapiro said.
   Lifland postponed until May 3 a hearing scheduled for Monday on
why Eastern shouldn't be sold in its entirety in an open auction.
Such a deal would include Eastern's Northeast shuttle service,
which the company already has agreed to sell to developer Donald
Trump for $365 million.
   The delay was intended to give potential buyers more time to
examine Eastern's financial data and to give parties involved in
the airline's bankruptcy case more time to negotiate over a
possible reorganization plan.
   The delay also was intended to give Shapiro more time to study
documents submitted by Eastern management and unions regarding
previous financial transactions between Miami-based Eastern and
Texas Air.
</TEXT>
