<FIRST>r a AM-MarketShooting     04-24 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Market Shooting,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Man Convicted in Supermarket Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man described as a ``coldblooded
killer'' was found guilty Monday of murdering five people in a 1987
supermarket hold-up by two gunmen who authorities say posed as
cleaning men.
   A Circuit Court jury convicted Donnie Blankenship, 27, of five
counts of second-degree murder and one count each of robbery,
unlawful use of a weapon and receiving stolen property.
   Blankenship faces a maximum sentence of 205 years in prison.
Sentencing was scheduled for June 8.
   Prosecutors had sought first-degree murder convictions, which
could have resulted in a death sentence.
   Blankenship's attorney, Linda Murphy, said she would appeal, but
said she considered the verdict a victory. She said the jury
apparently believed her client was involved in the robbery but was
not the triggerman.
   Special prosecutor Garrett L. Randall agreed the jury must have
had some doubt about Blankenship's role in the slayings.
   In his closing argument, Randall called Blankenship a
``coldblooded killer'' who deserved the death penalty.
   The jury reached its decision late Monday morning after
deliberations that began Saturday. The panel did not meet Sunday.
   On Sept. 4, 1987, two men entered the National Supermarket after
closing time, apparently by posing as a cleaning crew, police said.
Six store employees and a security guard were forced to lie on the
floor, then were shot. The two who survived testified at
Blankenship's trial.
   The other gunman, Marvin Jennings, 27, was convicted last
September of 16 felony counts, including five counts of first
degree murder. He was sentenced to five consecutive life prison
terms without parole.
   Chris Brown, whose mother, head cashier Rose M. Brown, 49, was
among those slain, expressed satisfaction about Monday's verdict.
   ``I think all of us are more or less glad it's over now,'' Brown
said. ``The verdict is in and we know that Donnie Blankenship, like
Marvin Jennings, will be off the street for quite some time.''
</TEXT>
