<DOCNO> AP890424-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Politics     04-24 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Politics,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini Names Committee To Amend Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini named a
20-man committee Monday to amend Iran's constitution, Tehran radio
reported _ a move that could have far-reaching implications,
including the question of who will succeed the 88-year-old Khomeini
when he dies.
   The committee included President Ali Khamenei, Prime Minister
Hussein Musavi and Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani. It was
given two months to ``rectify the defects'' in the Islamic
Republic's 1980 constitution.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said Khomeini announced the
committee's formation in a letter to Khamenei.
   ``After 10 years of experience in governing the country, many
authorities and officials ... are of the opinion that the
constitution ... contains defects and problems,'' he wrote.
   ``Rectifying these defects is an unavoidable necessity for our
Islamic and revolutionary society, and delays could cause
catastrophies and bitter results for the country and the
revolution.''
   Khomeini said officials had asked him to correct the
constitution's flaws and clarify its ambiguities, the radio said.
   This month, 160 members of the 270-seat Parliament urged
Khomeini to make constitutional changes. The Supreme Judicial
Council later endorsed that call.
   Khomeini said the constitutional amendments will be put to
Iran's electorate in a referendum. He did not say when.
   Among issues Khomeini said should be discussed were the
leadership question and the powers of the judiciary and executive
branches.
   Khomeini removed his designated successor, Ayatollah Hussein-Ali
Montazeri, last month, saying Montazeri had been duped by enemies
of the revolution.
   Montazeri, 64, demanded wider freedoms following the end of the
war with Iraq and asked that widespread executions of political
dissidents be halted.
   Political analysts believe no single individual, but a committee
of three to five leaders will run Iran in the post-Khomeini era.
   The new committee is to make the constitutional changes needed
to accommodate such a council.
   Khomeini is widely believed to favor this in the absence of
anyone of his stature or authority to take his place.
   Another major issue is executive branch power. An unclear
division of power exists between the presidency and the premiership.
   Rafsanjani has announced his candidacy for the presidency in
elections to be held in late summer. He reportedly wants the prime
minister's post abolished and the presidency strengthened to
eliminate competing power centers that have paralyzed the
decision-making process.
   The committee appeared to be more or less split evenly between
hardliners and so-called pragmatists.
   Others prominent figures chosen included Chief Justice Musavi
Ardebili, Deputy Parliament Speaker Mehdi Karrubi, Chief Justice
Ayatollah Musavi Ardebili and Prosecutor-General Musavi Khoeiniha.
   Absent, however, was Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi,
leader of the hard-line faction now in the ascendancy in Iran.
   Khomeini also asked the committee to clarify the role of the
Expediency Council. He formed that body in 1987 to resolve
differences between Parliament and the Council of Guardians, a
conservative-dominated watchdog body with the power to veto
parliamentary legislation it considers violate Islamic law.
   Radicals criticized the Expediency Council for sidestepping
Parliament by initiating and passing bills not approved by
Parliament.
   These included harsh new anti-narcotics laws that mandated the
death sentence for possession of small quantities of drugs.
   Khomeini also asked the committee to review the powers of the
management of the state-run Islamic Republic Radio and Television
network. This may mean the broadcast services face curbs because
hardliners believe they promote certain political leaders, such as
Rafsanjani, and exclude others.
   Rafsanjani, once considered the No. 2 man in Iran after
Khomeini, has slipped from favor as the radicals strengthened their
grip.
   He sought to build bridges with the West to end Iran's 10 years
of isolation, a move bitterly opposed by hard-line, anti-Western
rivals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
