<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Pipeline     04-24 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Pipeline,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Blow Up Gasoline Pipeline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels blew up a gasoline
pipeline Monday in the fourth attack on Colombian petroleum
facilities within a week.
   The National Liberation Army, known as ELN, claimed
reponsibility for the attack, according to Ecopetrol, the
government's petroleum company.
   ELN has vowed to drive foreign oil companies out of Colombia and
last Tuesday its guerrillas bombed the country's largest oil
pipeline at three points. The oil line is still out of operation,
but Ecopetrol said service could be restored on Tuesday.
   A bomb damaged the gasoline pipeline near the town of La Cumbre,
175 miles west of Bogota, Ecopetrol said in a news release. It said
it expected the line would be quickly repaired and there would be
no shortage because of an ample supply of stored fuels.
   The pipeline carries 25,000 barrels of imported gasoline daily
from the Pacific port of Buenaventura to the eastern city of Cali.
   It was the 10th time this year that ELN rebels have attacked oil
installations in Colombia.
   The damaged oil pipeline carried an average 220,000 barrels
daily from the Canon Limon field in northeastern Colombia to the
Caribbean port of Covenas for export.
   The Canon Limon field is jointly operated by Ecopetrol, Royal
Dutch Shell and Occidental Petroleum.
   On Wednesday, ELN guerrillas attacked a drilling rig operated by
Ecopetrol and the Brazilian oil company Petrobras and kidnapped
four engineers _ three Brazilians and a Colombian. No demands have
been made public for the release of the victims.
   Two days later the same guerrilla unit raided a Colombian oil
company's camp in the northeast and stole a $17,000 payroll.
</TEXT>
