<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-24 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in the Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms unleashed heavy rain and golf ball-sized
hail Monday in the upper Midwest, and spring snow fell in
mountainous sections of the West. Temperatures hit record highs in
Kansas, Nebraska and Missouri.
   Isolated strong thunderstorms struck in northwest Iowa, south
central Minnesota and northeastern North Dakota.
   Large hail fell in or near the Iowa cities of Spencer, Everly
and Royal, and on Cando, N.D. One Iowa storm dumped heavy rain,
including 3{ inches of rain near Hartly and 2{ inches in Sutherland.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms also fell in western Texas,
and from eastern Kentucky to western North Carolina and northern
South Carolina.
   Rain and some thunderstorms fell in northern and central
California and western Oregon.
   Snow continued to fall at higher altitudes in northern
California, as well as in the mountains of southern Oregon. Snow
advisories remained in effect in Oregon for the southern Cascades
and the Siskiyou Mountains.
   Snow also fell in Nevada and New Hampshire. Two inches fell in
the same six-hour period in Winnemucca, Nev., and Mount Washington,
N.H.
   Temperatures climbed into the 90s in western and central Kansas
and southeast Nebraska.
   Records for the date were set in Concordia, Kan., where it was
89 degrees, 1 degree over the 1954 mark; Kansas City, Mo., (88
degrees, 84 degrees in 1986); Lincoln, Neb., (91, 90 in 1960); and
in St. Joseph, Mo. (89, 87 in 1986).
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees in South Lake Tahoe, Calif., to 99 degrees in Hays, Kan.
The nation's low Monday morning was 17 degrees in Gunnison, Colo.
   Tuesday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the northern Plains and the upper Mississippi
Valley to the central Plains and the Texas Panhandle; rain showers
from the central and southern Pacific Coast to the northern and
central Intermountain region to Montana; snow across the northern
Rockies; and snow showers in northern Maine.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s in the northern
Rockies and northern Maine; the 50s and 60s from the Pacific Coast
to the intermountain region, much of the northern Plains, northern
Minnesota, the Great Lakes and New England; the 90s from western
Texas to much of Kansas and Missouri and to southern Illinois and
generally in the 70s and 80s in the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
