<FIRST>u i AM-Korea-Bombing     04-24 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Bombing,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Confessed North Korean Agent Sentenced to Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court convicted a confessed North
Korean agent Tuesday and sentenced her to hang for the 1987 bombing
of a South Korean airliner that killed all 115 people on board.
   However, government officials have said privately they expect a
pardon to be granted later.
   The agent, Kim Hyon Hui, burst into tears when the Seoul
District Court found her guilty of violating national security and
aviation laws and sentenced her to death by hanging.
   Relatives of the plane victims sat quietly in court as they
heard the verdict.
   The court ruled Kim was guilty of planting a bomb aboard a
Korean Air Boeing 707 that disappeared Nov. 29, 1987, on a flight
from Baghdad, Iraq, to Seoul. It was lost over the Andaman Sea as
it approached the Burmese coast.
   Kim, a 27-year-old North Korean, had confessed to planting a
bomb on the plane and said she wanted to die to atone for the
deaths of the victims.
   Her legal counsel said after the verdict that no decision was
made on whether to appeal.
   South Korean government officials have said they did not expect
a death sentence for Kim would be carried out, despite her
confession of plotting to bomb the plane as part of a North Korean
plan to disrupt last summer's Olympic Games in Seoul.
   Officials said Kim was expected to be pardoned on grounds she
was duped by communist North Korea and has repented.
   North Korea has denied involvement in the airplane attack. It
says South Korea engineered the bombing to embarrass the communist
North.
</TEXT>
