<FIRST>r a AM-StadiumLeap     04-24 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stadium Leap,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Leaps to Death at Shea Stadium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman climbed to the top of the right field
foul pole at empty Shea Stadium on Monday and jumped 120 feet to
her death on the playing field, police said.
   Police said the woman, clad only in a plain flannel shirt,
climbed over a fence to get into the stadium, then used some cables
near the orange pole to get to the top, according to two
groundskeepers who saw the incident.
   She dived from the pole shortly after 9 a.m., said police
spokeswoman Officer Janice Swinney.
   The rest of the woman's clothing was found outside the stadium,
near the ticket sales booth, police said. No identification was
found, and the woman left no note.
   The woman, estimated to be between 30 and 40 years old, was
pronounced dead at the scene.
   ``This is just a tragedy,'' said Jay Horwitz, spokesman for the
New York Mets, who play at the stadium in Queens. ``We're sorry
someone was that distraught they would do this.''
   He said the woman landed ``in the right corner of right field,''
in what would be foul territory during a game.
   A foul pole is used by umpires to judge whether a batted ball in
the air is fair or foul.
   Monday's incident was not the first suicide at the 25-year-old
stadium. ``In the early 1980s someone jumped from a ramp near Gate
C and landed outside the stadium,'' Horwitz said.
   The spokesman said there were no plans to change security in
light of the incident. ``We have security here 24 hours a day, what
can you do if someone wants to do this? Unfortunately, they're
going to find a way.''
   The Mets, who had no game Monday, are scheduled to play the
Atlanta Braves at Shea on Tuesday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
