<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Strike 1stLd-Writethru a0748 04-24 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0748,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Teachers March For Union Democracy, More Pay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with higher crowd estimate, details
on forced resignation of union chief. CORRECTS name from Elva to Elba.
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150,000 striking teachers and
supporters crowded the city's main plaza Monday, shouting slogans,
carrying banners demanding pay raises and union democracy and
celebrating the resignation of their union boss.
   The departure of Carlos Jonguitud Barrios, who ran the union for
17 years, was a major demand of the dissident teachers. However,
their leader, Teodoro Palomino, said the walkout will continue
until all demands were met, including a 100 percent raise.
   He said the turnout at the march, ``despite threats of
dismissals, shows the determination of the teachers to keep
fighting.''
   The National Education Workers' Coordinate claims the support of
500,000 of the 1.1 million members of the National Education
Workers' Union, the largest and one of the strongest in Mexico and
all Latin America.
   Among the thousands of banners that teachers carried were ones
reading, ``Respectable Salary Increase and Democracy,'' ``100
Percent Salary Increase.'' Several key members of Jonguitud's
faction, including union Secretary-General Jose Refugio Araujo,
stepped down after Jonguitud resigned Sunday after a meeting with
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   Salinas ousted the oil workers' union boss in January.
Government sources said on condition of anonymity that Salinas
planned for months to squeeze out Jonguitud, but waited for the
proper moment. They said Jonguitud's resignation was a first step
toward cleaning up the union.
   ``The union has developed a certain life style over the last 17
years that won't be easy to change,'' the sources said.
   Jonguitud was probably the most important union boss remaining
from a clique that held labor in line and turned out the vote for
the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party in exchange for
political office and the power that goes with control of the
coffers of large labor organizations.
   Jonguitud retains his post as a federal senator.
   The union's national council on Monday chose Elba Esther
Gordillo Morales as new secretary-general.
   Many dissidents complained she is aligned with the old guard
loyal to the Institutional Revolutionary Party, but Palomino said
she ``signifies a change, the possibility of deepening democracy
within the union.''
   The dissidents demand free union elections as well as a raise.
They rejected government offers of a 10 percent salary increase and
an 18 percent benefits raise.
   ``Ten percent, ha, ha, ha!,'' marchers shouted, some of them
shielding themselves from the hot sun with umbrellas.
   Teachers take home an average of $142 a month.
   It is common for teachers to hold two jobs to make ends meet,
working in public schools during one session, in a private school
during the other. Many drive taxis.
   Talks between the union factions will resume following a weekend
recess, Palomino said.
   ``The departure of Jonguitud is a triumph of the dissident
movement, but not the solution to the conflict, which will only be
overcome when the salary and union demands are met
satisfactorily,'' the coordinate's negotiating commission said.
   The strikers ignored a warning from the Education Department
that sanctions would be taken against those not in the classroom on
Monday.
   Salinas has cracked down on union bosses, ordering oil workers'
boss Joaquin Hernandez Galicia to jail in January on weapons
charges and orchestrating the removal of musician's union leader
Venus Rey.
   Unlike Hernandez Galicia, who was open in his dislike for
Salinas, Jonguitud cooperated with the administration, following
party tradition, and had been considered safe from the union
cleanup campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
