<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Anderson     04-24 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Anderson,1st ld-writethru a0643,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs at end with new Peggy Say comment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Quayle-AP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush promised Monday to ``go the extra
mile'' to seek the release of U.S. hostages held in Lebanon.
   Bush, speaking before the annual luncheon of The Associated
Press, introduced the topic by saying he wanted to ``say a word
about Terry Anderson,'' chief Middle East correspondent of the AP,
who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   ``I just want to say without being able to give you any good
news that we are concerned; we will follow every intelligence lead;
we will go the extra mile to do what we can,'' he said.
   ``We will continue to keep this question of the hostages on the
front burner,'' the president said.
   Anderson, the longest held hostage, is among nine Americans the
State Department says are held in Lebanon. The others are Thomas
Sutherland, Frank Reed, Joseph James Cicippio, Edward Austin Tracy,
Jesse Turner, Robert Polhill, Alann Steen and William Higgins.
   Anderson, 41, has been seen or heard from only in pictures and
videotapes released by his captors and in news from freed hostages.
   At a ceremony in Washington last month marking the fourth year
since his kidnapping, the State Department issued a statement
saying: ``The hostage holders should release their captives
immediately and unconditionally, and we call on all countries with
influence over the hostages, such as Iran, to use that influence to
obtain freedom for all the hostages.''
   Anderson's sister, Peggy Say, who has led private efforts on his
behalf, said in March he was ``frustrated, tired and lonely ... and
tired of being caged like an animal.''
   Officials say the hostages are held by various factions but that
all are elements of the umbrella group Hezbollah over which Iran
exhibits control.
   Reacting to Bush's statement Monday, Ms. Say said, ``it's a
difficult place to be, to hear that we have no good news after more
than four years. It's a little disheartening. At the same time, I
can only hope that the hostages will be a major priority of this
administration.''
   ``I think one of the hardest tings for the families to accept is
that there doesn't seem to be any sense of urgency,'' she said.
</TEXT>
