<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SovietDefections     04-24 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Defections,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Soviets Defect During Border Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviets defected while government officials were
signing a protocol aimed at easing travel restrictions between
Alaska and Siberia, the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
said Monday.
   The INS issued a brief news release that said the Soviets
approached an Alaska National Guard Eskimo Scout and asked for
political asylum just hours before the signing ceremony on Sunday.
   The scout notified his commander, who contacted the INS in Nome,
said INS spokesman Gary Johnson. The INS gave the Soviets
permission to stay on Little Diomede Island, and they spent the
night in the National Guard Armory there.
   Johnson said the Soviets would be flown to Nome, and on to
Anchorage when weather permitted.
   There was no word on whether the rest of the Soviet delegation
raised any objections to what took place. Nor was it clear whether
the delegation had returned home. Telephone service to the remote
island in the Bering Strait was disrupted by bad weather Monday.
   The Soviets were on Little Diomede for a ceremony involving
Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper and his counterpart from the Magadan
region of Siberia. The protocol they signed urged the U.S. and
Soviet governments to approve a border commission to handle visits
by Eskimos between Alaska and Siberia.
   The Eskimos would not need visas to make the trip, under the
terms of the protocol.
   The fog and blowing snow had prevented Cowper from reaching
Little Diomede on Sunday, and the signing ceremony was conducted by
telephone.
   The ceremony was held in conjunction with the Bering Bridge
Expedition, a skiing and sled dog journey from Siberia to Alaska.
The expedition consists of six Soviets and six Americans. Two of
the Soviets and two of the Americans are Eskimos.
   A number of Eskimo families were separated when the Soviets
closed the border in the Bering Strait at the onset of the Cold War
in the late 1940s.
   There was no word whether the defectors were Eskimos.
   The Soviet island of Big Diomede three miles across the strait
from Little Diomede is a military installation. The Eskimos who
once lived there were relocated to the Siberian mainland in the
1950s.
</TEXT>
