<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Turner-Resignation     04-24 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turner-Resignation,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Police Chief to Quit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia Police Chief Maurice T.
Turner has submitted his retirement papers and will step down July
31, according to The Washington Post.
   Turner, who could not be reached for comment, had been
increasingly at odds with Mayor Marion S. Barry over the past few
months, the newspaper reported in its Tuesday editions.
   Turner has been with the Washington police department for the
past 32 years, and Barry said that he will begin a search for a new
police chief immediately.
   Asst. Chief Isaac Fulwood, the department's second-ranking
official, will be named to succeed Turner, the Post reported.
   In a statement issued by his office Monday night, Barry praised
Turner saying, ``Chief Turner has had an illustrious and
distinguished career in law enforcement. He is respected both
locally and nationally for his leadership of the finest police
department in the country.''
   Turner is said to be in line for a consultant's position with
the office of national drug policy director William J. Bennett, the
Post said.
</TEXT>
