<DOCNO> AP890424-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0646EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     04-24 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0682</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lane Kirkland sees the ``sanctification of
greed'' he attributes to the Reagan years beginning to crumble,
bringing favorable winds to the sails of the movement he often
refers to as a ship.
   ``I think there is perhaps the beginning of some change in
climate,'' the AFL-CIO president said in an interview last week.
``We've been beating against some fairly strong winds, but I think
the ship is sound and seaworthy. And winds change.''
   His is a view cautiously shared by other labor leaders, who in
recent weeks have found themselves awash with good news, a rare
tiding in a decade the American labor movement would prefer to
forget.
   Few labor leaders expect a sudden turnaround of the decline of
the 1980s, during which membership in unions has dropped by 3
million to 17 million and the percentage of workers who are union
members dropped from 23 percent in 1980 to 16.8 percent last year.
   But many believe the passing of the Reagan administration and
labor's recent high profile may help unions halt their slide and
improve their public standing.
   ``I think the American people are listening to what we are
saying and, yes, I think things are progressing,'' United Auto
Workers President Owen Bieber said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of students at Beijing's
universities went on strike today, calling for democracy, human
rights and a free press in the largest student boycott in Communist
China's history.
   At Beijing University, the country's most prestigious, students
for the first time produced an independent newspaper.
   The class boycott today brought into a new phase pro-democracy
protests that were sparked by the April 15 death of ousted
Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang, a popular reformer.
   Posters calling on students to strike, satirical cartoons of
government leaders, and essays decrying official corruption covered
the walls of many universities throughout Beijing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCKY BOY, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a century after frontier wars
ceased on the plains and valleys of Montana, Indians are embroiled
in a new battle for independence against the federal government.
   On the Rocky Boys Indian Reservation in north-central Montana, a
tribal prosecutor has filed criminal charges against the chief
agent of the Bureau of Indian Affairs, accusing him of interfering
in tribal affairs by threatening not to recognize an elected tribal
government.
   The case has implications nationwide for Indian tribes' power to
control their own governments and reservations.
   ``My whole idea in this thing was, `How much authority does this
guy have?''' said Chippewa-Cree Tribal Prosecutor Jim Morsette.
``This is a problem not only in Rocky Boy, but on all the
reservations.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WAPATO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In central Washington's Yakima Valley,
where fruit trees bloom in blazing sunshine, fear has taken root
because of an outbreak of a contagious disease that has killed six
people this year.
   Twenty people, including four infants, have become ill with
meningococcal bacteria, which can lead to meningitis and other
illnesses.
   Doctors are swamped, firefighters worried about giving
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, parents pulled their children out of
preschools, and about 18,000 people have been vaccinated.
   The greatest worry is that there is no effective vaccine,
therefore no protection, for children under age 1.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MAAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The carcasses of burnt cars and shattered
window frames are being swept off the streets of Jordan's
riot-swept southern towns.
   People say the anger vented in four days of violence last week
to protest government-imposed austerity measures will not disappear
so easily.
   Jordan has in recent years escaped most of the Middle East's
turmoil so last week's outbreak of discontent _ from people who for
generations have been the monarchy's staunchest loyalists _ came as
a shock.
   ``The rioters want things to get better in Jordan,'' said a
25-year-old man from the city of Kerak who said he was among the
stone-throwers who attacked government buildings and banks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
