<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Canada-Embassy Adv28   04-24 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Embassy, Adv 28,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs April 28 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Canadian Embassy in Washington Designed to Carry a Message</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, note May 3 date 3rd graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada has built a new embassy in Washington and
the architect says it is designed to carry a message.
   ``Our mandate from External Affairs was that the building was to
demonstrate good neighborliness and openness, friendliness,''
architect Arthur Erickson said in an interview. ``We really took
them as the basic theme for the building.''
   Canada is the only nation to have an embassy on Pennsylvania
Avenue, the thoroughfare between the U.S. Capitol and the White
House. Prime Minister Brian Mulroney will attend the inauguration
May 3.
   As for the location, Erickson said: ``I think in light of the
new trade agreement and everything else, it's becoming even more
significant.''
   A free-trade agreement with the United States went into effect
Jan. 1.
   The Canadian maple leaf flag already is flying over the embassy
across the street from the new East Building of the National
Gallery of Art.
   The architect is a native of British Columbia who maintains
offices there, in Los Angeles and in Toronto. He is the only
Canadian who has received the gold medal of the American Institute
of Architects.
   The Washington site was acquired more than a decade ago during
an early stage of Pennsylvania Avenue's revival.
   Erickson said he intended the embassy to get across the idea of
welcoming as well. He added that he wanted to demonstrate not only
Canada's unique qualities but also its close relationship with the
United States.
   ``You acknowledge the similarities of cultural background and
that sort of the thing but at the same time indicate the
differences,'' he said.
   The architect said the enormous span that is the most visible
feature of the building was intended to bring to mind the vastness
of spaces in Canada, the world's second-largest country.
   ``It's a very generous span, and that to me represented the
sweep and generosity of, I hate to say the Canadian landscape, but
I guess that's really what I mean,'' he said.
   The 12 pillars on the embassy's rotunda represent Canada's 10
provinces and two territories. A final touch for the entrance, due
to be ready in about a year, will be an 18-foot by 12-foot ``spirit
canoe'' sculpture by artist Bill Reid of the Haida people native to
British Columbia's Queen Charlotte Islands.
   Not all comment on the highly visible embassy has been positive.
   The Canadian news weekly Maclean's, in a report from Washington
critical enough to prompt Erickson to write a letter to the editor,
said the building was ``drawing praise and raising eyebrows,
objections and arguments.''
   Erickson, who was born in Vancouver in 1924, said he wrote his
response because he considered the article an example of ``typical
Canadian sour grapes about anything a Canadian accomplishes.''
   Derek Burney, Canada's new ambassador to the United States, told
Maclean's the new embassy is ``a strong and confident building for
a strong and confident Canada. ... It conveys the message that I
want to convey: Canada counts.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs April 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
