<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv30   04-24 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv30,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, April 30, the 120th day of 1989. There are 245
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Two hundred years ago, on April 30, 1789, George Washington took
the oath of office as the first president of the United States
during a ceremony in New York.
   On this date:
   In 1803, the United States purchased the Louisiana Territory
from France.
   In 1812, Louisiana entered the Union as the 18th state.
   In 1900, Hawaii was organized as a U.S. territory.
   In 1900, engineer John Luther ``Casey'' Jones of the Illinois
Central Railroad was killed in a wreck near Vaughan, Miss., as he
stayed at his controls, trying to save the passengers.
   In 1939, President Franklin D. Roosevelt officially opened the
New York World's Fair, billed as a look at ``The World of
Tomorrow,'' in a ceremony broadcast on a new medium called
``television.''
   In 1945, as Russian troops approached his bunker in Berlin,
Adolf Hitler committed suicide along with his wife of one day, Eva
Braun.
   In 1948, the Organization of American States held its first
meeting, in Bogota, Colombia.
   In 1968, police ended a weeklong occupation of several buildings
at Columbia University in New York City as they routed left-wing
student demonstrators.
   In 1970, President Richard M. Nixon announced the United States
was sending troops into Cambodia, an action that sparked widespread
protests.
   In 1973, President Nixon announced the resignations of aides
H.R. Haldeman and John Ehrlichman, along with Attorney General
Richard G. Kleindienst and White House counsel John W. Dean.
   In 1975, the South Vietnamese capital of Saigon fell to
Communist forces as President Duong Van Minh announced an
unconditional surrender.
   In 1980, three gunmen seized control of the Iranian embassy in
London, seizing about 20 hostages. British commandos stormed the
building May 5.
   In 1980, Queen Juliana of the Netherlands abdicated on her 71st
birthday. She was succeeded by her daughter, Princess Beatrix.
   Ten years ago: The cargo ship ``Ashdod'' became the first
Israeli vessel to sail through Egypt's Suez Canal since Israel's
founding in 1948, a journey made possible by the Egyptian-Israeli
peace treaty.
   Five years ago: President Ronald Reagan, nearing the end of his
China visit, attended a farewell banquet in Beijing, then flew to
Shanghai, where he addressed more than 1,000 students at Fudan
University.
   One year ago: Gen. Manuel Noriega, waving a machete that he
called a symbol of the valor of the Panamanian people, vowed at a
rally to keep fighting U.S. efforts to oust him as Panama's
military ruler.
   Today's birthdays: Princess Juliana of the Netherlands is 80.
Actress Eve Arden is 77. Singer Willie Nelson is 56. Actor-talk
show host Gary Collins is 51. Actress Jill Clayburgh is 45.
   Thought for today: ``The preservation of the sacred fire of
liberty, and the destiny of the republican model of government, are
justly considered as deeply, perhaps as finally staked, on the
experiment entrusted to the hands of the American people.'' _
President George Washington (1732-1799), in his first inaugural
address.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for use Sunday, April 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
