<DOCNO> AP890424-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears ADV25   04-24 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV 25,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues April 25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>GOP Holding Its Fire on Wright _ For Now</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians have an uncanny knack for stepping
on their own lines and for speaking when silence would serve them
best. It's a gold mine for consultants, who charge big fees for
telling their candidates to be quiet.
   Republicans, at least most of them, figured it out for
themselves when House Speaker Jim Wright was hauled up on ethics
charges. With the nation's top Democratic office holder facing 69
charges of violating House rules, no comment could improve upon the
issue for the GOP.
   Wright's Democratic defenders argue the whole case is a matter
of partisan politics, even though the charges came from an ethics
committee evenly divided between the parties, six members apiece.
Since that is a central message of the defense, Republicans
attempts to capitalize on the Wright case right now would be
counterproductive.
   So the GOP theme has been judicious righteousness, leaving the
Democrats to stew over their own problems. The minority leader,
Rep. Bob Michel of Illinois, counseled his colleagues to exercise
``extraordinary restraint and patience until final action is
taken.''
   President Bush has been careful to avoid the Wright case. ``The
last thing I want to do is involve myself in any way,'' he has said.
   One school of political thought has it that Republicans will use
the Wright ethics case to retaliate against Democrats for Senate
rejection of the Bush's nomination of John G. Tower to be secretary
of defense. Bush doesn't like that thought: ``I simply wouldn't
condone that at all, and I would condemn it.''
   Even Rep. Newt Gingrich of Georgia, the new Republican whip,
kept his profile and voice uncharacteristically low for a while,
avoiding public comment when the Ethics Committee charges were
announced.
   That couldn't last, and didn't. Gingrich, who lodged the
accusations that led to the Wright investigation, spoke up last
week, repeating that he believes the speaker will be out by summer.
   ``I don't see how the guy survives,'' Gingrich said at luncheon
with reporters. He said he doubted the charges ever would reach the
House floor, suggesting that Democratic leaders would press Wright
to resign as speaker in return for some lesser punishment.
   Gingrich then insisted Republicans are carefully avoiding any
intrusion on the ethics committee process.
   ``We have been saying this ought to be done in a careful and
judicious way, and Jack Brooks and Charlie Wilson have been running
around publicly threatening members of the ethics committee,'' he
said.
   Brooks and Wilson are Texas Democrats and leaders in the Wright
defense.
   Rep. Vin Weber of Minnesota, an activist conservative of the
Gingrich school, claimed the Democrats have made ``a nonpartisan
issue into a political firestorm.''
   In commentary he wrote for The New York Times, Weber said
``while most Republicans have been waiting to judge the case on the
facts, virtually all prominent Democrats have declared the speaker
innocent _ before hearing the evidence.''
   ``We Republicans are not attacking the gentleman from Texas,''
Rep. Dan Burton of Indiana told the House. ``We are taking a
wait-and-see attitude until all the facts are out, until we all
read the report, until it is brought before the House.''
   Well, sort of. Gingrich praised the ethics committee findings as
solid and remarkably thorough, although he acknowledged he had only
skimmed the documents. He said he'd lived with the Wright case long
enough to know serious work when he sees it.
   Republicans can afford political piety on this one because they
assume that Wright is on a hook he cannot get off _ and the
Democratic majority that made him speaker will ultimately have to
figure out what to do about it.
   Gingrich suggested a way out short of an embarrassing showdown
on Wright, although he insisted he wasn't offering a deal. He said
they could cut their losses if Wright were to resign as speaker and
Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley of Washington succeeded him.
   ``There would be a very large effort on both sides of the aisle,
I think, to have a period of bipartisanship if you had Foley as
speaker, and to try to heal some of the wounds,'' Gingrich said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-SouthAfrica-Smuggling Adv03 1stLd-Writethru 04-24 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Smuggling, Adv 03, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0190,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs May 3 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of rhinoceros in 1st graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>South Africa an Outlet for Smuggled Ivory and Rhino Horns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big-time smugglers are using
South Africa as a major transit point for shipping poached ivory
and rhinoceros horns out of Africa.
   The development, which is attributed in part to South Africa's
eagerness for international trade, has infuriated local
conservationists, who say it tarnishes the nation's reputation as a
leader in wildlife preservation.
   They have urged the government to tighten customs inspections,
intensify police investigations and stiffen penalties.
   ``Until this can be achieved, South African conservationists
must hang their heads in shame,'' wrote John Ledger, director of
the Endangered Wildlife Trust, in a recent magazine editorial. ``We
have been blind to the criminals in our midst.''
   Ledger and his colleagues say South Africans and foreigners
collaborate in operating vast international smuggling rings. They
are among the paymasters of poachers who, in the past two decades,
have played the main role in cutting Africa's rhino population from
about 70,000 to 4,000 and the elephant population from 1.3 million
to about 450,000.
   The toll of elephants has prompted many countries to closely
control the trade in ivory.
   Typically, ivory and rhino horns are smuggled into South Africa
by truck from countries such as Zambia, Zaire, Angola or
Mozambique. Experts say the contraband usually is flown to the Far
East, where the biggest markets are.
   Rhino horn is sold in powdered form in the Far East and other
countries as an aphrodisiac.
   Many Far Eastern countries have increased trade with South
Africa over the past few years as Western nations imposed trade
sanctions to protest its apartheid policies.
   Esmond Bradley-Martin, a Kenyan-based expert on the illegal
trade in rhino horns, says the biggest demand for rhino products is
in Taiwan, which has close economic and political ties with South
Africa.
   Encouraged by the government, Taiwanese businessmen have
established scores of factories in South Africa in recent years,
and hundreds of Taiwanese have moved here.
   ``Thus, the perfect opportunity has been provided for Chinese
businessmen to purchase rhino horn and hide from illegal South
African dealers and take these supplies from Jan Smuts airport in
Johannesburg to Taipei,'' Bradley-Martin wrote last year.
   Ledger said customs workers at Jan Smuts lack the resources to
investigate all outgoing cargo, especially shipments that appear to
have proper permits.
   At highway border posts, he said, customs officials checking
incoming goods from neighboring states search more intensively for
weapons and explosives than for elephant tusks or rhino horns.
   Also, in a bid to encourage regional trade, South Africa has a
customs agreement with several of its neighbors and this means many
vehicles enter without thorough searches. Some containers pass
through South Africa without ever being inspected.
   ``We've developed a good network of trading because of our
political isolation,'' said Clive Walker, a prominent Johannesburg
conservationist. ``We've been used by smugglers who have found a
convenient way of doing business with a good degree of safety.''
   Ledger said the problem lies with light penalties for smugglers,
who face no more than a 2,000-rand ($800) fine if found in
possession of contraband rhino horns.
   ``It's an easy option for a crook,'' he said in an interview.
``The penalties are a fraction of what they'd be for drug
smugglers.''
   Parliament is considering legislation that would increase the
maximum penalty to a 100,000-rand ($40,000) fine or 15 years in
prison.
   In a recent documentary, the state-run South African
Broadcasting Corp. said 50 tons of ivory was exported from South
Africa last year, accompanied by seemingly proper permits. However,
the broadcast said only 14 tons could be accounted for officially _
seven tons legally brought into South Africa and seven tons culled
from elephants killed in a population-control program at Kruger
National Park.
   A U.S. environmental group, the Conservation, Environmental and
Animal Welfare Consortium, alleged last year that the South African
military had helped organize an ivory smuggling racket intended to
provide funds for anti-Marxist guerrillas in Angola and Mozambique.
   A South African board of inquiry rejected charges of large-scale
military involvement, although it said the army did help Angola
rebels transport elephant tusks in 1978-79.
   Two South African army officers were among six people indicted
last year in Connecticut on charges that they smuggled rhino horns,
skins of other endangered animals and AK-47 rifles into the United
States.
   Ledger wants to declare war on all ivory and horn smugglers.
   ``While we have proudly extolled to the world the righteousness
of South Africa's conservation achievements, these evil people have
destroyed our reputation and our pride,'' he wrote in the
editorial. ``They have to be stopped.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs May 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv06-1stLd-Writethru b0197 04-24 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv06 - 1st Ld-Writethru, b0197,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Saturday, May 6</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 21st graf, `Five years ago...' to fix typos in d'Aubuisson
name.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, May 6, the 126th day of 1989. There are 239
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, on May 6, 1889, the Paris Exposition
formally opened, featuring the just-completed Eiffel Tower.
   On this date:
   In 1840, England introduced its first postage stamp.
   In 1861, Arkansas seceded from the Union.
   In 1882, Congress passed, over President Chester Alan Arthur's
veto, the Chinese Exclusion Act, which barred Chinese immigrants
from the United States for 10 years. Similar acts were passed in
1892 and 1902.
   In 1910, Britain's King Edward VII died.
   In 1915, Babe Ruth hit his first major-league home run as a
player for the Boston Red Sox.
   In 1935, the Works Progress Administration began operating.
   In 1937, the hydrogen-filled German dirigible ``Hindenburg''
burst into flames and crashed while docking in Lakehurst, N.J.,
killing 36 of the 97 people on board.
   In 1942, during World War II, U.S. forces under General Jonathan
Wainwright surrendered Corregidor to the Japanese.
   In 1954, medical student Roger Bannister broke the four-minute
mile during a track meet in Oxford, England, in 3:59:04 minutes.
   In 1960, Britain's Princess Margaret married Anthony
Armstrong-Jones, a commoner, at Westminster Abbey. The marriage
ended in divorce in 1978.
   In 1962, in the first test of its kind, the submerged submarine
USS Ethan Allen fired a Polaris missile armed with a nuclear
warhead that detonated above the Pacific Ocean.
   In 1978, ``Affirmed,'' ridden by Steve Cauthen, won the 104th
Kentucky Derby, the first leg of an eventual Triple Crown victory
the year after ``Seattle Slew'' also won the Triple Crown.
   In 1980, the bodies of eight Americans killed in the aborted
mission to rescue the hostages in Iran were flown to the United
States from Tehran by way of Switzerland.
   In 1983, West German government experts announced that tests had
proven the purported Hitler diaries to be ``obvious fakes.''
   In 1987, CIA Director William J. Casey died at age 74.
   Ten years ago: Chanting, ``No more Harrisburgs,'' a reference to
the accident at Pennsylvania's Three Mile Island atomic plant, tens
of thousands of people marched in Washington against nuclear energy.
   Five years ago: Voters in El Salvador went to the polls for the
second time in six weeks, this time to decide a presidential runoff
between Jose Napoleon Duarte and Roberto d'Aubuisson. Duarte would
emerge the winner.
   One year ago: In his first comment on the matter, President
Ronald Reagan said he didn't ``look kindly upon'' reports that a
memoir written by his former chief of staff, Donald Regan, painted
an unflattering portrait of first lady Nancy Reagan.
   Today's birthdays: Actor Stewart Granger is 76. Baseball great
Willie Mays is 58. Rock singer Bob Seger is 44. Singer Janet
Jackson is 23.
   Thought for today: ``Faults are thick where love is thin.'' _
Danish proverb.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for use Saturday, May 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv25   04-24 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 25,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tuesday, April 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Real World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In business and economics it is sometimes
difficult to find the real world, and thereafter to figure it out.
So often is a dream world depicted that it poses as the real thing.
   In the consumer economy, for instance, personal finance
publications offer endless tips on how to pick the best mutual
fund, how to find hidden stock values, how to cut debts with ease,
and how to slash taxes.
   Those who live in the real world know there are no easy ways to
pay bills, virtually no stock tips that are worth the risk, no
newly discovered ways to lower taxes _ and certainly no way to
slash them that is acceptable to Uncle Sam.
   In the dream world, a happy family of four is depicted with
smiling faces after having negotiated a home equity loan. Now they
can afford the things they want: a car, a boat, a vacation, a life
of comfortable ease and luxury.
   In the real world, however, you begin paying interest on the
equity loan in the very next month, and you may struggle to meet
the payments. And struggling, of course, is not compatible with
ease, luxury, boating or carefree vacations.
   Business is as bad. In construction, to name just one industry,
it is a certainty that good times will produce overbuilding,
followed soon after by abandoned commercial projects, condos that
won't sell, and distressed lenders.
   The dream world has little to do with the amount of money or the
alleged acumen of the dreamers. Some of the most highly financed
manufacturers live in the world of dreams, and their big bucks do
nothing to bring them around.
   Almost every economic recession, for example, is preceded by a
buildup of inventories, a consequence of producers convincing
themselves that good times are here to stay and that they must go
all out to meet the demand.
   In fact, that tendency has been even more observable in recent
years. Produce heavily, carmakers say, because we can always
institute a program of rebates or below-market interest rates to
move the goods.
   In the real world, of course, rebates and low interest rates
amount to the same thing as a price cut, and everyone knows it.
   The securities industry fades in and out of either world. When
times are good they can only get better, and when they turn bad
they can only grow worse, according to the dreamers. But when do
booms begin? When the dreams are bust.
   Securities forecasters often decline even to recognize the real
world, preferring instead to poke their heads far out into the
future, which cannot be understood or described. Big things are
always happening out there in space.
   What happens in those dreams of the future, however, seldom
descends to the day-to-day world. As seen by the dreamers, the
future changes each week. Before it ever arrives, before it is even
created, it is different from what it was.
   One of the current oddities in the securities market is the
assertion by many that junk bonds, so-called because of the risk
involved, are as good as other bonds, and to those who live in King
Midas land, maybe as good as gold.
   And to the realists who have lived through boom and bust on Wall
Street, there is no one phrase that describes the confusion of
dream world and real world better than this: Things have changed;
the old rules don't apply anymore.
   They have heard that phrase at the beginning and just before the
end of every bull market of the century, and one of the few
certainties on Wall Street is that it will be heard into the next
century at least.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday, April 25.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1423EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:RockHotlines Adv27   04-24 0963</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Rock Hotlines, Adv 27,0990</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thu AMs, April 27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Teen-Agers, Telephones and Rock 'n' Roll</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hey kids! You've heard Ice T's records, seen
D.J. Jazzy Jeff's videos. Now pick up your phone and talk to them!
   Well, sort of.
   They talk. You listen. And your parents pay.
   Welcome to the latest teen craze: telephone hot lines to the
stars. By dialing a number with a 900 prefix, listeners can hear a
prerecorded message from their favorite rock stars, talking about
whatever happens to enter their minds. It all costs about $2.50 for
two minutes.
   Kids are calling by the thousands. That's bringing smiles to the
faces of entrepreneurs prescient enough to tap into this holy
trinity of marketing _ teen-agers, telephones and rock 'n' roll.
   ``The market's right there,'' said Andrea West, who manages the
telephone service for American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. ``If
you're a teen-ager, you know music. And you certainly don't have an
aversion to the telephone.''
   The reigning kings of the phone lines are teen-age rap stars
D.J. Jazzy Jeff and the Fresh Prince. Their good-natured 1988 hit,
``Parents Just Don't Understand,'' was the type of song youngsters
could understand and parents not resent.
   Their telephone line opened nearly a year ago and at its peak,
fans were calling at the rate of 50,000 per day. It's approaching
the landmark of 3 million calls, said Michael Omansky, vice
president for marketing at RCA Records.
   Other teen faves have followed suit, including Bobby Brown,
Samantha Fox, Al B. Sure!, Lita Ford and New Kids on the Block, at
varying degrees of success.
   ``It's a great way for the fans to continue to get to know the
artists that they like,'' said Donnie Wahlberg, one of the five New
Kids on the Block. ``I think it's great. You call Bobby Brown's hot
line and it's almost like he's talking right to you. In a way, he
is.''
   Few of the messages are particularly weighty. One recent day on
the Jazzy Jeff line, the two rap stars talked about which Nintendo
computer games they liked to play. They said they were embarrassed
when they tried to buy some and handed a clerk the wrong credit
card _ just the kind of daily triviality teen-agers love to tell
their friends on the phone.
   The musicians have a fresh message every day, recording them in
bunches like the producers of television game shows.
   ``We think of a subject and just wing it,'' Wahlberg said. ``We
don't sit down and write out what we're going to say. We try to
talk just like the way we talk, as if the caller was right there in
the conversation.''
   Most messages are accompanied by a commercial for some
star-related product. Youngsters can get a free autographed picture
of Ice T, provided they send in a copy of their phone bill proving
they've called his phone line.
   It's the personal touch that's made the phone lines such a smash
_ even if it is on tape.
   Cory Eisner, vice president of Phone Programs Inc., can easily
say, ``I told you so.'' He approached several record companies for
his outfit, which sets up the phone lines, and was routinely turned
down before Omansky took a chance.
   It's a wonder it took so long. For record companies, it's a
great deal. The phone lines help sell records, and the records help
sell the phone lines. Both make money.
   Record companies are reluctant to say how much. But simple
addition paints a rosy picture. The phone company takes about 65
cents for a $2 call, with the remainder split between the record
company, the artist and go-betweens such as Phone Programs.
   That's more than $4 million generated by Jazzy Jeff's phone line
alone, minus expenses for advertising and recording the messages.
   ``There is a business objective behind all of this,'' said West
of AT&amp;T. ``If you can involve the audience more, know who your
audience is, you'll be able to be better at what you do.''
   The rock hot lines are direct descendants of AT&amp;T's phone lines
that allow Americans to eavesdrop on the conversations of shuttle
astronauts.
   Rick Springfield was the first musician to tap into the
technology back in 1984, West said. But it wasn't until rap _
itself a musical style that values talking over singing _ embraced
the phones that they exploded in popularity.
   Not everyone is happy about that.
   ``A lot of families have been learning the hard way how
appealing the 900 lines are for teen-agers or even younger kids,''
said Nancy Larraine Hoffman, a New York state senator and mother of
teen-age children.
   ``Kids don't know anything about a phone bill. It could have a
pretty devastating effect on a family's budget.''
   She's proposed legislation in New York that would require phone
companies to give parents the options of putting a ``block'' on
their phone lines to prevent children from calling the 900 lines.
   More than half the states require phone companies to offer such
blocks, although they differ on whether or not this is a free
service, said Debby Bernau, spokeswoman for the National Conference
of State Legislators. The proliferation of pornographic phone lines
and party lines instigated the actions.
   Although New York state doesn't require the blocks, New York
Telephone, which services more than 90 percent of the phones in the
state, already offers the option free of charges.
   But West said parents shouldn't be too worried. The rock phone
lines are hot right now, just like hula hoops, pet rocks and
streaking were in the past.
   ``For the same reason, it will go away,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, April 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
