<FIRST>s a BC-TheBoughBreaks Adv30   04-24 1213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The Bough Breaks, Adv 30,1243</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Doctor Accused In Babies' Deaths At Odds With Peers For Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP Extra</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Word of mouth and fliers distributed in
mostly poor, mostly black areas brought Gladys Mae Hinson and a lot
of women like her to the clinic where Dr. Jesse James Howard
delivered babies for $350.
   Ms. Hinson, 23, the youngest of 18, came from Mosses, an
impoverished backwater, to have her second child. Antoinette was
born at 6:55 p.m. on Aug. 20, 1986, and Howard sent mother and baby
home at 7:30 even though Antoinette was having trouble breathing.
Soon her breathing stopped.
   Gladys Mae gave her baby mouth-to-mouth resuscitation during the
30-minute race to a hospital, but lack of oxygen already had taken
its toll. ``She can't walk, she can't talk, she can't take care of
herself.''
   A month later, Howard sent Janice Peterson home 2{ hours after
Willie Jr. was born. Willie began having trouble breathing the next
day. Before he got to the hospital he died of inhaling meconium, or
fetal feces, a normally treatable complication of childbirth.
   Medical Examiner James R. Lauridson believed Willie shouldn't
have died, and asked the State Board of Medical Examiners to
investigate. Right away, said board Director Larry Dixon, six more
doctors urged action against Howard.
   The board investigated 11 of Howard's deliveries over an
18-month period _ including those of Willie, Antoinette, another
baby with brain damage and three others who died _ and asked the
Alabama Medical Licensure Commission to revoke his license. It took
until July 1987 for the commission to suspend Howard's license and
until the following March for revocation.
   ``We should have done something a little sooner, maybe,'' said
Dixon, a state senator. But he said the circumstances _ a black
doctor delivering black babies in an office for poor women who'd
had little prenatal care _ prevented the board and the commission
from moving any faster than they did.
   ``He was dealing with a patient population that has a much
higher infant mortality rate than the rest of the state. We didn't
know at first whether we were dealing with gross malpractice or a
phenomenon of the population.''
   Alabama's 1986 infant mortality rate was 13.3 deaths per 1,000
live births, the worst in the nation; nationally, the rate was
10.4. In 1987, Alabama fell to fourth, with 12.2; complete
nationwide statistics are unavailable.
   Howard, who says he's delivered 2,000 to 2,500 babies, contends
that the white-controlled medical community has been ``on my case''
for years, in part because his deliveries took business away from
hospitals and other doctors. A double standard of care exists in
Alabama, he says: Whites get quality care from well-paid doctors,
while poor blacks get whatever they can.
   Because of that double standard, Howard should be praised for
his work, said his attorney, Robert Turner. ``It's a miracle more
of his patients didn't die. It's a testament to his skill that they
didn't.''
   Howard was ``as much a missionary as a medical doctor,'' J.L.
Chestnut, another of his lawyers, argued in appealing the March 23,
1988, license revocation before Montgomery County Circuit Judge
Joseph Phelps.
   Board officials ``knew we were going to be charged with racial
discrimination when we got into it,'' Dixon said, adding that such
claims have been standard when action is taken against a member of
a minority group.
   The board accused Howard of sending babies home minutes after
problem deliveries; performing risky deliveries in an ill-equipped
office; not keeping newborns warm, leading to cold stress; and
``repeated failure ... to recognize and treat significant and
substantial life-threatening medical conditions.''
   ``The standards of medicine nowadays dictate that if you're
going to provide the care, there's a minimum standard of care
you've got to meet,'' said Dr. Earl Fox, head of the Alabama
Department of Public Health.
   Howard, a 1972 graduate of Meharry College's medical school in
Nashville, Tenn., says he met that standard in deliveries, which
accounted for 10 percent of his practice. ``Many of those babies
had problems from the get-go. I didn't do anything to those
mothers.''
   But Howard has been no stranger to the authorities.
   The board had investigated him before, in 1976, but declined to
take action, citing lack of evidence of alleged irregularities in
his prescription practices. Howard said he also had been
investigated twice for alleged problems with deliveries like those
that cost him his license.
   And in Selma, where Howard set up a clinic in 1973, he lost his
hospital privileges for stabbing Dr. Chudy Okoye during a scuffle
in a ditch; he also was convicted of assault, fined $500 and
sentenced to 30 days in jail, served on weekends. No formal charges
were filed in an earlier scuffle in an operating room where Okoye's
surgery took longer than scheduled.
   Howard also assaulted a woman employee who had been living with
him, and was fined $50 and given a 30-day suspended sentence and
six months' probation. In 1979, he was fined and given a suspended
sentence for petty larceny, and in 1980, he was convicted of
failing to file birth and death certificates. The death certificate
charge was dropped on appeal; Howard was fined $1 after pleading
guilty to the birth certificate charge.
   When Howard moved his clinic to Montgomery in 1985, members of
the area medical community already had seen some of his babies in
emergency rooms.
   ``We'd get a (dead) baby born to a low-income family, and the
first thing we'd ask is `Did it come from Dr. Howard?''' said Ike
Moss, a former investigator with the state's Department of Forensic
Sciences. ``I started hollering, `Let's get his license,' when I
worked the second one.''
   Still, about 100 people showed up at a license hearing in
support of Howard, who is living in Tuscaloosa and awaiting Phelps'
decision.
   ``He was a neighborhood hero,'' said Dr. Thomas C. Nolan, a
member of the licensure commission.
   Sharon Jones, 18, of Fort Deposit, whose daughter died less than
a day after her June 9, 1987, birth, said Howard ``treated me very
nice.''
   ``It's just in God's hands,'' said Sharon's mother, Annie Pearl
Jones. ``I never felt like he killed the baby.''
   Febie Ann Crum's baby suffered brain damage during delivery June
5, 1987. ``He is not really the age he's supposed to be. He has not
got the growth a 2-year-old has supposed to get,'' said her
mother-in-law, Plummie Mae Crum of Greenville. ``He don't do
nothing much.''
   Gladys Mae Hinson describes Antoinette, now 2{, in similar terms.
   ``They say she will always be with me,'' Ms. Hinson said. ``I've
accepted the fact that this child will be with me until I die or
she dies.''
   Ms. Hinson, who had a son before Antoinette and has had a
daughter since, says she can't work because of the constant chance
Antoinette will have a seizure and the numerous dosages of medicine
she has to be given daily.
   She said she now believes Howard was wrong to send her home so
soon after Antoinette was born, particularly since she was in
trouble.
   But ``I trusted him,'' she said. ``He was my doctor.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
