<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--SlipperyElm Adv27   04-24 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Slippery Elm, Adv 27,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, April 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gnawed Slippery Elm May Be Sign Of Deer Sore Throats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folks have used slippery elm bark for
centuries to cure everything from sore throats to constipation, and
researchers are trying to find out whether white-tailed deer in
some areas are doing the same.
   Dr. Edwin Michael, a wildlife researcher at West Virginia
University, said he first came upon slippery elms that had been
stripped of their bark near this coal town just south of the
Pennsylvania border in 1981.
   After further observation, he concluded that a few deer, in
widely scattered areas, were responsible. ``This is not typical
deer behavior. These deer are choosing a particular species of
tree, at a particular time of year, and going to a lot of trouble
to strip the bark from them.
   ``There must be some reason.''
   Michael has just begun a two-year study to find out why some
deer prefer chewing the tender, inner bark of the slippery elm
while shunning neighboring trees, including such usual favorites as
maple and black cherry.
   ``Our first guess is that there is a lack of quantity or quality
in their food supply,'' he said. ``But the deer, at some point,
also must have learned that the bark is satisfying. Do they use it
as a cure or temporary relief for what ails them? I think that's
wild speculation, but it's possible.''
   Ripping the bark from the exposed roots and lower parts of the
tree is no easy task for the deer, which have no upper front teeth.
Nonetheless, deer in some parts of western Monongalia County have
stripped the bark from hundreds of slippery elms, killing most of
the saplings, he said.
   Evidence of similar behavior has been reported in Greene County,
Pa., north of Hagerstown, Md., and at Front Royal, Va.
   ``You might find 100 or 200 trees stripped clean in one spot,
but a mile or two away, where there are just as many deer and just
as many slippery elms, there will be no signs of bark stripping at
all,'' Michael said.
   ``How do they recognize that the tree is a slippery elm? Do they
smell it? Do they know it by sight? How do you explain the
scattered pockets of the behavior?''
   Indians used slippery elm bark as a remedy for coughs, sore
throats and to promote healing, said Clarke Ridgeway, a West
Virginia University expert on the historical development of drugs.
``They introduced it to the early colonists, who adapted Indian
remedies in the 1600s when they could not obtain their usual
medicines from Europe.''
   Still available in some pharmacies and a popular item in health
food stores, slippery elm bark is a mucilage that acts as a barrier
to irritation and has a lubricating effect when mixed with water.
   It doesn't have any antibacterial action but does contain a
number of sugars which make it a good source of food for deer when
other browse is in short supply, Ridgeway said. ``The deer could be
using it as a preferred source of nutrition. Or they could like the
way it swells up into an oily, gelatinous mass when they chew it.''
   Complicating Michael's research is ``that we don't know when a
deer has a sore throat. We don't know when a deer is ailing until
it's about to die.
   ``Do deer get sore throats? They must. There's no reason to
think that only people do. Now, is it only deer with sore throats
that are stripping the bark?
   ``We, of course, don't think that is the case. But it's
possible. We don't give wildlife enough credit for what they do.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for April 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
