<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-24 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in thin early European
trading today. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said the dollar will have difficulty
shrugging off last week's European interest rate shuffle. They said
the start of trading on Wall Street later today might give new
impetus to dollar selling.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.07 yen to a closing 131.38. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 131.30 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.8491 West German marks, up from 1.8460; 1.6317
Swiss francs, down from 1.6320; 6.2712 French francs, up from
6.2625; 2.0853 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0830; 1,357.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,357.50; and 1.1873 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1890.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7137, compared with
$1.7160 Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $383.50 a troy ounce,
down from $384.50 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $383.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $383.90, down from $384.15 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 32 cents to close at a bid
$385.06.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.76 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $5.78.
</TEXT>
