   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 370 up, 602 down and
510 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 22.30 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said it was not surprising to see the market run into
some resistance after its sharp rise over the past four weeks.
   They also noted that weakness in blue chips often occurs after
they have been driven higher, as they were late Friday, by computer
program trades related to a set of expiring stock index options or
futures.
   Aside from those technical forces, analysts said hopes remained
high on Wall Street that interest rates would turn downward before
long.
   An increase last Thursday in key West German interest rates sent
a brief jolt through the stock market. But it quickly recovered as
traders concluded that the Federal Reserve wouldn't take any
similar action.
   International Business Machines, which raised its quarterly
dividend from $1.10 a share to $1.21 a share, gained ] to 113~.
   Syntex fell 2{ to 44}. The stock rose sharply Friday on
speculation that F. Hoffmann-LaRoche &amp; Co. might be preparing to
make a bid for the company.
   But those expectations died down today when Hoffmann-La Roche
announced an internal restructuring plan.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .61 to 172.29. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .35 at 342.24.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 32.08 to
2,409.46, closing above 2,400 for the first time since it stood at
2,412.70 on Oct. 14, 1987.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 936 up, 517 down and 478 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 187.31 million shares, against 175.97
million in the previous session.
