<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Futures Plunge On Wetter Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices fell sharply
today on the Chicago Board of Trade following a rainy weekend in
some key growing areas.
   Wheat futures opened slightly higher, reflecting continued
dryness in Kansas.
   Weekend showers brought relief to parts of western Illinois and
eastern Iowa, a section of the Corn Belt still struggling to
recover from last year's drought.
   ``We got a lot of rain where it was needed and there's a lot
more rain in the forecast for this week,'' said Victor Lespinasse,
a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Corn and soybean prices also were pressured by heavy farmer
selling of those commodities over the weekend.
   But the weather remained warm and dry over the weekend in
Kansas, where the winter wheat crop has been severely damaged by
drought conditions.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.16 a bushel; corn was 5 cents to
6} cents lower with May at $2.70\ a bushel; oats were 4 cents to 5
cents lower with May at $1.97{ a bushel; soybeans were 12 cents to
15\ cents lower with May at $7.48 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .23 cent higher with June at
71.30 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .48 cent
higher with May at 76.65 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .40
cent lower with June at 45.20 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .20 cent lower to .13 cent higher with May at 31.10 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
