<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Comsat     04-24 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Comsat,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comsat Earnings Rise 16 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comsat Corp. said Monday its earnings rose 16
percent in the first three months of 1989, primarily from growth in
its international satellite operations.
   Comsat said international telecommunications revenues grew due
to increased traffic demand, but were offset partly by promotion
discounts instituted in the second half of 1988. Maritime revenue
growth resulted from increased telephone traffic, mainly from
cruise ships and other commercial vessels, Comsat said.
   Net income for the quarter ending March 31 was $16.5 million, or
89 cents a share, on revenues of $97.4 million, compared with
earnings of $14.3 million, or 77 cents a share, on earnings of
$84.1 million in the first quarter of 1988.
   International revenues increased to $67.8 million in the
quarter, compared with $56.5 million in the first quarter of 1988.
   Comsat's video entertainment segment showed a $3.2 million
operating loss on revenues of $11.7 million in the first three
months of 1989, compared with a $1.2 million loss on revenues of
$10.9 million in first quarter 1988. Comsat attributed the loss to
increased marketing and operating costs.
   Comsat is a publicly traded corporation which provides
international, domestic and maritime communications and information
services. It represents the United States in the International
Telecommunications Satellite Organization (Intelsat) and the
International Maritime Satellite Organization (Inmarsat).
</TEXT>
