<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   04-24 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parties in Eastern Bankruptcy to Meet in Court Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 new grafs to UPDATE with bankruptcy judge postponing
hearing again, examiner confirming Pritzker has received data, TWA expressing
interest. Picks up 7th graf, Eastern's management...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge today postponed for
the second time a hearing over whether strike-bound Eastern
Airlines should be put up for sale in its entirety.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland rescheduled today's
hearing for May 3 to give potential buyers more time to examine
Eastern financial data and to give parties involved in the
airline's bankruptcy case more time to negotiate over a possible
reorganization plan.
   The judge has asked Eastern, its unions and major creditors to
demonstrate why the airline shouldn't be put up for auction in its
entirety, including its Northeast shuttle service slated to be sold
to developer Donald Trump.
   Meanwhile, a ``household name'' financial institution has
recently emerged as a new serious bidder for Eastern, along with
billionaire hotelier Jay Pritzker, Trans World Airlines Inc.
Chairman Carl Icahn and ex-baseball commissioner Peter V.
Ueberroth, according to sources close to the situation.
   And Mohamed Hadid, a Washington real estate investor who
recently agreed to buy the Ritz-Carlton hotels in Washington and
New York, confirmed through an associate Friday he is interested in
buying Miami-based Eastern.
   Pritzker, who reportedly has offered around $500 million for
Eastern, has been given access to confidential financial data
concerning the airline, bankruptcy examiner David I. Shapiro
confirmed today.
   Shapiro also said TWA officials had expressed interest in
getting access to the financial data, which is being released to
parties who agree to confidentiality restrictions.
   Ueberroth, whose $464 million deal to buy Eastern collapsed
April 12, also is believed to still be interested in the carrier.
   Eastern's management is expected to present early this week to a
committee representing its major creditors a plan for sharply
reducing its operations and selling substantial assets. On
Thursday, the creditors committee, which also includes union
representatives, discussed a financial review of the airline by the
investment firm Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.
   Union leaders and their advisers, meanwhile, have been sifting
through a pile of offers for the carrier to determine whether they
are viable. The unions, who have been approached by a number of
suitors, interviewed one such candidate Thursday evening and
eventually decided he was ``a wash-out,'' sources said.
   Around 25 would-be buyers have had some sort of contact with the
unions since Eastern's Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing on March 9,
including about a dozen who were considered serious enough for more
extensive talks, the sources said.
   The airline has been virtually grounded since March 4, when its
Machinists union struck over a long-simmering wage dispute and
pilots and flight attendants walked out in sympathy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
