<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-SmithKline     04-24 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-SmithKline,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profits Fell During First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp., which has reached
agreement to merge with Great Britain's Beecham Group subject to
stockholder approval, announced Monday sales were up in the first
quarter, but profits fell sharply.
   Net earnings fell 22 percent to $130.2 million from the $166.5
million a year ago. Sales rose 7 percent to $1.24 billion, compared
to $1.16 billion in the 1988 January-to-March quarter.
   Profits translate to $1.05 a share compared to $1.34 in the
similar 1988 period.
   Henry Wendt, chairman and chief executive, said the decline in
earnings in the quarter was in line with expectations.
   The primary factor was the adverse comparison of U.S.
pharmaceutical sales with a period of heavy trade stocking in early
1988, which made sales unusually high, the company said. The rise
of the dollar also depressed the dollar value of overseas earnings
and sales.
   Clinical Laboratory sales climbed 69 percent, or $80 million,
reflecting last year's second quarter acquisition of International
Clinical Laboratories.
   SmithKline Beckman and Beecham announced April 12 that it had
reached agreement to merge. Besides stockholders' approval it needs
regulatory approval and a proxy statement is expected to be filed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission in mid-May.
</TEXT>
