<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Gateway     04-24 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Gateway,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Food Retailer Gateway Says It Was Approached by Kohlberg
Kravis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British food retailer Gateway Corp., the target of
a hostile $2.9 billion takeover bid from a group of British
investors, said Monday it has been approached by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts and Co., the U.S. leveraged buyout house.
   A Gateway spokeswoman, who didn't want to be identified further,
said the talks with Kohlberg Kravis were preliminary but might lead
to further discussions.
   Gateway said the approach was one of several it has received
since the investor group made its hostile 1.7 billion pound bid
last Tuesday.
   The spokeswoman declined to identify the other parties who
approached the company.
   Gateway has rejected as inadequate the bid from the investor
group, which is led by the London investment firm S.G. Warburg and
Co., and includes Globe Investment Trust PLC and Mercury Asset
Management Ltd., both institutional investors in Gateway. Mercury
is a unit of Warburg.
   The group intends to restructure Gateway by selling off its
non-food businesses, such as its Herman's sporting goods chain in
the United Sattes.
   The Warburg-led group, called Isoceles PLC, would privately own
the remaining interests, with the aim of taking them public again
within three to five years.
   Gateway, formerly called Dee Corp., last year fended off a
hostile 2.04 billion pound, or $3.49 billion, bid from Barker and
Dobson Group PLC, a confectionery company.
   Gateway, which operates some 820 stores, is Britain's third
largest food retailer after J. Sainsbury PLC and Tesco PLC.
</TEXT>
