<FIRST>u f PM-Northwest 1stLd-Writethru   04-24 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, 1st Ld-Writethru,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Changes Direction In Poison Pill Lawsuit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 new grafs to UPDATE with court hearing in Delaware;
picks up 5th graf pvs: ``Rothmeier declined ...; ADDS byline</HEAD>
<HEAD>echtfkbjdtfkbjd</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Marvin Davis has revised his
lawsuit challenging the ``poison pill'' takeover defense of NWA
Inc., the Northwest Airlines' parent company he wants to buy in a
$2.7 billion hostile tender offer.
   The lawsuit in the Court of Chancery in Wilmington, Del.,
originally sought to invalidate the pill. But at a hearing today,
lawyer Gilchrist Sparks said Davis is asking only for the
elimination of a provision that would prevent a new board of
directors from dismantling the pill for 180 days.
   Davis has launched a proxy fight to take control of the board of
directors at the company's May 15 annual meeting. If he were to
succeed, a provision in the ``poison pill'' plan would prevent the
new board from dismantling the takeover defense for 180 days.
   Such a provision would cripple the new board from accepting
legitimate buyout offers, thus hindering Davis' proxy fight, Sparks
said.
   ``Six months is a very long time,'' Sparks said. ``Stockholders
want to get the money now, not in six months. So they will vote for
whoever will get them the money now.''
   Chancellor William Allen said he would rule soon on the request.
   Sheldon Raab, a lawyer for Northwest, objected to the request.
He said the 180-day waiting provision ``has the purpose and effect
of getting would-be acquirers (such as Davis) to come to the board
and negotiate.''
   It is a way of ``buying time to get higher bids, explore
alternatives to get maximum shareholder value,'' Raab said. ``The
job of a corporation's director is not to shoot himself and his
shareholder in the foot,'' but to make a ``deliberated'' decision
on their behalf.
   Meanwhile, Northwest Chairman Steven Rothmeier says he would
like a ``white knight'' investor to come forward and work with
current management if Northwest Airlines cannot remain independent.
   Rothmeier told the Wall Street Journal the best course would be
for the company to remain independent and follow the growth
strategy he has charted for the nation's fourth-largest airline.
But he said the company is exploring putting a large stake in NWA
in the hands of friendly investors.
   ``There are potentially friendly investors out there,'' said
Rothmeier.
   Davis' tender offer stands at $90 a share even though the stock
has been trading well above that price. NWA stock closed Friday at
$102.50 on the New York Stock Exchange, up $3.75. The board was
scheduled to meet today to review the offer and other options.
   Rothmeier declined to identify any potential friendly investors,
but other NWA officials said 10 to 15 parties have expressed
interest in all or part of the company, the Journal reported. They
include leveraged buy-out firms and airline and air-freight
companies.
   A recapitalization involving a special shareholder dividend is
another option.
   NWA board member Robert A. Charpie, chairman of Cabot Corp. in
Boston, said the board had asked its investment advisers, First
Boston Corp., to examine the possibility of recapitalization.
   ``Many corporations have done well at it. Good managers can
manage highly leveraged companies,'' Charpie told the Journal.
   The only other investment group with a confirmed interest in
buying Northwest is led by Los Angeles investor and former Marriott
Corp. official Albert Checci and former NWA director Gary Wilson,
now an executive at Walt Disney Co. That group owns a 4.9 percent
stake in NWA and could be friendly to NWA management.
   The Journal reported that the Checci group has financial backing
from Elders IXL Ltd., one of Australia's largest companies with
interests in beer, wine, livestock and financial services. The
newspaper said neither Checci nor Elders could be reached for
comment.
   Meanwhile, the New York Times reported today that Kelso &amp; Co., a
small investment bank based in New York, has decided to consider a
bid for the airline. A spokesman for Kelso and a Northwest
spokesman declined to comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
