<HEAD>London Shares Close Marginally Higher After Dull Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on London's Stock Exchange closed
marginally higher Monday as the market surrendered its early gains
after Wall Street opened lower.
   Cautious optimism that British interest rates might not rise
helped shares to post gains at the opening. Encouraging this view
were the pound's relative stability and a slight retreat in
short-term money market rates.
   But trading activity was dull as players awaited Wednesday's
release of British trade figures for March.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 1 point, or 0.05 percent, at 2,062.0. The Financial Times
30-share index was up 1.4 points at 1,701.9 at the close. The
Financial Times 500-share index rose 1.39 points to close at
1,173.13.
   Volume was light as 340.8 million shares changed hands, compared
with 400.7 million shares at the same time Friday.
