<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firmer In Europe, Gold Also Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against the major currencies
in European trading on Monday, helped by a weaker West German mark.
Gold prices also rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the mark dropped amid uncertainty
about where it is going, as a result of last week's Bonn government
reshuffle.
   But the decline of the mark could be reversed by an expected
government announcement of suspension of the 10 percent withholding
tax on income from interest.
   A possible additional plus for the mark is that the markets
expect the U.S. first-quarter gross national product figures due on
Wednesday will show the American economy has started to slow down.
Traders said that would reduce the likelihood of higher U.S.
interest rates and thereby make the mark more attractive.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7050 late Monday, more than
one cent cheaper for buyers than Friday's late $1.7160.
   In Tokyo the dollar eased to 131.38 Japanese yen from 131.45. In
London late Monday the dollar traded slightly lower at 131.37.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Friday's late rates, included: 1.8575 West German marks, up from
1.8460; 1.6395 Swiss francs, up from 1.6320; 6.2975 French francs,
up from 6.2625; 2.0960 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0830; 1,362.50
Italian lire, up from 1,357.50; and 1.1890 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1850.
   In Hong Kong gold closed at $384.05 a troy ounce, down from
$385.45 late Friday. Elsewhere, gold bullion prices rose.
   In London, the major market, gold was priced at $384.90 bid a
troy ounce late Monday, up from $384.40 late Friday. The late bid
price in Zurich was $384.65 an ounce, up from $384.15.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.81 bid a troy ounce,
up from $5.78.
</TEXT>
