<FIRST>r f BC-ContinentalFares     04-24 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continental Fares,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Continental Announces Reduced Fare Plan For Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines, trying to garner more
business from families on summer vacations, unveiled a sale on
children's fares with some tickets as low as $1.
   Monday's announcement came on the heels of the Houston-based
carrier's decision to raise some of its fares at the start of the
busy summer tourist season. Several other airlines also have
decided to follow Continental's plan to increase some fares.
   Continental's new lower fares for children are immediately
available for purchase through May 26 for flights taken June 1
through Sept. 10. The new fares are available on all domestic
mainland Continental and Continental Express flights, and the $1
fares are good for travel on Tuesdays and Wednesdays.
   During the remainder of the week, children receive a 50 percent
reduction off Continental's so-called MaxSaver discount fares.
   For example, a family of four traveling on a Tuesday or
Wednesday between Newark, N.J., and Los Angeles would pay $718 now
for off-peak MaxSaver tickets, compared with $1,592 for tickets
purchased after May 26.
   Continental also said that families may change their
reservations once during the summer without any penalty if the
destination remains the same and the appropriate discount seats are
available.
   The new fares can be purchased for children ages 2 to 17, when
traveling with an adult who has purchased a MaxSaver ticket. A
family with two adults and four children would purchase three adult
MaxSaver tickets and three children's tickets if one child is 12
years or older.
   Continental said seats are limited and the new fares are
non-refundable.
   On April 13, Continental announced it would raise some of its
summer fares. The increases range up to $20 one way, depending on
the destination, and do not apply to first-class or full-fare coach
tickets.
   Continental is a subsidiary of Texas Air Corp., one of the
nation's largest airline companies. Its sister carrier, Miami-based
Eastern Airlines, was hit by a strike starting March 4 and filed
for bankruptcy protection on March 9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
