<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Close Sharply Lower On Midwestern Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices closed sharply
lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade following heavy weekend
showers in one of the driest sections of the Corn Belt.
   Oats also closed with sharp losses but wheat futures gained
slightly on continued dry weather in the Great Plains.
   A weather system triggered severe thunderstorms in western
Illinois and eastern Iowa over the weekend but brought little
relief to the rest of the Midwest, where corn planting has begun
and soybean growers are preparing to plant.
   ``The coverage was probably less than 20 to 25 percent of each
state, but it was enough to create a negative atmosphere this
morning'' in the grain markets, said Mickey Luth, a soybean analyst
in Chicago with Shearson Lehmann Hutton Inc.
   The losses in the corn and soybean markets more than offset
Friday's steep gains.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 1} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.16 a bushel; corn was 6 cents to
7{ cents lower with May at $2.69\ a bushel; oats were 6 cents to 6{
cents lower with May at $1.96\ a bushel; soybeans were 11{ cents to
18 cents lower with May at $7.43 a bushel.
