<FIRST>r f AM-Amex-SoAfrica     04-24 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amex-SoAfrica,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders Reject South Africa Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co.'s shareholders voted
overwhelmingly Monday against a proposal to sever all remaining
ties between the financial giant and racially segregated South
Africa.
   American Express closed its South African offices in 1975 and
sold its loan portfolio there last year, but the company continues
to issue its charge cards and travelers checks through a bank in
that country.
   Eleven percent of the shares were voted in favor of the proposal
to cut ties with South Africa.
   Chairman James D. Robinson III said that while his company
objects to South Africa's apartheid policies, it feels obligated to
provide travel-related services and assistance to its customers
wordlwide.
   American Express has 32 million cardholders worldwide. The
company does not provide a breakdown by country.
   The South African proposal was made by the College Retirement
Equities Fund, which holds 2.4 million of American Express' 417.42
million common shares outstanding.
</TEXT>
