<DOCNO> AP890424-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SteelSharing     04-24 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Sharing,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Foreign Steelmakers Swap Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign and U.S. steelmakers share technology
and investment routinely these days as a fact of life in competing
for business in the global economy, two steel industry leaders said
Monday.
   ``We don't have a monopoly on steel in the U.S.A.,'' said
Vincent J. Pongia, president of the Association of Iron and Steel
Engineers, as the association's three-day spring conference began
Monday.
   ``It's a global economy today, particularly in the steel
market,'' said Herschel B. Poole, the association's managing
director and a former executive of USX Corp.
   The foreign influence in steelmaking is obvious at the
Cincinnati conference, which is attracting an estimated 1,000 steel
industry executives and engineers for two days of technical
presentations. The conference ends Wednesday with a tour of Armco
Inc.'s Middletown Works steel mill.
   Steel industry leaders from 10 industrialized nations are making
presentations at the conference on new steel production technology,
including automated controls and other new equipment. The total
includes 47 presentations by U.S. steel industry leaders and 10 by
Japanese leaders, six from Canada, five from the United Kingdom and
four from West Germany.
   Pongia said the association functions as a means by which
engineers from U.S. and foreign companies can exchange information
about technologies and any drawbacks.
   ``Engineers talk to one another, and very frankly. They won't
give away proprietary information,'' said Pongia, who has
experience as a steel industry engineer and as manager of
operations and maintenance functions.
   Shared investment between U.S. and foreign steelmakers in new
plants has become more widespread because of the enormous costs,
conference spokesman Russ Robinson said. A new continuous-casting
plant alone _ just part of a larger steel mill _ could cost $150
million, he said.
   Nucor Corp. of Charlotte, N.C., is building an innovative mill
in Crawfordsville, Ind., designed to roll thinner strips of steel
and move hot steel more quickly from casters to rolling equipment,
thus saving energy costs and production time.
   Pongia said the steel industry will be watching closely to see
whether the process is successful. The concept is based on
technology used in West Germany.
   Pongia is vice president of CitiSteel USA Inc., a Chinese-owned
company which renovated and reopened a 250-employee steel mill in
Claymont, Del. The owners purchased the company within the last
year.
   The Armco mill that will be toured is preparing to take
advantage of Japanese steel technology. Armco announced on March 27
that its Middletown-based Eastern Steel Division and Japan's
Kawasaki Steel Corp. signed an agreement under which Kawasaki will
buy a 40 percent share of the division for $350 million.
   Armco plans to ask its shareholders to approve the joint venture
at the company's annual meeting Friday in Whippany, N.J.
   Pongia said the steel industry has increased its spending on new
plants and expansion as the industry's financial comeback has
progressed from years of heavy losses in the early 1980s.
   The U.S. steel industry posted a collective $2.4 billion profit
last year and is increasing spending in capital improvement
projects this year to $2.3 billion, up by 28 percent from last
year, Pongia said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890424-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-InsuranceTaxes     04-24 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insurance Taxes,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax Law Boosted Payments by Property, Casualty Insurance Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1986 tax overhaul added $1.7 billion a
year to the income taxes of U.S. property and casualty insurance
companies, an industry survey indicated Monday.
   For 1987, the new law boosted the tax bills of the
property-casualty companies to $3.5 billion, according to the Price
Waterhouse accounting firm. That included $92 million in
alternative minimum tax, a special levy designed to ensure that all
corporations with a profit pay some tax regardless of their
deductions.
   The companies' rising taxes were traced to three provisions in
the 1986 law that were aimed specifically at property-casualty
companies: loss reserve discounting, unearned-premium offset, and a
proration adjustment.
   The Price Waterhouse survey, released by Insurance Industry
Services, suggested the new law in the long run will mean an even
larger increase in property-casualty taxes, since operating losses
were used to offset a share of the companies' taxable income in
1987.
   The changes in the law raised the companies' taxable income by
$9.5 billion in 1987.
   The conclusions were based on a survey of insurance companies
that accounted for 79 percent of property-casualty premiums in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
