<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Broker     04-24 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Broker,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salomon Inc. Reports First-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salomon Inc. said Monday it lost $28 million in
the first three months of the year, with profits in the company's
energy division partially compensating for $150 million in losses
by the company's securities and commodities arms.
   The loss was the latest in a series of gloomy financial reports
by Wall Street firms attributed to a sluggish securities business.
   Salomon, the parent of Salomon Brothers Inc., said the losses
compared to net income of $173 million, or $1.19 per share, in the
same period last year. Revenue declined 4.3 percent to $1.54
billion from $1.61 billion.
   The company reported a $95 million pre-tax loss by Salomon
Brothers and a $55 million loss by Philipp Brothers Inc., its
commodities brokerage arm. Those compared with earnings of $253
million by Salomon Brothers and $15 million by Philipp Brothers in
the 1988 first quarter.
   ``During periods of high market volatility, thr company's
trading operations often show wide swings _ sometimes favorable and
sometimes adverse,'' Salomon said in a statement. ``The first
quarter was one of those periods.''
   Salomon said its energy division, Phibro Energy, made $98
million before taxes, more than 2{ times as much as in the same
period last year, boosted by oil price increases and added refining
capacity.
   The firm said a $72 million pre-tax loss was reduced by a $44
million income tax benefit.
