<HEAD>Posts Earnings Rise in 1st-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. said Monday its
first-quarter earnings rose 17.8 percent as its interest income
soared even as revenue tumbled 13 percent from a strong period a
year ago.
   Overall, the company said it earned $82.8 million, or $4.59 a
share, in the first quarter compared with $70.3 million, or $4.16 a
share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue fell to $1.12 billion from $1.29 billion a
year earlier when ABC telecast the 1988 Super Bowl game and the
Winter Olympics.
   The latest results included interest income of $25.5 million, up
six times from interest income of $3.9 million a year earlier.
   The company said its operating income slipped 2 percent to
$163.8 million as its operating profit from broadcasting operations
slipped while income from publishing operations held steady.
   Nonetheless, the company said its ABC Television Network had a
modest profit in the first quarter in contrast with a significant
loss in 1988. It did not provide specific figures for either period.
   Previously, CBS said its network was profitable in the first
quarter and industry analysts estimate that General Electric Co.'s
NBC Television Network was profitable for the first three months of
1989. GE does not usually report specific figures for NBC.
   Peter Appert, media analyst for C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell
Inc., said the three major networks appear to be benefiting from a
strengthening in the advertising marketplace and their own previous
cost-cutting efforts.
   Capital Cities-ABC said the ad marketplace for both its network
and its TV stations as well as at ESPN, the cable network in which
it owns controlling interest ad marketplace, had improved.
   In addition to the ABC Television Network, Capital Cities-ABC
operates eight television stations, six radio networks and 21 radio
stations. It is a cable TV programmer and publishes newspaper,
shopping guides, business periodicals and books.
