<HEAD>Ahmanson Up 34 Percent; CalFed Down More Than 50 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent company of Home Savings of
America, the nation's largest savings and loan, reported Monday
that its first-quarter earnings rose 34 percent, while CalFed Inc.
reported a 50.8 percent drop.
   Home's parent, H.F. Ahmanson &amp; Co., deals almost entirely in
adjustable-rate mortgages on single-family homes.
   CalFed, the nation's fourth-largest thrift holding company and
parent of California Federal Savings and Loan, is increasing the
share of its home loans that have adjustable rates.
   H.F. Ahmanson &amp; Co. said first-quarter earnings rose to $39.2
million, or 40 cents per share, up from $29.2 million, or 30 cents
a share, from the first quarter of 1988, when Ahmanson had reported
a 66 percent profit drop due to a decline in earnings from sales of
mortgage-backed securities.
   Earning assets for the first quarter of this year grew by more
than 5 percent during the quarter to a record $38.7 billion on
March 31, up 11 percent from $3.9 billion one year ago.
   Ahmanson officials last month denied the influx was mostly due
to a switchover of funds from Gibraltar Savings and Loan, seized by
the federal government.
   California Federal Savings reported 1989 first-quarter net
earnings of $17.5 million, or 67 cents a share, compared to $34.4
million, or $1.27 a share for the first quarter of 1988.
   CalFed's deposit base increased 6.5 percent from $10.7 billion
at the end of March 1988 to $11.4 billion on the quarter just ended.
   CalFed Inc.'s assets totaled $28.3 billion at the end of March,
compared to $27.6 billion at the end of 1988.
