<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Exxon-Rawl     04-24 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-Rawl,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Chief: 10 Years From Now You'll See `Nothing' of Valdez Oil
Goo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp.'s chief executive predicts that
remnants of the Valdez oil slick will vanish within 10 years
because of cleanup efforts, a comeback by Mother Nature and
evaporation of the leftover sludge.
   In an interview in the May 8 edition of Fortune Magazine, which
went on sale on most newsstands Monday, Lawrence Rawl also says the
largest U.S. oil company could have controlled up to half the spill
ifit had received approval from Coast Guard and Alaskan authorities
to dump chemical dispersants by air.
   Rawl also rejected criticism of Exxon's behavior and his lack of
public visibility in the days after one of its tankers crashed into
an underwater reef off the Alaskan coast March 24, spewing more
than 240,000 barrels of oil into Prince William Sound, the worst
spill in U.S. history.
   ``You're damned if you do and damned if you don't,'' Rawl said
in the interview. ``I concluded that we were going to be up to our
butts in alligators right here.''
   Exxon has said it will clean up the mess, which has devastated
the area around Valdez and led to congressional calls for tighter
regulatory control over oil company access to the huge reserves in
the nation's largest state.
   Rawl declined to predict how long the cleanup would take or what
it would cost the company, but he told the magazine he's seen other
larger spill cleanups that have been ``relatively inexpensive
because the environment has just come right back.''
   Asked what reporters will find if they return to Valdez in 10
years, Rawl said: ``Nothing. I would think they can return to
Valdez a lot sooner than 10 years from now. I don't think they will
find much in terms of environmental damage.''
   Rawl said one reason he was optimistic about the cleanup is
``we're going to put a hell of an effort on it.''
   He also said ``oil evaporates and it oxidizes. We can pick a lot
of it up. It is surprising, but in World War II we lost 16 times
more oil off the East Coast of the U.S. in the early months of 1942
when your tankers were torpedoed, and there was no permanent damage
to the shoreline.''
   Rawl said Exxon had been ready to dump chemical dispersants on
the spewing oil shortly after the accident, but ``the basic problem
we ran into was that we had environmentalists advising the Alaskan
Department of Environmental Conservation that the dispersant could
be toxic.''
   He said the consequent delay to load planes full of the
dispersant to dump on the oil was one of the main reasons the
public perceived the oil giant as acting slowly and irresponsibly.
   ``When you get 240,000 barrels of oil on the water, you cannot
get it all up,'' Rawl said. ``But we could have kep
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   t up to 50
percent of the oil from ending up on the beach somewhere.''
</TEXT>
