<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     04-24 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain In Corn Belt Triggers Plunge In Corn, Soybean Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Weekend showers in one of the driest parts of the Corn Belt
triggered a steep sell-off of corn and soybean futures Monday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, more than offsetting the sharp gains of
the previous session.
   Oats also closed lower but wheat futures gained slightly on
continued dry weather in Kansas.
   On other markets, energy futures plunged; precious metals
advanced; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Wheat settled { cent lower to 2{ cents higher with the contract
for delivery in May at $4.15} a bushel; corn was 6\ cents to 7{
cents lower with May at $2.69 a bushel; oats were 6\ cents to 6}
cents lower with May at $1.96\ a bushel; soybeans were 11{ cents to
17{ cents lower with May at $7.44{ a bushel.
   Severe thunderstorms occurred in western Illinois and eastern
Iowa over the weekend but brought little relief to the rest of the
Midwest, where corn planting has begun and soybean growers are
preparing to plant.
   ``The coverage was probably less than 20 to 25 percent of each
state, but it was enough to create a negative atmosphere this
morning'' in the grain markets, said Mickey Luth, a soybean analyst
in Chicago with Shearson Lehmann Hutton Inc.
   In a six-to-10-day forecast issued after the close, the National
Weather Service predicted normal temperatures and normal ainfall in
the Midwest early next week. The weather service called for
continued above-normal temperatures in the Great Plains,
threatening further deterioration of the drought-stressed Kansas
wheat crop.
   Corn and soybean prices also were pressured Monday by heavy
farmer selling of old-crop supplies over the weekend following last
week's rally. May soybeans had surged 12{ cents a bushel on Friday
and corn had gained 2{ cents to 5{ cents.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, most unleaded gasoline and
heating-oil contracts finished down the permitted daily limit of 2
cents a gallon amid disappointment over an Environmental Protection
Agency decision delaying the expected date of Massachusetts' switch
to a less-polluting gasoline standard.
   The lower-pollution gasoline is more expensive to produce.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 54 cents to 79 cents
lower with June at $20.61 a barrel; heating oil was 1.82 cents to 2
cents lower with May at 51.81 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
1.93 cents to 2 cents lower with May at 72.23 cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures posted strong gains on New York's
Commodity Exchange on buying partly inspired by the gold market's
resistance to selling below about $383 a troy ounce for spot
delivery.
   ``No matter what they tried, they weren't able to get it lower,
so they had to turn it around at some point and take the path of
less resistance _ take it higher,'' said Richard Levine, vice
president of the precious metals and foreign exchange group at
Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   Gold settled $2.80 to $2.90 higher with June at $391 a troy
ounce; silver was 6.8 cents to 8.4 cents higher with May at $5.833
a troy ounce.
   Cattle futures ended mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
with selling inspired by expectations for increasing supplies of
slaughter-ready cattle into the summer. Those perceptions were
bolstered by Friday's Agriculture Department quarterly
cattle-on-feed report, which showed 3 percent more cattle being
fattened for slaughter as of April 1 than on the same date a year
earlier.
   Strong cash markets boosted near-month pork futures but prices
for deferred delivery slipped on expectations of greater supplies
in the months ahead.
   Live cattle settled .65 cent lower to .20 cent higher with June
at 70.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .27 cent lower to .08
cent higher with May at 76.20 cents a pound; live hogs were .13
cent lower to .18 cent higher with June at 45.67 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .17 cent lower to .23 cent higher with May
at 31.45 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
