<DOCNO> AP890424-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Navy-AirForceFighter     04-24 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy-Air Force Fighter,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighter Use To Be Studied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force said Monday it had awarded
contracts to two competing teams of companies to determine how a
new jet fighter they are designing can be modified for use by the
Navy as well.
   The two contracts, each worth $50 million and awarded by the Air
Force on behalf of the Navy, are part of a previously announced
cooperation program between the two services in which the Air Force
is developing a new jet fighter and the Navy is developing a new
ground-attack jet for the 21st century.
   Under the 1986 cooperation program, the Air Force's so-called
Advanced Tactical Fighter is to be used by the Navy's aircraft
carriers as a replacement for the F-14 Tomcat, and the Navy's
Advanced Tactical Aircraft is to be used by Air Force tactical
bombing squadrons.
   The two teams competing on the Advanced Tactical Fighter include
Lockheed Corp. and General Dynamics Corp., and Northrop Corp. and
McDonnell Douglas Corp. One of those teams is to be selected in
1991 to build the plane.
   The contracts awarded Monday are designed to allow the Air Force
contractors ``to identify the changes which are necessary to meet
the Navy's unique (aircraft) carrier suitability and mission
requirements ...''
   ``Some of the changes required to make the Navy variant
carrier-suitable include adding a wing fold, strengthening the
landing gear, adding a nose tow and arresting hook and a high-lift
system to make approach speed and attitude compatible with carrier
launches and landings ...,'' the Air Force added.
   While the Air Force was responsible for awarding the contracts,
the Navy said Monday it was funding the work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
