<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Unocal     04-24 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Unocal,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unocal Profit Drops 48 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unocal Corp. posted a 48 percent decline in
first-quarter profit, due mainly to accounting changes that
produced unusual gains in 1988's first quarter.
   Unocal also announced the election of Richard J. Stegemeier to
chairman of the board. Stegemeier, 61, also was re-elected
president and chief executive officer.
   For the first three months of 1989, Unocal's after-tax profit
totaled $87 million, or 75 cents a share, compared with $178
million, or $1.53 a share, in the 1988 first quarter.
   Revenue totaled $2.64 billion, up 14 percent from $2.32 billion
in the year-ago period.
   The Los Angeles-based oil company said its 1988 first-quarter
results included a $456 million cumulative gain from a change in
accounting procedures, which were partly offset by after-tax
charges of $322 million for write-downs.
   Without adjustments, first-quarter 1988 earnings were $44
million, or 38 cents per share, Unocal said.
   Stegemeier succeeds Fred L. Harley, 72, who announced his
retirement last June.
   Stegemeier said that rising crude oil prices helped boost
Unocal's exploration and production earnings, but they were
partially offset by lower net income in the company's refining and
marketing business.
   Capital expenditures for the quarter were $202 million, up from
$189 million for the first quarter of 1988, Unocal said.
   As of March 31, Unocal had reduced its debt to $4.33 billion,
down $275 million from the end of 1988. The company said it has now
paid down $1.8 billion since October 1985, when it incurred the
huge debt trying to evade a takeover attempt by T. Boone Pickens Jr.
</TEXT>
