<HEAD>Boeing Reports 18.4 Percent Earnings Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. posted an 18.4 percent earnings gain
and broke $4 billion in sales in the first quarter, management told
shareholders Monday at the company's annual meeting.
   Boeing predicted record sales for 1989 and defended its lagging
military business as it announced an increase in its dividend and a
3-for-2 stock split.
   Boeing's earnings rose to $161 million, or $1.05 a share, from
$136 million, or 89 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 9.9
percent to $4.001 billion from $3.64 billion.
   Chairman and chief executive officer Frank Shrontz told a full
house of
   A 45-cents-per-share cash dividend, 5 cents higher than last
year's dividend, will be payable June 9 to shareholders of record
on May 12, 1989.
   After the stock split, which will also take effect June 9 for
the same stockholders, the dividend per share will be 30 cents.
   ``I am convinced we are headed to a great corporate year in
1989,'' Frank Shrontz, the chairman and chief executive, told
shareholders.
   The company attributed the increase in first-quarter earnings to
higher sales volume and a reduction in research and development and
other expenses in commercial aircraft and computing.
   Shrontz said ``concern about aging aircraft is bound to be a
significant factor'' in the company's improved jet sales prospects
for this year.
   Boeing predicts overall sales of $22 billion for 1989, company
spokesman Tom Cole said.
   The company's firm backlog of orders, which totaled $59.3
billion as of March 1, 88 percent of it for commercial aircraft,
led the company to increase production rates of its 737, 747, 757
and 767 programs, Shrontz said. Firm backlogs at year-end 1988 were
$53.6 billion.
   Boeing's record year for profits was 1986, with $665 million on
sales of $16.3 billion. Last year, profits were $614 million.
   Boeing last declared a stock split in 1985, when the price hit
$68.75. Last year, Boeing increased the dividend per share to 40
cents, from 35 cents in 1987.
