<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSalesOutlook     04-24 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales Outlook,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Year-To-Year Comparison Closer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Each passing day of spring is giving automakers a
better picture of how the rest of their year is shaping up, and
there's speculation that it may not look as good as they'd planned.
   Mid-April sales figures by the eight U.S. automakers are due
Tuesday, and the industry has been looking for rebounding numbers.
   It is the first 10-day sales reporting period to feel the full
impact of incentive programs announced in late March and early
April by General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
   March and April normally herald the spring car-buying season,
but sales this past March were lower than expected. Automakers
responded with a number of new incentives, hoping to make customers
deals they couldn't refuse.
   Those hopes haven't necessarily become reality.
   Car and light truck sales during the first 10 days of April
appeared strong on paper, rising 28.3 percent over the same period
last year. Ford led the charge, boosting sales of its domestically
made cars by 47 percent. But those figures compared with
year-earlier numbers weakened when incentives expired at the end of
March 1988.
   Sales had rebounded by mid-April last year, meaning a
year-to-year comparison on Tuesday will be more valid.
   ``You're comparing it with a fairly strong period last year,''
analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. said Monday.
   ``I guess you'd say they (incentives) are working but not as
well as they used to,'' he said. ``If that's so, mid-April sales
were better than the March rate, but not as good as early April.''
   Analyst Douglas Laughlin of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. of New York
agreed that April sales were critical for the industry.
   ``I'm holding my breath a little on this one,'' he said, adding
that he was watching interest rates particularly closely.
   ``If interest rates start to trend down, I think that would
alleviate some of the concern (among automakers) about the impact
of this particular (incentive) program, '' he said. ``It would
suggest that things will be easier in the next few months.
   ``If interest rates hang up here,'' Laughlin said, ``it may be a
source of concern for the industry.''
   One of the first places any industry concern would be noted is
in the companies' production schedules. GM, Ford and Chrysler held
to ambitious production levels through the first quarter of this
year, leading some analysts to speculate that production rates
would have to be changed later this year, especially at
model-changeover time in the third quarter.
   Ward's Automotive Reports, a weekly industry newsletter, said in
Monday editions that GM had cut its production schedule
significantly for June, July and August.
</TEXT>
