<FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UMW-Pittston     04-24 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMW-Pittston,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>200 Striking Miners Arrested; Some Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLINTWOOD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested at least 200 United Mine
Workers members Monday for blocking roads and mine entrances as the
union expanded its violence-marred strike against The Pittston Coal
Group.
   Although state police reported no violence, a local hospital
treated seven miners who said they were injured while being
arrested.
   The sitdown strike, which blocked traffic on state and county
roads in Dickenson County, led to a spontaneous parade in
Clintwood, with union supporters jamming the streets and courthouse
steps.
   ``They're not going to run these mines with scabs, and they're
not going to run these mines without us,'' said Marty Hudson, the
executive assistant to UMW Vice President Cecil Roberts.
   The UMW on Monday expanded its strike against Pittston to
temporarily include Westmoreland Coal Co., which it accused of
plotting to provide Pittston with 200,000 to 300,000 tons of coal
to fulfill contracts. Westmoreland has denied that charge.
   The 1,400 Pittston employees who have been on strike since April
5 in Virginia were joined on the picket lines at 12:01 a.m. Monday
by about 750 Westmoreland employees who are taking off three of the
10 ``memorial days'' _ or personal days _ allowed by their contract.
   UMW District 28 President Jackie Stump said union President
Richard Trumka called the three-day work stoppage at Westmoreland's
mines in the western tip of Virginia.
   ``Each and every company is going to be looked at whether or not
they're filling Pittston's orders,'' Stump said. ``If they are, we
consider it to be a conspiracy to break the union.''
   The Pittston employees in Virginia and 300 in West Virginia went
on strike April 5, accusing the company of unfair practices during
contract talks. The miners had been working without a contract
since February 1988.
   Hudson said about 300 miners Monday blocked the entrance to the
McClure mine in Dickenson County and about 200 blocked access to
the Lambert Fork mine in Russell County.
   About 800 to 1,000 blocked all three entrances to the Moss No. 3
coal preparation plant in Russell County.
   ``We're going to let our rear ends touch the asphalt and we're
not going to move,'' Hudson said. ``We're going to let the county
feed us a while.''
   Many strikers, preparing for their inevitable arrests, rid
themselves of all forms of identification to make it more difficult
for police to process them.
   At 6 a.m., state police began arresting union members who
blocked roads in Freemont and Clinchfield. The strikers were
charged with obstructing free passage, a misdemeanor, said Lt. J.D.
Willis of the Virginia State Police in Wytheville.
   Most were released on their own recognizance, but at least 24
had been jailed in the Dickenson County Jail, according to Sheriff
Avery Phipps.
   ``We don't know if there were actually any injuries,'' said
Trooper B.I Sparks of the Virginia State Police. ``There were some
complaints of injuries.''
   Doctors at the Dickenson County Medical Center in Clintwood
treated and released six miners with lacerations and bruises. A
seventh, suffering from blurred vision, was held.
   After miners blocked off two Virginia roads, state police
blocked off all roads into the areas in which the arrests were made
and turned back reporters.
   By late afternoon, while arrested miners were being processed in
the Duckenson County Courthouse, a spontaneous parade erupted in
the streets of Clintwood. Streets were jammed with cars festooned
with homemade signs of support for miners.
   Pittston Coal Group President Michael Odom and company
spokeswoman Susan Copeland did not immediately return phone calls
from The Associated Press on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
